3	1	A patient presents with acute blood loss following trauma. Which of the following is the most immediate compensatory response?	Decreased sympathetic tone	Increased ADH secretion	Increased renal plasma flow	Increased GFR	B	Acute blood loss -> ↓ blood volume/pressure -> baroreceptor activation -> ↑ ADH release to conserve water and maintain blood pressure; RPF and GFR actually decrease, not increase. Blood loss should lead to ↑ sympathetic flow, ↓ renal plasma flow & GFR.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
4	1	A clinician is assessing a patient for malnutrition. Standard nutritional charts primarily incorporate which parameters?	Weight loss and BMI	Height alone	Serum sodium levels	Blood pressure	A	Standard nutritional assessment mainly uses weight loss + BMI, as they best reflect current and chronic nutritional status (more reliable than electrolytes or height alone).	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
5	1	Which of the following is the primary role of neutrophils in innate immunity?	Antibody production	Phagocytosis and microbial killing	Antigen presentation	Cytokine-mediated signaling	B	Neutrophils are the first-line innate immune cells that rapidly phagocytose and destroy microbes using enzymes and ROS.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
6	1	A child presents with growth retardation and visual disturbances. Imaging reveals a suprasellar mass compressing the optic chiasm. What visual field defect is most likely?	Homonymous hemianopia	Bitemporal hemianopia	Central scotoma	Inferior quadrantanopia	B	Suprasellar mass compressing the optic chiasm -> loss of temporal visual fields in both eyes (bitemporal hemianopia) (FA pg 540) Recall that nonfunctional tumors present with mass effect (e.g., compression of the optic chiasm), and pituitary apoplexy leads to hypopituitarism. The growth retardation in this case is due to apoplexy affecting somatotrophs -> ↓ GH -> growth retardation. Functional tumors, in contrast, secrete hormones in excess, leading to conditions such as acromegaly/gigantism.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
7	1	30-year-old man is found to have bilaterally enlarged kidneys with multiple cysts on ultrasound. His father had similar disease. What is the pattern of inheritance?	Autosomal recessive	Autosomal dominant	X-linked recessive	Mitochondrial	B		\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
8	1	A patient sustains trauma to the right side of the neck. On imaging, the right hemidiaphragm is elevated during respiration. What is the most likely cause?	Lesion of phrenic nerve	Hemothorax	Pneumothorax	Vagus nerve injury	A	The phrenic nerve (C3-C5) supplies the diaphragm; injury (often from neck trauma) -> ipsilateral hemidiaphragm on x-ray (elevated hemidiaphragm on inspiration) (FA pg 681).	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
9	1	12-year-old girl is brought by her mother due to absence of menstruation. On examination, she has clitoral enlargement and ambiguous genitalia. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH)	17α-hydroxylase deficiency	Turner syndrome	Androgen insensitivity syndrome	A	Classic CAH (21-hydroxylase deficiency) is the most common CAH. It leads to 1) ↓ aldosterone -> salt wasting, hyperkalemia 2) ↑ Sex hormones (androgens) -> in FEMALES: virilization (clitoromegaly, ambiguous genitalia) & primary amenorrhea. In 17α-hydroxylase deficiency: 1) ↑ Aldosterone -> HTN & hypokalemia 2) ↓ Sex hormones -> in FEMALES: lack of secondary sexual characteristics (FA 339).	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
10	1	Which of the following best explains the rapid conduction of impulses in Purkinje fibers?	Increased fiber diameter	Increased number of gap junctions	Increased sodium permeability	Increased calcium influx	B	Purkinje Fibers have highest speed of conduction due to -Wide diameter > large no of gap junctions > large no of sodium Channel >Less no of myofibril > Short refractory period Speed of conduction: -Purkinje fibers > Bundle of His > Atria > Ventricles > SA node > AV node Speed of Rate -SA Node > AV Node > Purkinji fibers.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
11	1	What is required for muscle contraction?	Tropomyosin	Irritant	Stretch	J receptor	C		\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
12	1	A 27-year-old woman with regular 28-day menstrual cycles presents for evaluation of fertility. The clinician wants to confirm whether ovulation is occurring. Which of the following is the most reliable test in this patient?	Serum estrogen level on day 21	Serum progesterone level on day 21	Serum LH level on day 21	Serum FSH level on day 3	B	Mid-luteal phase serum progesterone (day 21 in a 28-day cycle) is the most reliable marker of ovulation, as it reflects corpus luteum activity after ovulation.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
13	1	Woman with a history of severe postpartum hemorrhage years ago presents with hypotension (BP 80/50 mmHg), hyponatremia, and features of adrenal insufficiency. She also has a history of depression and failure to lactate after delivery. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Addisonian crisis	Pituitary apoplexy	Sheehan syndrome	Cushing syndrome	C	Severe postpartum hemorrhage -> ischemic infarct of anterior pituitary (Sheehan syndrome) leading to loss of secretion of Anterior Pituitary hormones: pregnancy-induced pituitary growth -> ↑ susceptibility to hypoperfusion. Usually presents with failure to lactate (↓ prolactin), adrenal insufficiency (↓ ACTH) etc (FA 343) Remember Pituitary apoplexy has sudden hemorrhage.	\N	2026-07-11 03:23:27.439165	\N
25	1	A patient with rheumatoid arthritis is started on methotrexate (MTX). Which of the following best explains its mechanism of action?	Inhibition of thymidylate synthase	Inhibition of dihydrofolate reductase	Inhibition of DNA topoisomerase II	Alkylation of DNA	B	Folic acid analog that competitively inhibits dihydrofolate reductase. Myelosuppression (reversible with leucovorin "rescue"). Remember it causes pulmonary fibrosis.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
26	1	Which of the following best defines proto-oncogenes?	Genes that inhibit tumor growth	Genes responsible for apoptosis	Normal cellular genes that can become oncogenic after mutation	Genes involved in DNA repair	C	Proto-oncogenes: Normal genes that promote cell growth -> when mutated/overexpressed, they become oncogenes that cause uncontrolled cell proliferation.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
27	1	A patient presents with recurrent abscess formation. The causative organism is catalase-positive. Which organism is most likely?	Streptococcus pyogenes	Staphylococcus aureus	Enterococcus faecalis	Clostridium perfringens	B	Chronic granulomatous disease: X-linked form most common. Defect of NADPH oxidase in NEUTROPHILS. INC susceptibility to catalase +ve organisms.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
28	1	A patient with cavernous sinus thrombosis presents with ophthalmoplegia and reduced corneal sensation. Which cranial nerve is most likely affected earliest?	Optic nerve (CN II)	Oculomotor nerve (CN III)	Ophthalmic division of trigeminal nerve (CN V1)	Facial nerve (CN VII)	C	Corneal reflex: afferent CN V1 (nasociliary branch); efferent CN VII (temporal and zygomatic branches orbicularis oculi) (PA pg 519). Cavernous sinus thrombosis: proposes involvement of CNs III, IV, V1 V2, VI plus postganglionic sympathetic pupillary fibers enroute to orbit. As CN VII does not pass through CN VII so the correct answer will be CN V1.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
29	1	A young adult presents with diplopia. Examination reveals impaired adduction of the right eye and nystagmus of the left eye on abduction. The lesion is located in:	Optic chiasm	Oculomotor nerve	Medial longitudinal fasciculus	Cerebellar peduncle	C	Medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF): Internuclear ophthalmoplegia: ipsilateral eye fails to adduct (impaired adduction given in the Qs stem) + nystagmus of contralateral eye with abduction). Seen in multiple sclerosis (so it should be Right MLP).	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
30	1	A patient is unable to identify objects placed in his hand with eyes closed despite intact primary sensations. The lesion is most likely located in:	Spinothalamic tract	Dorsal column	Superior parietal lobule	Primary motor cortex	C	Lesion of Superior parietal lobe -> astereognosis (unable to judge shapes or forms of objects), due to impaired cortical processing.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
31	1	A neonate presents with enlarged echogenic kidneys and hepatic fibrosis. Family history suggests a recessive inheritance pattern. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Autosomal dominant PKD	Autosomal recessive PKD	Multicystic dysplastic kidney	Wilms tumor	B	ARPKD is autosomal recessive. Recall if similar condition presents in adults, it is called ADPKD (Adult).	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
32	1	Two asymptomatic parents are carriers of an autosomal recessive disorder. What is the probability that their child will be affected?	25%	50%	75%	100%	A	Autosomal recessive: both parents are carriers (Aa x Aa) -> 1 out of 4 (25%) offspring will be affected (aa) (please practice 2*2 pedigree table).	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
33	1	A patient with atrial fibrillation is started on apixaban. What is its primary mechanism?	Direct thrombin inhibition	Factor Xa inhibition	Vitamin K antagonism	Platelet glycoprotein inhibition	B	Apixaban is a direct inhibitor (ban) of factor Xa. Remember all Xa inhibitors have xa in their name Apixaban, edoxaban, rivaroxaban (FA Hematology).	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
34	1	A patient on long-term metformin therapy develops peripheral neuropathy and macrocytic anemia. Which deficiency is most likely?	Iron	Vitamin B12	Folate	Vitamin B6	B	Metformin can cause Vit B12 deficiency -> megaloblastic anemia, peripheral neuropathy. HY point: DM itself also causes peripheral neuropathy but it does lead to megaloblastic anemia. Remember PPIs also cause vit b12 deficiency.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
35	1	A patient develops flank pain and reduced urine output 24 hours after hysterectomy. Ureteric injury is suspected. Which structure is most commonly involved during surgery?	Ovarian ligament	Round ligament	Uterine artery	Infundibulopelvic ligament	C	The most important single practical relationship in this region is that of the ureter to the supravaginal cervix. At this point, the ureter lies just above the level of the lateral fornix, below the uterine vessels as these pass across within the broad ligament. In performing a hysterectomy, the ureter may be accidentally divided in clamping the uterine vessels, especially when the pelvic anatomy has been distorted by a previous operation, a mass of fibroids, infection or malignant infiltration.	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
36	1	A patient presents with non-fluent, effortful speech but preserved comprehension. The lesion is located in:	Superior temporal gyrus	Inferior frontal gyrus	Angular gyrus	Occipital cortex	B	Broca aphasia (expressive): Non-fluent, effortful speech with intact comprehension. Remember Wernicke aphasia (receptive): fluent but meaningless speech with poor comprehension due to lesion in the posterior superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke's area).	2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
37	1	A patient presents with acute unilateral ureteric obstruction. What change is expected in GFR and filtration fraction (FF)?	↑ GFR, ↑ FF	↓ GFR, ↑ FF	↑ GFR, ↓ FF	↓ GFR, ↓ FF	D		2	2026-07-12 00:28:23.875603	\N
