50	2	EEG shows lambda waves when the patient alternates between eye opening and closing while awake. This finding is associated with:	Seizure activity	Sleep stage	Normal alert wakefulness	Coma	C	Normal alert wakefulness -> Lambda waves = normal visual cortex activity seen with eye opening/closing while awake. Lambda waves -> positive, triangular-shaped, occipital waves; seen bilaterally during eye opening and visual fixation in awake state. Awake and Eye Close: Alpha Wave. Awake and Eye open: Beta Wave (Wave during algebra arithmetic means solving). N1: Theta Wave (4-7Hz). N2: Sleep spindles (12-14Hz) and K complexes (High Voltage biphasic waves). N3&4: Delta Wave (0.5-4Hz) – Low Frequency and High Voltage Wave.	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
51	2	A female patient with upper respiratory tract infection has viral symptoms. Her mother insists on antibiotics despite counselling that they are not required. What is the most appropriate principle guiding the doctor's decision?	Autonomy	Beneficence	Non-maleficence	Justice	C	Non-maleficence (do not harm): Not prescribing antibiotics in a viral URTI follows. Why no antibiotics? Because antibiotics have side effects, and unnecessary use can lead to antimicrobial resistance in the future. Right of the patient to make personal health care decisions (ie, autonomy) conflicts with acting in the best interest of the patient (ie, beneficence) and avoiding potentially harmful adverse effects (ie, non maleficence).	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
52	2	A patient develops sudden ankle pain after being prescribed ciprofloxacin for UTI. Most likely diagnosis?	Plantar fasciitis	Achilles tendon rupture	Osteoarthritis	Septic arthritis	B	It May cause tendonitis or tendon rupture in people > 60 years old and in patients taking prednisone. It also causes QT prolongation -> can lead to TDPointez. MOA: Inhibite prokaryotic enzymes topoisomerase II (DNA gyrase) and topoisomerase IV. Bactericidal.	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
53	2	An obese female with type 2 diabetes is prescribed a drug that decreases glucose absorption from the gut. Which drug is most likely?	Metformin	Acarbose	Glibenclamide	Insulin	B	Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors (Acarbose, miglitol): Inhibit intestinal brush-border alpha-glucosidases -> postprandial hyperglycemia.	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
54	2	A patient has chronic diarrhea, weight loss, and transmural inflammation of bowel. Diagnosis?	Ulcerative colitis	IBS	Crohn's disease	Celiac disease	C		4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
55	2	A 45-year-old woman presents with fatigue, pruritus, and elevated alkaline phosphatase. Autoimmune liver disease is suspected. Which antibody is most specific for confirming the diagnosis?	Anti-nuclear antibody (ANA)	Anti-mitochondrial antibody (AMA)	Anti-streptolysin O (ASO)	Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (ANCA)	B		4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
56	2	A young woman presents with episodic finger discoloration on exposure to cold, turning white then blue, associated with pain. Pharmacological treatment is planned. Which is the drug of choice?	Beta-blocker	Nifedipine	ACE inhibitor	Aspirin	B	Raynaud phenomenon. Remember if you are asked to pick one among many auto-immune conditions to ask for the underlying cause of Raynaud, pick Systemic sclerosis (Limited form: CREST; R=Raynaud).	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
57	2	A patient presents with a stab wound in the left 6th intercostal space near the midclavicular line. Which cardiac chamber is most likely injured?	Right atrium	Left ventricle	Right ventricle	Left atrium	B	The left ventricle forms the apex of the heart and can reach as far as the fifth intercostal space at the left midclavicular line (MCL). All other heart chambers, including the right ventricle, lie medial to the left MCL, and are unlikely to have been affected by the injury.	4	2026-07-12 00:29:11.351023	\N
