61	2	A young patient presents with palpitations. ECG shows a short PR interval and a wide QRS complex with delta waves. What is the diagnosis?	AV block	Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome	Atrial fibrillation	Ventricular tachycardia	B	WPW syndrome: accessory bundle of Kent bypasses AV node (which is normal pathway, has slow conduction) -> pre-excitation of ventricles -> short PR interval (delta wave) + wide QRS	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
62	2	A patient sustains a fracture and subsequently develops loss of sensation over the medial aspect of the forearm and hand. Which nerve is most likely injured?	Radial nerve	Median nerve	Ulnar nerve	Musculocutaneous nerve	C	Injury to the ulnar nerve causes sensory loss over the medial aspect of the forearm/hand	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
63	2	A newborn presents with the arm adducted, internally rotated, extended at the elbow, and pronated ("waiter's tip" posture). What is the diagnosis?	Klumpke palsy	Erb's palsy	Radial nerve palsy	Median nerve palsy	B	Infants: lateral traction on neck during delivery -> Traction or tear of upper trunk (C5-C6 roots) -> loss of Abduction (arm hangs by side); Lateral rotation (arm medially rotated); Flexion, supination (arm extended and pronated) -> in the affected arm being held in adduction and internal rotation with the forearm pronated and the wrist flexed (ie, waiter's tip posture)	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
119	3	In a normal menstrual cycle, which uterine phase corresponds to the mid-cycle (post-ovulatory period leading to implantation preparation)?	Secretory	Proliferative	Menstrual	Atrophic	A	Post-ovulation (progesterone) → secretory phase → endometrium ready for implantation	10	2026-07-12 00:31:29.834307	\N
64	2	An elderly patient presents with fever, cough, and consolidation on chest X-ray consistent with community-acquired pneumonia(CAP). What is the most common causative organism for this pneumonia(PNA)?	Staphylococcus aureus	Klebsiella pneumoniae	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Pseudomonas aeruginosa	C	Strep pneumo is associated with rusty sputum and is the most common cause of CAP. Cell wall inhibitors are preferred. Recall that Mycoplasma is a wall-less organism that causes bilateral interstitial PNA and is treated with protein synthesis inhibitors. Klebsiella pneumoniae causes aspiration pneumonia in alcohol use disorder patients, classically affecting the upper lobes and producing currant jelly sputum due to necrotizing, abscess-freeing infection. (UW QID 9989)	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
65	2	A patient diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis is started on standard DOTS therapy. How many drugs are included in the intensive phase?	1 drug	2 drugs	4 drugs	6 drugs	C		5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
66	2	A patient presents with salicylate poisoning. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial management to enhance drug excretion?	Urine acidification	Urine alkalinization	Hemodialysis only	Steroid therapy	B	Salicylates are weak acids. Alkalinizing the urine (e.g., with bicarbonate) ionizes the drug, preventing its reabsorption in renal tubules and enhancing excretion.	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
67	2	After ingestion of a glucose-rich meal, which hormonal change is expected?	Increased glucagon	Increased insulin	Both decreased	No significant change	B	After a glucose-rich meal, blood glucose rises -> stimulates pancreatic β-cells -> insulin increases, while glucagon is suppressed.	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
68	2	A patient on spironolactone develops hyperkalemia. What is the most appropriate next step in management?	Continue the drug	Stop the drug	Increase the dose	Add potassium supplements	B	Spironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic (act on cortical collecting tubule in distal part of the nephron), so it can cause hyperkalemia. The most appropriate step is to discontinue the drug to prevent worsening potassium levels.	5	2026-07-12 00:29:31.936483	\N
