72	2	A transplant recipient develops a condition in which donor immune cells attack host tissues, leading to skin rash and gastrointestinal symptoms. This reaction is classified as which type of hypersensitivity?	Type I	Type II	Type III	Type IV	D	Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD) is caused by donor T cells attacking host tissues, making it a Type IV (T-cell mediated delayed) hypersensitivity reaction. It most commonly occurs after allogeneic hematopoietic cell transplant. Patients affected by GVHD are generally severely immunodeficient due to the primary disease process or as a result of immunosuppressive medications. This allows immunocompetent donor T cells from the graft to survive and migrate into host tissues, where they recognize host MHC antigens as foreign and become sensitized. On activation, donor CD4+ and CD8+ T cells (not B cells) participate in host cell destruction. Features: Maculopapular rash, jaundice, diarrhea, hepatosplenomegaly	6	2026-07-12 00:29:56.843336	\N
73	2	A bee sting presented on OPD with facial swelling and developing difficulty in breathing. Doctor give IM adrenaline in order to prevent	Local Urticaria	Hypotension	Systemic anaphylaxis	Systemic infection	C		6	2026-07-12 00:29:56.843336	\N
74	2	A patient is taking Aspirin for cardiovascular protection. Which mediator does it primarily inhibit?	Thromboxane A2 (Tx A2)	ADP	Calcium	Fibrin	A	TxA3 promotes platelet aggregation, and low-dose aspirin inhibits it, leading to decreased platelet aggregation -> antithrombotic effect (increased bleeding tendency as a side effect).	6	2026-07-12 00:29:56.843336	\N
75	2	A patient is unable to abduct the arm above shoulder level and has difficulty combing hair. Which nerve is most likely injured?	Axillary nerve	Long thoracic nerve	Radial nerve	Median nerve	A	Injury in the posterior triangle of the neck (LN dissection/Breast surgery) -> Spinal accessory nerve (CN XI) injury causes trapezius paralysis -> scapular instability with shoulder droop and impaired overhead arm abduction (>100°) -> leading to difficulty in combing hair or placing dishes on a high shelf which require upward rotation and stabilization of the scapula. Injury to neck of humerus -> Axillary nerve injury causes deltoid weakness -> impaired arm abduction from 15-90° with loss of sensation over the lateral shoulder.	6	2026-07-12 00:29:56.843336	\N
76	2	A trauma patient presents after a road traffic accident with hypotension, respiratory distress, hyperresonant chest, and absent breath sounds on one side. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Hemothorax	Pneumothorax	Tension pneumothorax	Pleural effusion	C	Tension PTX: Tension pneumothorax = obstructive shock with unilateral absent breath sounds after trauma.	6	2026-07-12 00:29:56.843336	\N
77	3	A biopsy from damaged tissue shows irreversible cell injury. Which of the following microscopic findings confirms this?	Cell swelling	Fatty change	Nuclear pyknosis	Reversible edema	C	Irreversible cell injury: -Breakdown of plasma membrane -> cytosolic enzymes (eg, troponin) leak outside of cell, influx of Ca2+ -> activation of degradative enzymes -Mitochondrial damage/dysfunction -> loss of electron transport chain -> ↓ATP -Rupture of lysosomes -> autolysis -Nuclear degradation: pyknosis (nuclear condensation) -> karyorrhexis (nuclear fragmentation caused by endonuclease-mediated cleavage) -> karyolysis (nuclear dissolution) -Amorphous densities/inclusions in mitochondria	7	2026-07-12 00:30:17.191477	\N
