344	2	A 28-year-old patient presents with pupillary abnormalities following a midbrain lesion. The parasympathetic preganglionic fibers destined for the ciliary ganglion are affected. From which cranial nerve do these preganglionic fibers originate?	Oculomotor nerve (CN III)	Optic nerve (CN II)	Trochlear nerve (CN IV)	Trigeminal nerve (CN V)	A	This is related to the parasympathetic pathway of the eye. Ciliary ganglion receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the oculomotor nerve (CN III).\nPathway:\n• Edinger-Westphal nucleus → CN III → ciliary ganglion → short ciliary nerves\n• Function: pupil constriction (miosis) and accommodation	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
345	2	A 45-year-old patient undergoes a retrobulbar block for ocular surgery. Shortly after the procedure, the patient develops sudden bradycardia and hypotension. Which of the following reflexes is most likely responsible for this complication?	Cushing reflex	Oculocardiac reflex	Baroreceptor reflex	Bezold-Jarisch reflex	B	This is the Oculocardiac reflex.\nTrigger: traction or pressure on the eye or retrobulbar block\n• Afferent: trigeminal nerve (ophthalmic branch, CN V1)\n• Efferent: vagus nerve (CN X)\n• Effect: bradycardia, hypotension, nausea, arrhythmias	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
346	2	A 55-year-old patient presents with dehydration, metabolic acidosis, and hypokalemia following profuse gastrointestinal fluid loss. Which of the following sites of fluid loss is most consistent with this acid-base and electrolyte pattern?	Stomach	Duodenum	Colon	Esophagus	C	This pattern is consistent with Diarrhea. Diarrheal fluid loss from the colon leads to:\n• Loss of bicarbonate (HCO3-) → metabolic acidosis\n• Loss of potassium → hypokalemia\n• Dehydration	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
347	2	A 60-year-old man with long-standing hypertension undergoes fundoscopic examination. The retinal vessels appear narrowed with copper and silver wire appearance. Which of the following conditions is most associated with this finding?	Chronic hypertension	Diabetic retinopathy	Glaucoma	Retinal detachment	A	This is Chronic hypertension.\n• Copper wire and silver wire arterioles occur due to:\n  o Chronic thickening of arteriolar walls\n  o Hyaline arteriolosclerosis\n  o Increased light reflection from sclerosed vessels\nThese are classic retinal changes in long-standing hypertension.	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
348	2	A 58-year-old man with chronic inflammatory disease presents with fatigue and pallor. Laboratory tests show low hemoglobin, low MCV, and increased serum ferritin. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Iron deficiency anemia	Anemia of chronic disease	Sideroblastic anemia	Thalassemia trait	B	This is Anemia of chronic disease.\nKey findings:\n• Low MCV (can be microcytic or normocytic)\n• High ferritin (iron trapped in macrophages)\n• Low serum iron\n• Low transferrin\nMechanism: inflammation → ↑ hepcidin → iron trapped in storage sites, unavailable for erythropoiesis.	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
349	2	A 62-year-old man presents with recurrent episodes of dizziness, nausea, and vomiting, especially after meals. He is found to have labile blood pressure and impaired autonomic reflexes. A brainstem lesion is suspected affecting visceral sensory integration. Which of the following structures is the primary site for processing visceral afferent information from cranial nerves VII, IX, and X?	Nucleus ambiguus	Nucleus tractus solitarius	Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus	Inferior olivary nucleus	B	Nucleus tractus solitarius is the primary sensory receptive area for sensory inputs coming from the cardiovascular, respiratory, and gastrointestinal systems, primarily via cranial nerves VII, IX, and X.	47	2026-07-13 02:07:35.222803	\N
356	2	A 58-year-old man with chronic inflammatory disease presents with fatigue and pallor. Laboratory tests show show low hemoglobin, low MCV, and increased serum ferritin. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Iron deficiency anemia	Anemia of chronic disease	Sideroblastic anemia	Thalassemia trait	B	Anemia of chronic disease is characterized by low MCV (or normocytic), high ferritin (iron trapped in storage sites due to inflammation-induced hepcidin), low serum iron, and low transferrin.	47	2026-07-13 02:10:09.781263	\N
358	2	A 22-year-old man feels his phone vibrating in his pocket. The sensation of vibration is primarily detected by which of the following receptors?	Meissner corpuscles	Pacinian corpuscles	Merkel cells	Ruffini endings	B	These are Pacinian corpuscles. Vibration sense is detected by Pacinian corpuscles, which are:\n• Rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors\n• Located deep in the dermis and subcutaneous tissue\n• Highly sensitive to deep pressure and high-frequency vibration (like a vibrating phone)\n• Especially important for detecting vibration transmitted through tissues\n\nOther receptors:\n• Meissner corpuscles -> light touch, low-frequency vibration\n• Merkel cells -> sustained pressure, texture\n• Ruffini endings -> skin stretch and sustained pressure	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
359	2	A 45-year-old man presents with severe colicky flank pain and hematuria. Urinalysis shows acidic urine. Imaging with plain X-ray KUB fails to show any visible stone, but ultrasound suggests renal calculus. Which of the following is most likely the composition of the stone?	Calcium oxalate	Struvite	Uric acid	Cystine	C	This is Uric acid stone. Uric acid stones are:\n• Radiolucent -> not visible on plain X-ray\n• Formed in acidic urine (low pH)\n• Associated with conditions like gout, high purine diet, and dehydration\n• Can sometimes be detected on ultrasound or CT (CT is most sensitive)\n\nOther stones:\n• Calcium oxalate -> radiopaque (seen on X-ray)\n• Struvite -> radiopaque, associated with infection (urease-positive bacteria)\n• Cystine -> faintly radiopaque, genetic cystinuria	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
360	2	A 35-year-old woman undergoes partial gastrectomy for peptic ulcer disease. A few weeks later, she develops episodes of abdominal cramping, dizziness, sweating, and palpitations shortly after meals. These symptoms are most likely due to rapid intestinal absorption leading to which of the following?	Hyperkalemia	Hypoglycemia	Hypercalcemia	Metabolic alkalosis	B	This is hypoglycemia (late dumping syndrome). Dumping syndrome occurs after gastric surgery due to rapid emptying of hyperosmolar contents into the small intestine. It has two phases:\n\nEarly dumping (within 30 min):\nFluid shift into intestine -> abdominal cramps, diarrhea, hypotension\n\nLate dumping (1-3 hours after meals):\nRapid glucose absorption -> exaggerated insulin release -> Leads to reactive hypoglycemia\nSymptoms: sweating, dizziness, palpitations, weakness\n\nThus, the most characteristic metabolic complication is low blood glucose (hypoglycemia).	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
361	2	A 50-year-old man presents with massive upper gastrointestinal bleeding. Endoscopy reveals a bleeding ulcer on the posterior wall of the stomach. Which of the following arteries is most likely involved?	Left gastric artery	Right gastric artery	Splenic artery	Gastroduodenal artery	C	This is a Splenic artery. Posterior gastric wall ulcers are clinically important because they can erode into the splenic artery, leading to severe hemorrhage.\n\nKey anatomy:\n• Posterior wall of stomach is closely related to the pancreas and splenic artery\n• Ulcer penetration here -> can cause massive, life-threatening bleeding\n\nOther options:\n• Left gastric artery -> usually supplies lesser curvature\n• Right gastric artery -> lesser curvature (distal part)\n• Gastroduodenal artery -> posterior duodenal ulcers (not stomach)	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
362	2	A 22-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of finger discoloration triggered by cold exposure. Her fingers first turn white, then blue, and finally red upon rewarming. There is no associated connective tissue disease. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Buerger disease	Raynaud disease	Systemic sclerosis	Peripheral arterial disease	B	This is Raynaud disease (primary Raynaud phenomenon).\n\nKey features:\n• Episodic vasospasm of digital arteries triggered by cold or stress\n• Classic color change: white (ischemia) -> blue (cyanosis) -> red (reperfusion)\n• Typically young women\n• No underlying systemic disease (unlike Raynaud phenomenon secondary to conditions like systemic sclerosis)	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
363	2	A 34-year-old chronic smoker presents with pain in his feet while walking that is relieved by rest. He also has ischemic ulcers on his toes and absent distal pulses. Angiography shows segmental vascular occlusion with corkscrew collateral vessels. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Buerger disease	Raynaud disease	Atherosclerotic peripheral artery disease	Polyarteritis nodosa	A	This is Buerger disease (thromboangiitis obliterans).\n\nKey features:\n• Strong association with heavy smoking\n• Occurs in young males\n• Causes segmental inflammation and thrombosis of small and medium arteries and veins\n• Leads to distal extremity ischemia, ulcers, and gangrene	48	2026-07-13 02:10:37.69666	\N
364	2	A 28-year-old pregnant woman in her third trimester develops fever, dry cough, and dyspnea following a vesicular skin rash. Chest X-ray shows diffuse bilateral interstitial infiltrates. She rapidly develops hypoxia. Which of the following is the most likely causative organism?	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Varicella-zoster virus	Mycoplasma pneumoniae	Influenza A virus	B	This is Varicella-zoster virus (VZV) pneumonia.\nKey features:\n• Occurs in adults, especially pregnant women or immunocompromised patients\n• Follows or accompanies chickenpox (vesicular rash)\n• Causes primary varicella pneumonia\n• Presents with:\n  o Fever\n  o Dry cough\n  o Dyspnea\n  o Diffuse bilateral interstitial (nodular) infiltrates on chest X-ray\n• Can progress rapidly to respiratory failure	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
365	2	Which of the following substances is absent (or present in negligible amount) in breast milk?	Lactoferrin	α-lactalbumin	Iron	Calcium	C		49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
366	2	A 65-year-old man with long-standing diabetes mellitus presents with progressive pain in both legs while walking, which is relieved by rest. On examination, distal pulses are weak. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation to assess the condition?	CT angiography	MR angiography	Duplex (Doppler) ultrasound	Conventional angiography	C	This is Peripheral arterial disease (PAD).\nKey features:\n• Common in diabetic patients\n• Presents with intermittent claudication\n• Reduced or absent distal pulses\nInitial investigation of choice:\n• Duplex (Doppler) ultrasound\n  o Non-invasive\n  o Assesses blood flow, stenosis, and occlusion\n  o First-line screening test	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
367	2	A 30-year-old farmer presents with excessive salivation, sweating, lacrimation, abdominal cramps, and pinpoint pupils after exposure to pesticides. He is diagnosed with organophosphate poisoning. Which of the following is the most appropriate antidote that reactivates acetylcholinesterase?	Neostigmine	Naloxone	Pralidoxime	Physostigmine	C	This is Pralidoxime. Organophosphate poisoning causes irreversible inhibition of acetylcholinesterase, leading to excess acetylcholine (cholinergic crisis).\nTreatment:\n• Atropine -> blocks muscarinic receptors (treats symptoms like secretions, bronchospasm)\n• Pralidoxime (2-PAM) -> reactivates acetylcholinesterase if given early, especially at nicotinic synapses\n• Best outcome when given before "aging" of the enzyme-organophosphate complex	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
368	2	What is the recommended daily fiber (dietary roughage) intake for an adult?	5-10 grams	10-15 grams	25-30 grams	50-60 grams	C		49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
369	2	A 3-year-old child was playing with small objects and suddenly developed acute onset dyspnea, coughing, and cyanosis. On examination, there is decreased air entry on one side of the chest. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Acute asthma attack	Foreign body aspiration	Croup	Pneumonia	B	This is Foreign body aspiration.\nKey features:\n• Sudden onset cough, dyspnea, and cyanosis in a child while playing\n• Common history of choking episode\n• Unilateral decreased air entry suggests airway obstruction on one side\n• May also show wheeze or stridor depending on location	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
370	2	A 70-year-old man with known chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) presents with hematemesis and melena. On examination, he has splenomegaly and signs of portal hypertension. Which of the following is the most likely source of bleeding?	Left gastric vein	Right gastric vein	Short gastric veins	Superior mesenteric vein	A	This is the left gastric vein (coronary vein).\nKey concept:\n• Portal hypertension leads to formation of portosystemic anastomoses\n• One major site is at the lower esophagus (esophageal varices)\nVenous drainage:\n• Left gastric vein -> portal vein system\n• It anastomoses with esophageal veins (systemic circulation)\nIn portal hypertension:\n• Increased pressure in left gastric vein -> dilation of submucosal esophageal veins -> esophageal varices\n• Rupture causes massive hematemesis and melena	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
371	2	A 68-year-old man with chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) is undergoing chemotherapy. He develops acute flank pain and hematuria. Urinalysis shows acidic urine, and imaging suggests radiolucent renal stones. Which of the following is the most likely type of stone?	Calcium oxalate	Struvite	Uric acid	Calcium phosphate	C	These are Uric acid stones.\nKey points:\n• CLL patients on chemotherapy -> tumor lysis syndrome (TLS)\n• Rapid breakdown of tumor cells -> ↑ purine metabolism -> ↑ uric acid production\n• Uric acid precipitates in urine, especially in acidic urine\n• Forms radiolucent stones (not seen on X-ray)	49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
372	2	A 55-year-old man presents with a painless left-sided scrotal swelling and bag of worms appearance that increases on standing and decreases on lying down. Imaging reveals thrombosis of the left renal vein. Which of the following is the most likely associated finding?	Right-sided varicocele	Left-sided varicocele			 		49	2026-07-13 02:11:19.394403	\N
373	2	A 40-year-old woman presents with burning pain, tingling, and numbness along the medial ankle and sole of the foot, worsening at night. Tinel's sign is positive behind the medial malleolus. Which of the following nerves is most likely compressed?	Common peroneal nerve	Tibial nerve	Saphenous nerve	Superficial peroneal nerve	B	Tarsal tunnel syndrome occurs due to compression of the tibial nerve as it passes behind the medial malleolus under the flexor retinaculum. Key features: Pain, burning, paresthesia in medial ankle and sole of foot; Worse at night or with prolonged standing; Positive Tinel's sign behind medial malleolus; May affect intrinsic muscles of the sole.	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
385	3	A patient with a history of bronchial asthma presents with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT). Which of the following drugs should be used with caution due to its potential to worsen asthma?	Adenosine	Verapamil	Digoxin	Amiodarone	A	Adenosine can cause bronchoconstriction and should be used with caution or avoided in patients with asthma or COPD.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
374	2	A 2-year-old boy presents with a painless, cystic swelling in the scrotum that transilluminates. The swelling is suspected to be a congenital hydrocele. Which of the following is the embryological origin of this condition?	Tunica albuginea	Peritoneum (processus vaginalis)	Transversalis fascia	Dartos fascia	B	Congenital hydrocele occurs due to failure of closure of processus vaginalis. The processus vaginalis is an outpouching of the peritoneum that accompanies testicular descent. Persistent patency allows fluid accumulation -> hydrocele.	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
375	2	In an IVF laboratory, fertilization of an oocyte is monitored. To prevent abnormal fertilization with multiple sperm (polyspermy), which of the following structures primarily acts as the physiological block?	Corona radiata	Zona pellucida	Perivitelline space	Oolemma (oocyte membrane)	B	This is Zona pellucida. Key concept: After the first sperm fuses with the oocyte, the zona pellucida undergoes the cortical reaction. Cortical granules release enzymes that modify the zona pellucida. This leads to: Hardening of zona; Loss of sperm-binding receptors (ZP3 modification) -> prevents entry of additional sperm (block to polyspermy).	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
376	2	What is the approximate difference in osmolality between plasma and interstitial fluid?	2 mOsm/kg	1.5 mOsm/kg	2.5 mOsm/kg	3.5 mOsm/kg	B	This is ~1.5 mOsm/kg difference. Key concept: Plasma and interstitial fluid are separated by capillary endothelium which is highly permeable to small solutes. Therefore, their osmolality is almost equal. However, a small difference exists due to plasma proteins (oncotic pressure), which are present in plasma but not in interstitial fluid. Important point: The difference is very minimal (~1-2 mOsm/kg). Standard exam Ans: ~1.5 mOsm/kg.	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
377	2	A patient with long-standing untreated hyperuricemia presents with acute painful swelling of the big toe (podagra). Shortly after, he develops facial weakness on one side, with inability to close the eye, but forehead movements are spared. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Upper motor neuron facial nerve palsy	Lower motor neuron facial nerve palsy	Trigeminal nerve palsy	Bell's palsy affecting only trigeminal nerve	A	This is Upper motor neuron (UMN) facial nerve palsy. Key feature: Forehead sparing -> classic sign of UMN lesion. Neuroanatomy: Upper facial muscles receive bilateral cortical input. Lower facial muscles receive contralateral cortical input only -> So UMN lesion affects only lower face -> forehead is spared. Clinical correlation: Patient has unrelated acute gout, but facial finding is neurological. UMN lesion may be due to stroke or central pathology, not gout itself.	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
378	2	A patient with type 2 diabetes mellitus is started on a drug that improves insulin sensitivity by acting on nuclear receptors and increasing glucose uptake in adipose tissue and muscle. Which of the following best describes its mechanism of action?	Inhibition of alpha-glucosidase in intestine	Activation of PPAR-γ (nuclear receptor)	Stimulation of insulin release from beta cells	Inhibition of SGLT-2 in renal tubules	B	This is Pioglitazone. Key mechanism: Pioglitazone is a thiazolidinedione (TZD). It acts as an agonist of PPAR-γ (Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma). This is a nuclear receptor that regulates gene transcription. Effects: ↑ Insulin sensitivity in: Adipose tissue, Skeletal muscle, Liver. ↑ Glucose uptake, ↓ Insulin resistance.	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
379	2	A 70-year-old patient with chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) presents with massive ascites and hematemesis. He is suspected to have variceal bleeding due to portal hypertension. Octreotide has already been given. What is the next best step in management?	Endoscopic variceal ligation (banding)	Proton pump inhibitor therapy	Surgical gastrectomy	Barium swallow study	A	This is variceal bleeding in portal hypertension. Management of acute variceal bleed is stepwise: 1. Resuscitation (ABC + IV fluids/blood), 2. Vasoactive drugs -> Octreotide (already given in this case), 3. Endoscopic therapy (variceal ligation/banding).	50	2026-07-13 02:11:49.993403	\N
380	3	A patient with hypertension develops a persistent dry cough after starting antihypertensive therapy. Which of the following drugs is most likely responsible?	Enalapril	Amlodipine	Losartan	Hydrochlorothiazide	A	This is Enalapril. Key concept: ACE inhibitors (like enalapril) inhibit angiotensin-converting enzyme. This leads to: ↓ Angiotensin II, ↑ Bradykinin accumulation. Bradykinin buildup causes: Dry, persistent cough, Sometimes angioedema.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
381	3	A patient with diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) has been treated with insulin. Now the patient's condition has improved: pH = 7.32, bicarbonate = 18 mEq/L, anion gap = 11, but urine dipstick is still positive for ketones. What is the most likely explanation?	Persistent ketoacidosis with normal anion gap metabolic acidosis	β-hydroxybutyrate converted to acetoacetate, which is detected by urine dipstick	Renal impairment causing ketone retention	Ongoing uncontrolled insulin deficiency	B	This is the DKA recovery phase phenomenon. Key concept: In DKA, main ketone bodies are: β-hydroxybutyrate (major in acute DKA), Acetoacetate (minor initially). During treatment with insulin: β-hydroxybutyrate is converted back to acetoacetate. Urine dipstick detects only acetoacetate, not β-hydroxybutyrate. So urine ketones may remain positive even when metabolic acidosis is resolving.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
382	3	A patient presents within 3 hours of sudden onset unilateral weakness and speech difficulty suggestive of acute ischemic stroke. Non-contrast CT brain is normal. What is the most appropriate next step in management?	Start aspirin immediately	Give IV alteplase (thrombolysis)	Start heparin infusion	Perform carotid endarterectomy immediately	B	This is an acute ischemic stroke within a thrombolytic window (≤4.5 hours). Key points: CT brain is normal -> excludes hemorrhage. Presentation is within 3 hours (golden window). No contraindications mentioned. Management: IV alteplase (tPA) is the treatment of choice for eligible patients within 4.5 hours. It works by breaking down the thrombus and restoring cerebral blood flow.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
383	3	A 72-year-old man presents with sudden onset right-sided weakness and slurred speech. CT brain shows an established infarct with no hemorrhage. He arrived at the hospital 10 hours after symptom onset. What is the most appropriate next step in management?	IV alteplase	Mechanical thrombectomy only	Aspirin therapy	IV heparin infusion	C	This is an acute ischemic stroke outside the thrombolysis window (10 hours). Key points: IV thrombolysis (alteplase) is only indicated within 4.5 hours. Patient presents at 10 hours -> too late for tPA. CT shows no hemorrhage -> ischemic stroke confirmed.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
384	3	A patient with acute chest pain undergoes ECG. ST-segment elevation is seen in leads II, III, and aVF. Which of the following coronary arteries is most likely occluded?	Left anterior descending artery (LAD)	Left circumflex artery (LCX)	Right coronary artery (RCA)	Left main coronary artery	C	ST-elevation in leads II, III, and aVF indicates an inferior wall myocardial infarction, which is most commonly caused by occlusion of the Right Coronary Artery (RCA).	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
884	3	Aspirin toxicity what to give in order to increase urinary excrecation of aspirin:	Phosphate	Bicarbonate	NH4	Sodium	B		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
386	3	A 6-year-old child presents with prolonged fever, weight loss, hepatosplenomegaly, and pancytopenia. Bone marrow examination reveals intracellular amastigotes (Leishman-Donovan bodies). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Cutaneous leishmaniasis	Visceral leishmaniasis (Kala-azar)	Mucocutaneous leishmaniasis	Malaria	B	This is Visceral leishmaniasis (Kala-azar). Key points: Caused by Leishmania donovani. Transmitted by sandfly. Affects reticuloendothelial system (liver, spleen, bone marrow). Classic features: Prolonged fever, Massive hepatosplenomegaly, Pancytopenia, Weight loss and weakness, Bone marrow shows Leishman-Donovan bodies (amastigotes inside macrophages).	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
387	3	A patient presented with episodes of syncope and ECG shows polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a "twisting of the points" appearance. Which of the following electrolyte abnormalities is most commonly associated with this condition?	Hypercalcemia	Hypomagnesemia	Hypernatremia	Hyperkalemia	B	This is Torsades de pointes. Key concept: Torsades de pointes is a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia associated with prolonged QT interval. Most important electrolyte cause: Hypomagnesemia (most classic and high-yield).	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
388	3	A 45-year-old man works frequently in a kneeling position (e.g., carpet layer). He presents with pain and swelling over the front of the knee. On examination, there is a fluctuant swelling over the patella. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Prepatellar bursitis	Baker's cyst	Septic arthritis	Patellar fracture	A	This is Prepatellar bursitis. Key points: Also called "housemaid's knee". Caused by repeated kneeling or trauma.	51	2026-07-13 02:12:15.405092	\N
389	3	A patient is prescribed ciprofloxacin for a urinary tract infection. Which of the following best describes its mechanism of action?	Inhibition of cell wall synthesis	Inhibition of DNA gyrase (topoisomerase II)	Inhibition of 30S ribosomal subunit	Inhibition of folic acid synthesis	B	This is Ciprofloxacin. Key mechanism: Ciprofloxacin is a fluoroquinolone. It inhibits DNA gyrase (topoisomerase II) and also topoisomerase IV.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
390	3	A 25-year-old athlete suddenly experiences pain at the front of the thigh while kicking a football. He is unable to extend the knee properly. Which of the following structures is most likely injured?	Rectus femoris tendon	Iliopsoas tendon	Hamstring tendon	Patellar ligament	A	Rectus femoris is part of the quadriceps muscle group. It is the only quadriceps muscle that: Flexes hip, Extends knee.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
391	3	A brick baker who works in a hot environment presents with muscle weakness and fatigue after prolonged heat exposure. Laboratory tests show an electrolyte abnormality. Which of the following is most likely?	Hyponatremia	Hypernatremia	Hypercalcemia	Hypermagnesemia	A	Brick baking involves prolonged heat exposure + excessive sweating. Sweat contains both water and sodium. If the patient replaces losses with plain water (without salt) -> leads to dilutional hyponatremia.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
392	3	A newborn presents with ambiguous external genitalia. Karyotype analysis shows 46,XY. Testes are present, but the external genitalia appear female. Which of the following is the most likely cause?	Testosterone resistance	Androgen receptor insensitivity	Congenital adrenal hyperplasia	Turner syndrome	B	This is Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (AIS). Key features: 46,XY karyotype (genotypically male); Testes present (often undescended); Defective androgen receptors -> body cannot respond to testosterone. Leads to: Female or ambiguous external genitalia; Absent or rudimentary male internal structures; No uterus (due to anti-Müllerian hormone from testes).	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
393	3	A newborn presents with ambiguous genitalia. Karyotype analysis shows 46,XX. Which of the following is the most likely cause?	Androgen insensitivity syndrome	Congenital adrenal hyperplasia	5-alpha reductase deficiency	Klinefelter syndrome	B	This is Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH). Key features: 46,XX (genotypically female); Excess androgen production from adrenal glands; Most commonly due to 21-hydroxylase deficiency. Leads to: Virilization of external genitalia -> ambiguous genitalia; Internal genitalia remain female (uterus, ovaries present). Other associated findings: May have salt-wasting (downward arrow aldosterone); Upward arrow 17-hydroxyprogesterone.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
394	3	A patient presents with inability to flex the knee following an injury to the posterior thigh. If the injury is located on the posterolateral side, which muscle is most likely affected?	Biceps femoris	Semimembranosus	Semitendinosus	Gracilis	A	Hamstring muscles are responsible for knee flexion. Posterolateral muscle -> Biceps femoris. Posteromedial muscles -> Semimembranosus & Semitendinosus.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
395	3	A patient asks the doctor about details of their diagnosis, treatment plan, and ongoing procedures. This aspect of care is best described as which of the following?	Confidentiality	Informed consent	Information disclosure	Autonomy	C	This is Information disclosure. Key concept: Patients have the right to receive clear information about: Their diagnosis, Treatment options, Risks and benefits, Ongoing procedures.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
396	3	A patient with atrial fibrillation develops reduced cardiac output due to loss of atrial contraction. Approximately how much does cardiac output decrease in this condition?	5-10%	10-15%	20-30%	40-50%	C	This is a 20-30% reduction in cardiac output. Key concept: In atrial fibrillation, there is loss of atrial kick. Atrial contraction normally contributes about 20-30% of ventricular filling.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
397	3	A man with Huntington disease marries a healthy woman. What is the probability that their child will inherit the disease?	25%	50%	75%	100%	B	This is Huntington disease, which is an autosomal dominant disorder. Key points: Only one mutant allele is required for disease. If one parent is affected (heterozygous) and the other is normal: Each child has a 50% chance of inheriting the mutation.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
398	3	A patient with long-standing liver disease undergoes examination, and the liver surface is found to be dense and irregular. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Fatty liver disease	Acute hepatitis	Cirrhosis	Liver abscess	C	This is cirrhosis. Key features: Dense, irregular (nodular) liver surface.	52	2026-07-13 02:13:01.872255	\N
399	3	A 40-year-old housemaid presents with swelling and pain over the front of the knee due to repeated kneeling while working. Which of the following structures is most likely inflamed?	Infrapatellar bursa	Prepatellar bursa	Suprapatellar bursa	Popliteal bursa	B	This is Prepatellar bursitis ("Housemaid's knee"). Key points: Caused by repeated kneeling. Involves inflammation of the prepatellar bursa (located in front of the patella).	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
