401	3	A man with Achondroplasia marries a healthy woman. What is the probability that their child will inherit the condition?	25%	50%	75%	100%	B	This is Achondroplasia, which is an autosomal dominant disorder. Key points: Caused by mutation in FGFR3 gene. Only one mutant allele is required for expression. If one parent is affected (heterozygous) and the other is normal: Each child has a 50% chance of inheriting the disorder.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
402	3	A farmer develops abdominal pain and imaging shows a liver cyst suggestive of hydatid disease. Which of the following is the definitive (primary) host for Echinococcosis?	Sheep	Human	Dog	Cow	C	Echinococcus granulosus life cycle involves: Definitive host = Dog (adult tapeworm lives in intestine). Intermediate host = Sheep (larval cyst stage). Humans = accidental intermediate host.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
403	3	A 60-year-old man presents with sudden severe chest pain. ECG shows ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI). Which of the following is the most common underlying cause?	Coronary artery spasm	Coronary artery embolism	Atherosclerotic plaque rupture with arterial thrombosis	Aortic dissection	C	This is arterial thrombosis due to atherosclerotic plaque rupture. Key concept: The most common cause of myocardial infarction (MI) is: Rupture of atherosclerotic plaque -> platelet activation -> thrombus formation -> coronary artery occlusion.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
404	3	A child presents with fever, neck stiffness, and rapidly progressing petechial rash. The condition is complicated by bilateral adrenal hemorrhage (Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome). Which organism is most commonly associated with this condition?	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Neisseria meningitidis	Haemophilus influenzae	Staphylococcus aureus	B	This is Neisseria meningitidis. Key concept: Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome = acute adrenal hemorrhage. Classically caused by fulminant meningococcemia.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
405	3	A woman who is exclusively breastfeeding has not resumed menstruation for several months after delivery. Which hormone is primarily responsible for this lactational amenorrhea?	Estrogen	Progesterone	Prolactin	Oxytocin	C	This is Prolactin. Key concept: During breastfeeding, prolactin levels are elevated. Prolactin: Stimulates milk production, Inhibits GnRH secretion from hypothalamus, Leads to decreased LH and FSH, Prevents ovulation -> lactational amenorrhea. Important mechanism: Suckling -> increased prolactin -> suppression of hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
406	3	A patient presents with dyspepsia and is suspected to have Helicobacter pylori infection. Which of the following is the best non-invasive test to detect active infection?	Serum IgG antibody	Stool antigen test	Abdominal X-ray	Liver function test	B	This is a Stool antigen test. Key points: H. pylori stool antigen test detects active infection. It is: Non-invasive, Highly sensitive and specific, Useful for both diagnosis and post-treatment confirmation (eradication test).	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
407	3	A patient with liver capsule irritation (e.g., subphrenic abscess) complains of referred pain to the shoulder. Which nerve is responsible for this referred pain?	Vagus nerve	Phrenic nerve	Intercostal nerve	Sympathetic chain	B	The central tendon of the diaphragm and nearby structures (e.g., liver capsule, peritoneum under diaphragm) are supplied by the phrenic nerve (C3-C5). Irritation of diaphragm -> pain referred to shoulder (C3-C5 dermatome).	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
408	3	A patient presents with inability to abduct the arm beyond 15 degrees following trauma to the shoulder region. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?	Radial nerve	Axillary nerve	Musculocutaneous nerve	Median nerve	B	Arm abduction is mainly performed by: Supraspinatus (0-15°), Deltoid (15-90°) which is supplied by the axillary nerve.	53	2026-07-13 02:13:37.921613	\N
409	3	A newborn is noted to have the "waiter's tip" position of the upper limb after a difficult delivery. The arm is adducted and medially rotated, with an extended elbow and pronated forearm. Which of the following nerve roots are most likely injured?	C5-C6	C8-T1	C3-C5	T1-T2	A	Explanation: This is Erb's palsy (upper trunk brachial plexus injury).\nKey concept:\n• Injury to C5-C6 nerve roots (upper trunk)\nMuscles affected:\n• Deltoid, supraspinatus -> loss of abduction\n• Infraspinatus -> loss of external rotation\n• Biceps -> weak elbow flexion/supination	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
410	3	A patient with a history of malaria now presents again with fever, chills, and malaise after a symptom-free period. There is no G6PD assay available. Which of the following forms in the liver is most likely responsible for relapse?	Sporozoites	Merozoites	Hypnozoites	Gametocytes	C	Explanation:\n• Relapse malaria is classically caused by dormant liver forms called hypnozoites\nOrganisms involved:\n• Plasmodium vivax and Plasmodium ovale\nLife cycle point:\n• After mosquito bite -> sporozoites enter liver\n• Some develop into hypnozoites (dormant stage)\n• These can reactivate later -> cause relapse infection	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
411	3	An elderly patient presents with fever, neck stiffness, and altered mental status suggestive of meningitis. CSF Gram stain shows Gram-positive rods. Which of the following is the most likely organism?	Neisseria meningitidis	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Listeria monocytogenes	Haemophilus influenzae	C	Explanation:\n• It is a Gram-positive rod causing meningitis, especially in:\no Neonates\no Elderly\no Pregnant women\no Immunocompromised patients	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
