413	3	A 75-year-old man presents with urinary frequency, weak stream, nocturia, and episodes of urinary incontinence. Digital rectal examination reveals an enlarged, smooth prostate. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Prostate cancer	Benign prostatic hyperplasia	Acute prostatitis	Neurogenic bladder	B	Explanation:\nBPH\nCommon in elderly men\nCauses lower urinary tract symptoms (LUTS):\no Urinary frequency\no Nocturia\no Weak stream\no Urinary hesitancy\no Overflow incontinence (in advanced cases)\nExamination:\n• Smooth, enlarged prostate on DRE	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
414	3	A 70-year-old man has benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) along with hypertension. Which of the following drugs is most appropriate as it treats both conditions?	Tamsulosin	Doxazosin	Finasteride	Oxybutynin	B	Explanation: This is Doxazosin.\nKey concept:\n• Doxazosin is an α1-adrenergic blocker\n• It causes:\no Relaxation of smooth muscle in prostate -> improves urinary flow in BPH\no Vasodilation of blood vessels -> lowers blood pressure in hypertension	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
