415	3	A young obese woman presents with daily headaches, transient visual obscurations, and pulsatile tinnitus. Fundoscopy shows papilledema. CT brain is normal, and there is no mass lesion. Lumbar puncture shows elevated opening pressure with normal CSF composition. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Brain tumor	Meningitis	Idiopathic intracranial hypertension	Subarachnoid hemorrhage	C	Explanation: This is Idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH).\nKey features:\n• Classically seen in young obese women\n• Symptoms of raised intracranial pressure:\no Headache\no Transient visual loss\no Pulsatile tinnitus\n• Papilledema on fundoscopy\n• Imaging (CT/MRI): normal (no mass lesion)\n• Lumbar puncture:\no Increased opening pressure\no Normal CSF composition	54	2026-07-13 02:14:13.881424	\N
