417	3	...that can be scraped off, leaving an erythematous base. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?	Nystatin	Acyclovir	Fluconazole	Metronidazole	A	Diagnosis: Oral candidiasis (oral thrush) caused by Candida albicans\nTypical features:\n- White, curd-like plaques\n- Can be scraped off -> erythematous base\n- Common in infants, diabetics, immunocompromised patients	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
418	3	A patient has a history of a neck procedure and now presents with ptosis and inability to shrug the shoulder. Which of the following structures are most likely injured?	Facial nerve and vagus nerve	Spinal accessory nerve and sympathetic chain	Hypoglossal nerve and trigeminal nerve	Phrenic nerve and recurrent laryngeal nerve	B	Spinal accessory nerve (CN XI) supplies:\n- Sternocleidomastoid\n- Trapezius -> shoulder shrugging\nSympathetic chain (cervical sympathetic fibers) disruption causes:\n- Ptosis (Müller muscle paralysis)\n- Miosis\n- Anhidrosis\n-> features of Horner syndrome	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
419	3	A patient with uncontrolled diabetes mellitus presents with black necrotic nasal discharge, facial pain, and rapidly progressive fungal infection involving the nasal and sinus region. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Aspergillosis	Mucormycosis	Candidiasis	Cryptococcosis	B	Key points:\n- Strong association with uncontrolled diabetes (especially DKA)\n- Also seen in immunocompromised patients\nClassic features:\n- Black necrotic eschar ("black fungus")\n- Rhinocerebral involvement:\n  - Nasal congestion\n  - Facial pain\n  - Orbital swelling\n  - Black discharge\n- Rapidly progressive and life-threatening	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
420	3	A patient presents with syncope. ECG shows a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic "twisting" of fluctuating amplitude of QRS complexes around the baseline. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Ventricular fibrillation	Torsades de pointes	Atrial fibrillation	Ventricular tachycardia (monomorphic)	B	Torsades de pointes:\n- Polymorphic ventricular tachycardia\n- QRS complexes appear to "twist around the baseline"\n- Associated with prolonged QT interval\nCommon causes:\n- Hypomagnesemia\n- Hypokalemia\n- Drugs that prolong QT (e.g., antiarrhythmics, macrolides)	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
421	3	A chronic alcoholic patient presents with confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. Which of the following vitamin deficiencies is most likely responsible for this condition?	Vitamin B1 (Thiamine)	Vitamin B12 (Cobalamin)	Vitamin B6 (Pyridoxine)	Vitamin B3 (Niacin)	A	This is Vitamin B1 (Thiamine) deficiency -> Wernicke's encephalopathy.\nClassic triad:\n- Confusion\n- Ataxia\n- Ophthalmoplegia (eye movement abnormalities)	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
422	3	A researcher conducts a study to evaluate the effect of a new antihypertensive drug. Neither the patients nor the investigators know who is receiving the drug or placebo. What type of study design is this?	Cohort study	Case-control study	Double-blind randomized controlled trial	Cross-sectional study	C	Double-blind = both patient and investigator are unaware of group allocation\nRandomized controlled trial (RCT) = participants are randomly assigned to:\n- Treatment group (new drug)\n- Control group (placebo/standard drug)	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
