425	3	Which of the following are the main sites of gluconeogenesis in the human body?	Brain and muscle	Liver and kidney	Pancreas and spleen	Adipose tissue and heart	B	Gluconeogenesis occurs primarily in the liver and to a lesser extent in the kidneys.	55	2026-07-13 02:15:13.289553	\N
426	3	A patient presents with generalized tonic-clonic movements, loss of consciousness, tongue biting, and postictal confusion. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Absence seizure	Grand mal seizure (generalized tonic-clonic seizure)	Simple partial seizure	Atonic seizure	B	Grand mal seizure (generalized tonic-clonic seizure). Key features:\n• Sudden loss of consciousness\n• Tonic phase → body stiffening\n• Clonic phase → rhythmic jerking movements\n• Postictal confusion (important distinguishing feature)\n• Tongue biting, possible urinary incontinence	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
427	3	During aerobic respiration of one molecule of glucose, approximately how many ATP molecules are produced?	2	18	32	64	C	This is 32 ATP (in eukaryotes, commonly accepted in MCQs). Key concept:\n• Complete oxidation of 1 glucose molecule in aerobic respiration produces:\n  o Glycolysis\n  o Krebs cycle\n  o Electron transport chain (oxidative phosphorylation)	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
