429	3	A patient presents with dehydration due to excessive water loss. Laboratory evaluation suggests increased antidiuretic hormone (ADH) secretion. In which part of the nephron will ADH have its maximum effect to increase water reabsorption?	Proximal convoluted tubule (PCT)	Distal convoluted tubule (DCT)	Collecting duct	Loop of Henle	C	ADH acts mainly on the collecting duct (and late DCT)\n• It increases insertion of aquaporin-2 water channels\n• This allows increased water reabsorption from urine into blood	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
431	3	A child presents with daily high spiking fever, joint pain, and a characteristic salmon-colored evanescent rash that appears with fever spikes. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Juvenile idiopathic arthritis (systemic type)	Rheumatoid arthritis	Systemic lupus erythematosus	Reactive arthritis	A	This is Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis (Still disease). Key features:\n• Daily (quotidian) high spiking fever\n• Salmon-colored rash (evanescent, appears with fever)\n• Arthritis / joint pain\n• Often systemic inflammation (high ferritin, ESR)\nClassic triad:\n• Fever\n• Rash\n• Arthritis	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
432	3	A child presents with fatigue, generalized body aches, proximal muscle weakness, and a characteristic skin rash. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Dermatomyositis	Polymyalgia rheumatica	Myasthenia gravis	Fibromyalgia	A	Explanation: Dermatomyositis. Key features:\n• Proximal muscle weakness (difficulty climbing stairs, getting up)\n• Fatigue and body aches\n• Characteristic skin findings:\n  o Heliotrope rash (violet discoloration around eyes)\n  o Gottron's papules (over knuckles)	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
433	3	A patient presents with progressive shortness of breath, fatigue, and signs of heart failure. On examination, there is a displaced apex beat and an S3 heart sound. Echocardiography shows dilated cardiac chambers with reduced systolic function. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy	Dilated cardiomyopathy	Restrictive cardiomyopathy	Constrictive pericarditis	B	Explanation: Dilated cardiomyopathy. Key features:\n• Dilated ventricles and atria\n• Reduced systolic function (↓ ejection fraction)\n• Symptoms of heart failure (dyspnea, fatigue)\n• S3 gallop sound (due to volume overload)\n• Displaced apex beat (enlarged heart)	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
434	3	A student is sitting in a classroom and continuously tracks a moving fly with smooth, coordinated eye movements to keep the object in focus. Which of the following types of eye movement is being demonstrated?	Saccadic movement	Pursuit (smooth pursuit) movement	Vestibulo-ocular reflex	Nystagmus	B	Explanation: This is smooth pursuit (pursuit eye movement). Key concept:\n• Pursuit movements are smooth, continuous eye movements that:\n  o Track a moving target\n  o Keep the image stabilized on the fovea	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
435	3	A child presents with pallor, fatigue, and laboratory findings of hypochromic microcytic anemia. Stool examination reveals ova of a parasitic infection. Which of the following organisms is the most likely cause?	Ascaris lumbricoides	Ancylostoma duodenale	Entamoeba histolytica	Giardia lamblia	B	Explanation: Ancylostoma duodenale (hookworm infection). Key points:\n• Causes iron deficiency anemia → hypochromic microcytic anemia\n• Parasite attaches to intestinal mucosa and feeds on blood\n• Leads to chronic blood loss → anemia, especially in children	56	2026-07-13 02:15:45.171691	\N
436	3	A 12-year-old child presents with a history of sore throat 2-3 weeks ago, followed by fever, joint pain that moves from one joint to another, and generalized malaise. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Septic arthritis	Rheumatic fever	Osteoarthritis	Reactive arthritis	B	Rheumatic fever.\nKey points:\n• Follows Group A Streptococcal (Streptococcus pyogenes) pharyngitis\n• Latent period: 2-3 weeks after sore throat\n• Features:\n• Migratory polyarthritis (joint pain moves from joint to joint)\n• Fever\n• Carditis, chorea, erythema marginatum (may also occur)	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
437	3	A patient asks about brain metabolism during fasting. Which of the following is the primary fuel source used by the brain under normal conditions?	Fatty acids	Glucose	Ketone bodies only	Amino acids	B	The brain primarily uses glucose as its main energy source under normal conditions\n• It cannot effectively use fatty acids because they do not cross the blood-brain barrier\n• During prolonged fasting, the brain can partially adapt to use ketone bodies, but glucose is still required in small amounts	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
438	3	A patient with a long history of cigarette smoking asks about harmful substances present in tobacco smoke. Which of the following is a major class of carcinogenic compounds found in cigarette smoke?	Hydrocarbons (polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons)	Amino acids	Carbohydrates	Proteins	A	Cigarette smoke contains multiple toxic and carcinogenic substances including:\n• Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs)\n• Nitrosamines\n• Carbon monoxide\n• Nicotine	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
439	3	A 28-year-old woman is 6 weeks pregnant and is taking carbimazole (Neomercazole) for hyperthyroidism. She comes for review. What is the most appropriate change in her management?	Continue carbimazole	Stop all antithyroid drugs	Switch to propylthiouracil (PTU)	Start radioactive iodine therapy	C	Carbimazole/methimazole is teratogenic, especially in the first trimester (6 weeks = critical period of organogenesis)\n• Associated with:\n• Aplasia cutis\n• Choanal/esophageal atresia\nManagement in pregnancy:\n• First trimester -> PTU is preferred\n• After first trimester -> often switched back to carbimazole due to PTU hepatotoxicity risk	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
440	3	A young woman presents with weight gain, history of acne, irregular menstrual cycles, and low mood. Which of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to confirm the suspected diagnosis?	Serum prolactin level	Thyroid function test	Pelvic (ovarian) ultrasound	Serum cortisol level	C	This is Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS).\nKey features:\n• Weight gain\n• Acne (hyperandrogenism)\n• Menstrual irregularities (oligo/amenorrhea)\n• Mood changes may also be associated	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
441	3	A newborn is delivered to a mother who used lithium during pregnancy. The baby presents with cyanosis and a cardiac murmur on examination. What is the most likely congenital heart defect?	Tetralogy of Fallot	Ebstein anomaly	Patent ductus arteriosus	Ventricular septal defect	B	Maternal lithium use in pregnancy is classically associated with Ebstein anomaly\n• It is a congenital malformation of the tricuspid valve	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
442	3	A patient who has been taking a drug for several weeks reports that the same dose is now producing a weaker effect than before. Which of the following best describes this phenomenon?	Tachyphylaxis	Drug tolerance	Drug allergy	Drug dependence	B	Tolerance = gradual decrease in drug effect with repeated use of the same dose\n• So higher doses are needed to achieve the same effect\nMechanism:\n• Receptor downregulation\n• Increased drug metabolism\n• Cellular adaptation	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
443	3	A patient with type 2 diabetes mellitus is started on a new oral antidiabetic drug. The drug works by inhibiting sodium-glucose co-transporters in the proximal renal tubule, leading to increased urinary glucose excretion. Which of the following drug classes does this mechanism describe?	Sulfonylureas	Biguanides	SGLT2 inhibitors	DPP-4 inhibitorsz	C	Act in the proximal convoluted tubule (PCT) of kidney\n• Block sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2)\n• Result:\n• ↓ glucose reabsorption\n• ↑ glucose excretion in urine (glycosuria)\n• ↓ blood glucose level	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
