444	3	A patient presents after a stroke and is unable to speak fluently. He can only produce a few sounds and understands what others are saying. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Wernicke aphasia	Broca aphasia	Global aphasia	Conduction aphasia	B	Broca's aphasia is a non-fluent aphasia characterized by intact comprehension but severely impaired speech production.	57	2026-07-13 02:16:18.696257	\N
445	3	A patient with chronic kidney disease presents with muscle weakness and ECG changes showing peaked T waves, suggesting acute hyperkalemia. What is the first immediate treatment to stabilize the cardiac membrane?	Insulin with glucose	Calcium gluconate	Furosemide	Sodium bicarbonate	B	In acute hyperkalemia, the most urgent risk is cardiac arrhythmia. Calcium gluconate does NOT lower potassium, but it: Stabilizes cardiac myocyte membranes. Reduces risk of fatal arrhythmias.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
446	3	A patient with peptic ulcer disease is prescribed a drug that acts locally in the stomach and does not require systemic absorption to exert its effect. Which of the following drugs best fits this description?	Omeprazole	Sucralfate	Ranitidine	Misoprostol	B	Sucralfate is a locally acting cytoprotective drug. It does not require systemic absorption. It works by: Forming a protective barrier over ulcer base in acidic environment. Binding to ulcer crater and shielding from acid and pepsin.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
447	3	A patient presents with muscle weakness. ECG shows tall peaked (tented) T waves with prolonged PR interval and widening of QRS complexes. Which of the following is the most likely electrolyte abnormality?	Hypokalemia	Hyperkalemia	Hypercalcemia	Hypocalcemia	B	Hyperkalemia. Key ECG features: Tall, peaked (tented) T waves (earliest sign), Prolonged PR interval, Widened QRS complex, Can progress to sine-wave pattern and cardiac arrest.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
