450	3	A 68-year-old postmenopausal woman presents with back pain and a history of low-impact fractures. Which of the following is the most appropriate investigation to assess bone mineral density?	Serum calcium level	X-ray spine	DEXA scan	CT scan	C	DEXA scan (Dual-energy X-ray Absorptiometry). Key points: Gold standard test for diagnosing osteoporosis. Commonly used in postmenopausal elderly women. What it measures: Bone mineral density (BMD), Gives T-score: > -1 -> normal, -1 to -2.5 -> osteopenia, <= -2.5 -> osteoporosis.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
451	3	A patient presents with sudden onset of respiratory distress and chest pain following a long bone fracture. Which of the following is the most likely origin of the embolus?	Air embolism	Fat (bone marrow) embolism	Thromboembolism from deep veins	Amniotic fluid embolism	B	Fat (bone marrow) embolism. Key points: Occurs after long bone fractures (e.g., femur, tibia) or orthopedic surgery. Emboli originate from bone marrow fat entering the circulation.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
452	3	A 70-year-old patient presents with chronic pelvic pain. Laboratory tests show elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP), while calcium and phosphate levels are normal. X-ray reveals bone enlargement with a "cotton wool" appearance in the pelvis. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Osteoporosis	Osteomalacia	Paget disease of bone	Bone metastasis	C	Paget disease of bone. Key points: Common in elderly patients. Often affects pelvis, skull, spine, and femur. Symptoms: Bone pain (e.g., pelvic pain), Bone deformities. Lab findings: Markedly increased ALP (high bone turnover), Normal calcium and phosphate.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
453	3	A child presents with bowing of the legs, delayed growth, and bone pain. Laboratory tests show low vitamin D levels. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Rickets	Osteoporosis	Osteomalacia	Paget disease of bone	A	Rickets. Key points: Occurs in children (before epiphyseal closure). Due to vitamin D deficiency. Leads to defective bone mineralization. Clinical features: Bowing of legs (genu varum/valgum), Delayed growth, Fracture tendency, Delayed tooth eruption.	58	2026-07-13 02:16:59.097544	\N
454	3	A patient with allergic asthma is prescribed cromolyn sodium for prophylaxis. Which of the following best describes its mechanism of action?	Blocks histamine H1 receptors	Prevents mast cell degranulation	Inhibits leukotriene synthesis	Stimulates β2 receptors	B	Cromolyn sodium.\n• It is a mast cell stabilizer\n• Prevents release of inflammatory mediators (histamine, leukotrienes) by:\n• Blocking mast cell degranulation\nClinical use:\n• Prophylaxis of allergic asthma\n• Not useful for acute asthma attacks	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
455	3	A patient develops profuse, foul-smelling watery diarrhea and abdominal pain after being treated with antibiotics for a dental infection. Which of the following antibiotics is most commonly associated with this condition?	Penicillin	Clindamycin	Azithromycin	Doxycycline	B	Explanation: Clindamycin Causes Clostridioides difficile infection (pseudomembranous colitis)\n• Disrupts normal gut flora → overgrowth of C. difficile → toxin production	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
456	3	A patient in cardiogenic shock is started on an inotropic drug that increases cardiac output by stimulating β1 receptors, with mild β2-mediated vasodilation. Which of the following best describes its mechanism of action?	Pure α1 agonist causing vasoconstriction	β1 agonist causing positive inotropy and chronotropy with mild β2 vasodilation	Muscarinic agonist decreasing heart rate	Calcium channel blocker reducing contractility	B	Explanation: This is Dobutamine.\nKey points:\n• Primarily β1 agonist\n• Effects:\n  o Positive inotropy (↑ contractility)\n  o Positive chronotropy (↑ heart rate)\n  o Mild β2-mediated vasodilation may reduce afterload slightly	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
457	3	A 32-year-old man presents with dark "cola-colored" urine in the morning, fatigue, and episodes of abdominal pain. Laboratory tests show hemolytic anemia, and flow cytometry demonstrates absence of CD55 and CD59 on blood cells. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Sickle cell anemia	Autoimmune hemolytic anemia	Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria	G6PD deficiency	C	Explanation: Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria.\nKey points:\n• Acquired hemolytic anemia due to PIGA gene mutation\n• Leads to deficiency of CD55 and CD59 (protect RBCs from complement)\nClassic features:\n• Dark morning urine (hemoglobinuria)\n• Hemolysis (especially at night due to complement activation)\n• Thrombosis (especially hepatic vein → Budd-Chiari syndrome)	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
887	3	A 35 year old woman presents with complaints of heightened sensitivity to smells, particularly strong odors that she previously found tolerable, along with difficulties recalling recent events and learning new information. Which structure is likely involved in her symptoms?	Amygdala	Hippocampus	Cerebellum	Prefrontal cortex	A		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
458	3	Neutrophils temporarily adhere to endothelial cells before transmigration. Which of the following molecules is mainly responsible for this tight adhesion step?	Selectins	Integrins	Cadherins	Immunoglobulins	B	Explanation:\n1. Rolling → Selectins (E-selectin, P-selectin)\n2. Tight adhesion (firm attachment) → Integrins (LFA-1, Mac-1) binding to ICAM-1\n3. Diapedesis → PECAM-1 (CD31)	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
459	3	A patient taking long-term aspirin therapy develops easy bruising and is found to have an increased risk of bleeding complications, including hemorrhagic stroke. Which of the following best describes these adverse effects?	Nephrotoxicity and hyperkalemia	Thrombocytopenia and hemorrhagic complications	Hypoglycemia and lactic acidosis	Pulmonary fibrosis and ototoxicity	B	Explanation: This is Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid) toxicity/side effects.\nKey points:\n• Aspirin irreversibly inhibits COX-1 in platelets → ↓ thromboxane A2 → ↓ platelet aggregation\n• Leads to:\n  o Increased bleeding tendency\n  o Hemorrhagic stroke risk (especially at high doses or prolonged use)	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
460	3	A patient presents with acute bacterial infection. Neutrophils migrate to the site of infection and kill bacteria using intracellular enzymes and toxic proteins stored in granules. Which of the following granules are primarily responsible for the microbicidal activity of neutrophils?	Specific (secondary) granules	Azurophilic (primary) granules	Tertiary granules	Secretory vesicles	B	Explanation:\n• Neutrophils kill bacteria using primary (azurophilic) granules\n• These contain potent microbicidal substances such as:\n  o Myeloperoxidase (MPO)\n  o Lysozyme\n  o Acid hydrolases\n  o Defensins\n  o Proteases\nFunction:\n• Destroy engulfed microbes inside phagolysosomes\nOther granules:\n• Specific (secondary) granules → lactoferrin, collagenase (support function)	59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
