462	3	A patient is asked about the muscles involved in forced expiration during heavy exercise. Which of the following muscle groups are primarily responsible?	Diaphragm and external intercostals	Internal intercostals and abdominal muscles (including rectus abdominis)	Sternocleidomastoid and scalenes	Pectoralis major and minor	B		59	2026-07-13 02:17:30.939605	\N
463	2	Regarding the course of the facial nerve in relation to the parotid gland. Which of the following statements is correct?	Facial nerve lies deep to the parotid gland and innervates it	Facial nerve passes through and divides within the parotid gland	Facial nerve crosses superficial to the parotid gland	Facial nerve has no relation to the parotid gland	B	The facial nerve enters the parotid gland after exiting the stylomastoid foramen. Inside the gland, it divides into its terminal branches: Temporal, Zygomatic, Buccal, Marginal mandibular, Cervical	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
464	2	Muscle directly attached to the temporomandibular joint (TMJ), particularly those involved in mandibular movement and disc control. Which of the following muscles is primarily associated with the TMJ?	Masseter	Medial pterygoid	Lateral pterygoid	Temporalis	C	Lateral pterygoid is the only muscle directly attached to the TMJ joint capsule and articular disc. It helps in: Opening the mouth (depression of mandible), Protrusion of mandible, Side-to-side movements. Other muscles: Masseter -> elevation of mandible, Medial pterygoid -> elevation + grinding movements, Temporalis -> elevation and retraction of mandible	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
