467	2	A 65-year-old man presents with sudden onset severe pain, swelling, and redness of the big toe for the last 2 days. He also has low-grade fever. He reports eating a heavy meal and playing actively with his grandson a week ago. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Septic arthritis	Osteoarthritis	Acute gouty arthritis	Rheumatoid arthritis	C	Acute gouty arthritis. Sudden onset severe pain in big toe (podagra). Can have mild fever. Common triggers: Heavy meal (high purine intake), Physical stress/dehydration. Pathophysiology: Deposition of monosodium urate crystals in joints -> intense inflammatory response. Other options: Septic arthritis -> very high fever, toxic patient, usually single joint but more severe systemic illness. Osteoarthritis -> chronic, non-inflammatory. Rheumatoid arthritis -> chronic, symmetric small joint involvement.	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
468	2	A patient is brought to the emergency department after a road traffic accident (RTA) with severe bleeding and hypotension. The baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch show decreased firing due to reduced arterial pressure. Which of the following best explains this physiological response?	Increased parasympathetic outflow	Decreased sympathetic outflow	Decreased baroreceptor firing leading to increased sympathetic activity	Increased vagal tone causing bradycardia	C	Severe bleeding -> ↓ blood pressure (hypotension). This leads to decreased stretch of baroreceptors (carotid sinus & aortic arch). Result: ↓ baroreceptor firing to medulla -> increased sympathetic outflow -> vasoconstriction, tachycardia, increased cardiac output. Physiological effect: Body tries to maintain perfusion to vital organs.	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
469	2	A patient presents with difficulty speaking and swallowing after a brainstem stroke. On examination, when asked to protrude the tongue, it deviates to one side. Which of the following is the most likely site of lesion?	Midbrain	Pons	Medulla oblongata	Cerebellum	C	This is Medulla oblongata lesion. Tongue deviation indicates hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) dysfunction. CN XII nucleus is located in the medulla oblongata. Lesion causes: Tongue deviates toward the side of the lesion (LMN lesion), Dysarthria and dysphagia.	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
470	2	A patient presents with shortness of breath and blood gas analysis shows a rightward shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve. Which of the following is the most likely associated change?	Decreased temperature, decreased CO2	Increased pH (alkalosis)	Increased PCO2 and decreased pH	Decreased 2,3-BPG levels	C	A right shift means hemoglobin has decreased affinity for oxygen	60	2026-07-13 02:17:50.964555	\N
471	2	A patient with diabetic ketoacidosis is treated with insulin infusion. After treatment, which of the following electrolyte changes is most expected as a direct effect of insulin?	Hyperkalemia	Hypokalemia	Hypercalcemia	Hypernatremia	B	Insulin drives glucose into cells. At the same time, it drives potassium (K+) into cells via Na+/K+ ATPase activation. Result -> decrease in serum potassium -> hypokalemia	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
472	2	Which of the following is an example of a T-cell-mediated autoimmune disease?	Myasthenia gravis	Type 1 diabetes mellitus	Graves disease	Hashimoto thyroiditis	B	Type 1 diabetes is primarily a T-cell-mediated (Type IV hypersensitivity) autoimmune disease. CD8+ cytotoxic T cells destroy pancreatic β-cells. Mechanism: Autoimmune attack -> loss of insulin-producing β-cells -> Leads to absolute insulin deficiency	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
473	2	A patient with newly diagnosed Type 1 diabetes mellitus is evaluated for autoimmune markers. Which of the following antibodies is most commonly associated with this condition?	Anti-thyroid peroxidase (anti-TPO)	Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibody	Anti-GAD antibody	Anti-dsDNA antibody	C	Type 1 DM is an autoimmune destruction of pancreatic β-cells. The most common autoantibody is anti-GAD (glutamic acid decarboxylase antibody). Other associated antibodies: IA-2 antibodies, Insulin autoantibodies (especially in children)	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
474	2	A pregnant woman with HELLP syndrome and seizures is treated with magnesium sulfate. After administration, which of the following is the most important parameter to monitor for magnesium toxicity?	Blood pressure	Deep tendon reflexes (DTRs)	Urine output only	Blood glucose levels	B	For Magnesium sulfate toxicity monitoring follows: Deep tendon reflexes, Respiratory rate, Urine output	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
475	2	A 25-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of unilateral, throbbing headache associated with nausea and vomiting, sometimes preceded by visual aura. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Tension headache	Cluster headache	Migraine	Subarachnoid hemorrhage	C	Unilateral, pulsating (throbbing) headache. Associated symptoms: Nausea and vomiting, Photophobia/phonophobia (common), May have aura (visual or sensory symptoms before headache)	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
476	2	A newborn is found to have a small midline swelling over the sacral region. The skin is intact, and there are no neurological deficits or signs of spinal cord involvement. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Meningocele	Myelomeningocele	Spina bifida occulta	Encephalocele	C		61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
477	2	A child presents with a history of recurrent respiratory tract infections since early childhood, chronic sinusitis, and otitis media. Examination also reveals bronchiectasis. Which of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?	Cystic fibrosis	Primary ciliary dyskinesia	Asthma	Allergic rhinitis	B	Primary Ciliary dyskinesia: Defect in ciliary structure/function (dynein arm defect). Leads to poor mucociliary clearance -> recurrent infections. Clinical features: Recurrent respiratory infections, Chronic sinusitis, Otitis media, Bronchiectasis. Classic association: May be associated with situs inversus (Kartagener syndrome)	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
478	2	A patient presents with progressive exertional dyspnea, fatigue, and orthopnea. On auscultation, a low-pitched, rumbling mid-diastolic murmur is heard best at the apex with the patient in the left lateral position. An opening snap is also noted. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Aortic stenosis	Mitral regurgitation	Mitral stenosis	Tricuspid regurgitation	C	Mitral stenosis. Key features: Rheumatic heart disease is the most common cause. Murmur characteristics: Low-pitched, rumbling mid-diastolic murmur, Best heard at apex with bell, Opening snap after S2 (classic feature)	61	2026-07-13 02:18:26.333388	\N
