481	2	A child presents with seizures, intellectual disability, facial angiofibromas, shagreen patches, and imaging reveals cardiac rhabdomyomas and renal angiomyolipomas. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Neurofibromatosis type 1	Tuberous sclerosis	Sturge-Weber syndrome	Von Hippel-Lindau disease	B	Explanation: Tuberous sclerosis complex.\nKey features:\n• Classic neurocutaneous syndrome\nMajor clinical findings:\n• Neurological: seizures, intellectual disability\n• Skin: shagreen patches, facial angiofibromas, hypomelanotic ("ash leaf") spots\n• Cardiac: rhabdomyoma (common in children)\n• Renal: angiomyolipomas	62	2026-07-13 02:18:50.487557	\N
482	2	A drug (diazepam) has a long half-life. How long does it approximately take to reach steady state concentration after regular dosing is started?	2 days	3 days	9 days	24 hours	C	Explanation: This is based on the pharmacokinetic principle of Steady state.\nKey point:\n• Steady state is usually reached after 4-5 half-lives\nGiven:\n• Half-life of diazepam ≈ 2 days\nCalculation:\n• 4-5 half-lives → 2 x 4 to 2 x 5 = 8 to 10 days	62	2026-07-13 02:18:50.487557	\N
