499	3	A student develops nausea, vomiting, and abdominal cramps a few hours after eating reheated rice left at room temperature overnight. What is the most likely causative organism?	Staphylococcus aureus	Bacillus cereus	Clostridium botulinum	Salmonella typhi	B		63	2026-07-13 02:19:35.05775	\N
500	3	A 55-year-old has been experiencing progressive constipation and change in bowel habits for the last 6 months. He has been on antihypertensive medication for the past year. There is no history of acute infection. What is the most appropriate next step in management?	Increase dietary fiber and fluids	Start laxatives	Abdominal X-ray	Colonoscopy	D	New change in bowel habits for >6 weeks/months is an alarm symptom. Especially in older adults -> must rule out colorectal cancer or structural lesions.	63	2026-07-13 02:19:35.05775	\N
501	3	A patient presents with a bleeding tendency. Laboratory findings show: Normal bleeding time, Normal PT, Normal aPTT. What is the most likely cause or next step?	Vitamin K deficiency	Platelet dysfunction (e.g., aspirin use)	Hemophilia A	Von Willebrand disease	B	This is Platelet function disorder. Key interpretation:\n• Bleeding time = normal -> platelet function likely normal\n• PT and aPTT = normal -> coagulation cascade intact\n• Important correction: Vitamin K deficiency would increase PT (and sometimes aPTT) -> so NOT correct here.	63	2026-07-13 02:19:35.05775	\N
502	10	A patient with a history of untreated syphilis presents with sensory ataxia, lightning-like pains, loss of proprioception, and urinary incontinence (neurogenic bladder). What is the most likely diagnosis?	Multiple sclerosis	Tabes dorsalis	Guillain-Barré syndrome	Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis	B	Tabes dorsalis. Key points: • Occurs in tertiary syphilis (Treponema pallidum infection) • Affects dorsal columns + dorsal roots. Clinical features: • Loss of proprioception and vibration sense • Sensory ataxia (positive Romberg sign) • "Lightning pains" • Neurogenic bladder (bladder dysfunction/incontinence)	64	2026-07-13 02:20:03.042824	\N
513	3	A 75-year-old woman presents with progressive memory loss, difficulty performing daily activities, and recent disorientation to time and place. Her family reports that she often forgets recent events but recalls old memories relatively well. MRI of the brain shows general cortical atrophy, especially involving the hippocampus. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Vascular dementia	Alzheimer disease	Lewy body dementia	Frontotemporal dementia	B		66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
503	10	A 19-year-old tall, thin male presents with long limbs, hyperextensible joints, and a history of lens dislocation. On examination, he has a high-arched palate and a diastolic murmur suggestive of aortic regurgitation. A mutation affecting which of the following proteins is most likely responsible for his condition?	Collagen type I	Elastin	Fibrillin-1	Dystrophin	C	This patient has classic features of Marfan syndrome, a connective tissue disorder caused by mutations in the FBN1 gene. Fibrillin-1 is a glycoprotein essential for the formation of microfibrils, which provide structural support to elastic fibers. Defective fibrillin leads to: • Weak connective tissue • Aortic root dilation -> risk of aneurysm/dissection • Lens dislocation (typically upward)	64	2026-07-13 02:20:03.042824	\N
504	10	A 45-year-old man presents with difficulty walking after receiving an intramuscular injection in the gluteal region. On examination, when he stands on his right leg, his pelvis drops on the left side. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?	Inferior gluteal nerve	Superior gluteal nerve	Sciatic nerve	Femoral nerve	B	Injury to the superior gluteal nerve (L4-S1) affects gluteus medius and minimus. These muscles are responsible for abduction and stabilization of the pelvis during walking. Damage leads to Trendelenburg gait. Pelvis drops on the contralateral side when standing on the affected limb. Patient may lean toward the affected side (compensatory lurch) to maintain balance.	64	2026-07-13 02:20:03.042824	\N
505	10	A 32-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after exposure to smoke in a closed space. He is confused, tachycardic, and has lactic acidosis. Despite adequate oxygen levels, his cells are unable to utilize oxygen effectively. Inhibition of which of the following is the most likely cause of his condition?	Hemoglobin	Myoglobin	Cytochrome oxidase	Catalase	C	This scenario suggests Cyanide poisoning. Cyanide inhibits cytochrome oxidase (Complex IV) in the electron transport chain. This blocks oxidative phosphorylation, preventing cells from using oxygen. Leads to histotoxic hypoxia (oxygen present but cannot be utilized). Results in lactic acidosis due to anaerobic metabolism.	64	2026-07-13 02:20:03.042824	\N
506	3	A 65-year-old woman presents with gradual, painless loss of vision. She reports difficulty noticing objects in her peripheral field while central vision remains intact. Examination reveals increased intraocular pressure and optic disc cupping. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Acute angle-closure glaucoma	Cataract	Open-angle glaucoma	Retinal detachment	C	This presentation is typical of Open-angle glaucoma. It is characterized by progressive, painless vision loss. Damage occurs due to increased intraocular pressure over time. Leads to optic nerve cupping. Causes peripheral vision loss first (tunnel vision). Central vision is preserved until late stages.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
507	3	A 52-year-old woman presents with a slowly enlarging thyroid nodule. She later develops chronic cough and multiple "cannonball" lesions in the lungs on chest imaging. Fine-needle aspiration of the thyroid shows follicular-patterned malignant cells. Which of the following is the most likely route of metastasis?	Lymphatic spread to cervical lymph nodes	Hematogenous spread to lungs	Direct invasion into trachea	Perineural invasion	B	This is Follicular thyroid carcinoma. It typically spreads via blood (hematogenous spread) rather than lymphatics. Common metastatic sites: lungs and bones. Lung metastases often appear as "cannonball" lesions. Unlike papillary thyroid carcinoma, it rarely spreads to cervical lymph nodes.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
508	3	A 58-year-old man presents to the emergency department with sudden onset crushing chest pain for 2 hours. ECG shows ST elevation in the anterior leads, and he is diagnosed with acute myocardial infarction. He is given a thrombolytic drug that works by forming a complex with plasminogen to activate plasmin. Which of the following drugs was most likely administered?	Heparin	Warfarin	Streptokinase	Aspirin	C	This is Streptokinase. It is a thrombolytic agent used in acute myocardial infarction, pulmonary embolism, and DVT. It works by forming a complex with plasminogen -> activates plasmin. Plasmin breaks down fibrin clots -> thrombolysis.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
509	3	A 45-year-old man presents with a rapidly enlarging mass in the colon. Biopsy reveals malignant cells with genomic instability and failure of DNA damage control. Normally, a key tumor suppressor protein would halt the cell cycle at the G1 to S checkpoint in response to DNA damage. Which of the following proteins is most likely defective in this patient?	Rb protein	p53 protein	Cyclin D	CDK2	B	This involves TP53 (p53 protein). p53 is the "guardian of the genome". It regulates the G1 -> S checkpoint in the cell cycle. When DNA damage is detected, p53: Arrests cell cycle at G1 (via p21 activation), Allows DNA repair, Triggers apoptosis if damage is severe.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
510	3	A 6-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with progressive difficulty in walking and frequent falls. His mother reports that he has trouble climbing stairs and uses his hands to push himself up from a sitting position. On examination, there is calf pseudohypertrophy and a positive Gowers' sign. Which of the following is the underlying molecular defect in this condition?	Defect in dystrophin protein	Defect in fibrillin-1 protein	Defect in collagen type I	Defect in myosin heavy chain	A	This is Duchenne muscular dystrophy. It is caused by mutation in the dystrophin gene (DMD gene). Dystrophin is essential for linking cytoskeleton of muscle fibers to extracellular matrix. Without dystrophin -> muscle fiber damage during contraction.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
511	3	A 4-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with painless swelling of the right hemiscrotum that increases in size during the day and reduces when lying down. On examination, the swelling is soft, cystic, and transilluminates. The testis is difficult to palpate separately from the swelling. Which is the most likely diagnosis?	Epididymal cyst	Hydrocele (patent processus vaginalis)	Varicocele	Testicular tumor	B	Condition: Hydrocele. Key features: Painless scrotal swelling, Positive transillumination, Increases with standing, decreases when supine (communicating hydrocele). Pathophysiology: Persistent processus vaginalis -> communication between peritoneal cavity and scrotum -> Peritoneal fluid enters scrotal sac.	65	2026-07-13 02:20:37.769316	\N
512	3	A 26-year-old man presents with excessive thirst and passing large volumes of dilute urine for the past 3 months. Laboratory tests show high serum sodium and low urine osmolality. After administration of desmopressin, there is a marked increase in urine osmolality. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Type 1 diabetes mellitus	Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus	Central diabetes insipidus	Syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion (SIADH)	C	This is Diabetes insipidus. Key feature: excessive dilute urine (polyuria) + hypernatremia + polydipsia. Important diagnostic point: Desmopressin response test helps differentiate types of DI. Findings in this case: After desmopressin -> urine osmolality increases significantly. This indicates kidneys are responding to ADH	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
889	3	A patient having kawashiorkar came to hospital for evaluation and he is having abdominal distension and edema which is due to	Decreased PT	Decreased Albumin and raised bilirubin	Increased albumin	Hypoalbuminemia	D		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
514	3	A 45-year-old man presents with progressive involuntary movements, personality changes, and difficulty concentrating. His father had similar symptoms and died in his 50s. Genetic testing reveals an expanded CAG repeat in a gene associated with neurodegeneration. Which of the following genetic phenomena is most characteristic of this disorder?	Genomic imprinting	Anticipation	Mosaicism	Loss of heterozygosity	B	This is Huntington disease. Caused by CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the HTT gene. Shows genetic anticipation	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
515	3	A 50-year-old chronic alcoholic presents with jaundice, ascites, and signs of chronic liver disease. Liver biopsy shows hepatocyte ballooning and eosinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions composed of aggregated intermediate filaments. Which of the following is the most likely finding?	Councilman bodies	Mallory bodies	Negri bodies	Lewy bodies	B		66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
516	3	A 65-year-old man suddenly collapses in the emergency department. He is unresponsive, pulseless, and not breathing normally. The cardiac monitor shows chaotic, irregular electrical activity with no identifiable QRS complexes. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Atrial fibrillation	Ventricular tachycardia	Ventricular fibrillation	Asystole	C	This is Ventricular fibrillation. It is characterized by disorganized, chaotic ventricular electrical activity. There is no effective cardiac output -> cardiac arrest	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
517	3	A medical student is learning about vitamin deficiencies and comes across a condition associated with dermatitis, cheilosis, glossitis, and peripheral neuropathy. This condition is linked to deficiency of a vitamin, that is also known as "anti-dermatitis factor" and is a component of coenzyme a. Which of the following vitamins is most likely deficient?	Vitamin B1 (Thiamine)	Vitamin B2 (Riboflavin)	Vitamin B5 (Pantothenic acid)	Vitamin B6 (Pyridoxine)	C	This is Pantothenic acid. It is a component of Coenzyme A (CoA) and acyl carrier protein. Essential for fatty acid metabolism and energy production	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
518	3	A 45-year-old man presents with progressive abdominal distension and weight loss. On examination, there is shifting dullness consistent with ascites, but no hepatomegaly or splenomegaly. Paracentesis is performed, and the ascitic fluid is sent for analysis. Which of the following is the most useful test to distinguish tuberculous ascites from other causes?	Serum albumin	Serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG)	Ascitic fluid ADA (adenosine deaminase) level	Ascitic fluid amylase	C	This is Tuberculous peritonitis. In tuberculous ascites, hepatomegaly is often absent and ascites may be isolated. Key diagnostic point: Ascitic fluid ADA is highly suggestive of tuberculosis. Elevated ADA reflects T-lymphocyte activation in TB infection	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
519	3	A medical student is asked which gastrointestinal (GIT) carcinoma is considered the most treatable (best prognosis when detected early). Which of the following is the most correct answer?	Pancreatic carcinoma	Gastric carcinoma	Colorectal carcinoma	Esophageal carcinoma	B	Gastric cancer can be considered the most treatable GIT carcinoma when detected early (early gastric cancer). Key points: Early lesions can be completely curable by surgical resection (high survival if confined to mucosa/submucosa). Prognosis is significantly better when diagnosed at early gastric cancer stage	66	2026-07-13 02:21:13.468707	\N
520	3	presents with fever, facial pain, black nasal discharge, and swelling around the eye. On examination, there is black necrotic tissue in the nasal cavity. Imaging shows sinus involvement with possible orbital extension. Which of the following organisms is most likely responsible for this condition?	Aspergillus fumigatus	Candida albicans	Mucor species	Histoplasma capsulatum	C	This is Mucormycosis. It is a rapidly progressive, angioinvasive fungal infection.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
521	3	A 6-year-old child presents with bowed legs, delayed growth, and bone pain. On examination, there is widening of the wrist joints and frontal bossing. The child has low vitamin D levels. Which of the following is the major circulating form of vitamin D used to assess vitamin D status?	1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D	7-dehydrocholesterol	25-hydroxyvitamin D	Calcitriol	C	Condition: Rickets. Clinical features: Bowed legs, Delayed growth, Bone pain, Widened wrists, Frontal bossing. Vitamin D metabolism: Skin: 7-dehydrocholesterol -> vitamin D3; Liver: converts to 25-hydroxyvitamin D (major circulating/storage form); Kidney: converts to 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D (active form). Key points: 25(OH)D is the best indicator of body vitamin D stores. 1,25(OH)2D is active but not used for status assessment.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
522	3	A pathology student is reviewing granulomatous diseases and is asked which type of necrosis is classically associated with tuberculosis infection. Which of the following is the most appropriate answer?	Liquefactive necrosis	Fat necrosis	Caseous necrosis	Coagulative necrosis	C	This is Tuberculosis. TB characteristically causes granulomatous inflammation with caseous necrosis.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
523	3	A 16-year-old boy is evaluated for delayed puberty and tall stature. On examination, he has small firm testes, sparse facial hair, gynecomastia, and infertility. Laboratory tests show low testosterone and elevated LH and FSH levels. Which of the following is the most likely karyotype?	45,XO	46,XY	47,XXY	47,XYY	C	This is Klinefelter syndrome. It results from nondisjunction leading to an extra X chromosome in males.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
524	3	A 35-year-old man presents with fever, cough, and weight loss after working in soil and bird droppings. Chest imaging suggests a fungal infection. The clinician prescribes a drug that works by inhibiting ergosterol synthesis in the fungal cell membrane. Which of the following drugs was most likely given?	Amphotericin B	Fluconazole	Itraconazole	Griseofulvin	C	Inhibits 14-α-demethylase (cytochrome P450 enzyme). Blocks ergosterol synthesis in fungal cell membrane.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
525	3	A 68-year-old man is brought to the clinic after a stroke. He is unaware of his left arm and left side of his body, and when asked, he denies any weakness. On examination, he neglects objects on the left side and ignores his left arm. Which of the following brain regions is most likely affected?	Left frontal lobe	Left parietal lobe	Right parietal lobe	Right temporal lobe	C		68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
526	3	A 22-year-old woman is prescribed an antibiotic for acne vulgaris. She is advised to avoid taking the medication with milk or antacids and to use sun protection while on therapy. Which of the following drugs is most likely prescribed?	Amoxicillin	Ciprofloxacin	Tetracycline	Azithromycin	C	Explanation: Tetracycline. Key points: Binds to 30S ribosomal subunit -> inhibits protein synthesis. Chelates calcium, iron, and magnesium -> decreased absorption with milk/antacids. Causes photosensitivity (sunburn risk). Deposits in teeth and bones -> discoloration (avoid in pregnancy/children).	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
539	3	A 35-year-old man has started treatment for pulmonary tuberculosis. After a few days, he notices that his urine, sweat, and tears have turned reddish-orange. He is also informed that this drug induces hepatic enzymes and can reduce the effectiveness of oral contraceptive pills. Which of the following drugs is most likely responsible?	Isoniazid	Ethambutol	Pyrazinamide	Rifampicin	D		70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
527	3	A physiology student is asked which transport mechanism is responsible for maintaining the resting membrane potential of cells and establishing ionic gradients across the plasma membrane. Which of the following best describes this mechanism?	Passive diffusion	Facilitated diffusion	Na+/K+ ATPase pump	Symport glucose transport	C	Sodium-potassium ATPase. Actively transports ions using ATP (primary active transport). Pumps 3 Na+ out of the cell and 2 K+ into the cell.	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
528	3	A 72-year-old woman is started on an antidepressant for major depressive disorder. After 2 weeks, she develops confusion, headache, and lethargy. Laboratory tests show low serum sodium levels. Which of the following drugs is most likely responsible for this condition?	Amitriptyline	Fluoxetine	Escitalopram	Bupropion	C	This is Escitalopram. It can cause SIADH (Syndrome of Inappropriate ADH secretion).	68	2026-07-13 02:25:28.873506	\N
529	1	A patient presents with a history associated with a central air-conditioning system. Chest X-ray shows patchy pneumonia. Laboratory tests reveal hyponatremia. Which of the following diagnostic tests is most likely to confirm the causative organism?	Blood culture	Sputum Gram stain	Urine antigen test	Cold agglutinin test	C	This is Legionnaires' disease. Caused by Legionella pneumophila, commonly found in contaminated water systems (air conditioning, hotels, showers).	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
530	1	A 29-year-old woman is undergoing chemotherapy for breast cancer. Shortly after treatment, many of her cancer cells show cell shrinkage, chromatin condensation, and formation of apoptotic bodies without inflammation. Which of the following cellular processes is most likely responsible for these changes?	Coagulative necrosis	Liquefactive necrosis	Autophagy	Apoptosis	D	This is Apoptosis\nKey points:\n• Chemotherapy commonly induces programmed cell death (apoptosis) in cancer cells\n• Characteristic features:\n  - Cell shrinkage\n  - Chromatin condensation\n  - DNA fragmentation\n  - Formation of apoptotic bodies\n  - No inflammatory response	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
531	1	A 24-year-old man presents with fever, headache, photophobia, and neck stiffness. CSF analysis shows lymphocytic pleocytosis, normal glucose, and mildly elevated protein. PCR testing of CSF is positive for a virus known to cause recurrent oral and genital lesions. Which of the following is the most likely cause of his meningitis?	Neisseria meningitidis	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Herpes simplex virus type 2	Listeria monocytogenes	C	The patient has viral meningitis caused by Herpes simplex virus type 2, which is associated with recurrent oral and genital lesions, presenting with lymphocytic pleocytosis and normal glucose levels in the CSF.	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
532	1	A 40-year-old man presents with fever, right upper quadrant pain, and tenderness over the liver. He has a history of recent travel with poor sanitation exposure. Ultrasound shows a localized hepatic lesion. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Hepatocellular carcinoma	Liver cirrhosis	Hepatic abscess	Gallstones	C	This is Liver abscess\nKey points:\n• Presents with fever + right upper quadrant pain + liver tenderness\n• Often due to:\n  - Pyogenic bacteria (e.g., E. coli, Klebsiella) or\n  - Entamoeba histolytica (ameobic abscess)\n• Imaging shows localized liver lesion\n• May show hepatomegaly and tenderness	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
533	1	A 62-year-old man has difficulty rising from a seated position and climbing stairs. On examination, he has weakness in hip extension and difficulty maintaining an upright posture when standing up from a chair. Which of the following muscles is most likely affected?	Gluteus medius	Gluteus minimus	Gluteus maximus	Iliopsoas	C	Key points:\n• Primary muscle for hip extension (especially powerful movements)\n• Important for:\n  - Rising from sitting\n  - Climbing stairs\n  - Running and jumping\n• Weakness leads to:\n  - Difficulty standing up from a chair\n  - Difficulty climbing stairs\n  - Poor posture during extension movements\n• Site of Pelvis sink - its opposite muscle will be damaged\n• Right Pelvis Sink - Left Gluteus medius + minimus Damage\n• Difficulty in standing from sitting - Gluteus maximus damage (Inferior gluteal nerve).\n• Waddling Gate - Gluteus medius and minimus damage (Superior gluteal nerve)	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
534	1	A 32-year-old man with a history of epilepsy presents for follow-up. He reports dizziness, double vision, and unsteady gait after starting a new antiepileptic medication. On examination, he has nystagmus and ataxia. Which of the following drugs is most likely responsible for these symptoms?	Phenytoin	Valproate	Lamotrigine	Levetiracetam	A	Phenytoin toxicity characteristically presents with cerebellar symptoms, including nystagmus, ataxia, diplopia (double vision), and dizziness.	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
535	1	A newborn is delivered to a 38-year-old mother. On examination, the infant has a flat facial profile, epicanthic folds, upslanting palpebral fissures, a single transverse palmar crease, and hypotonia. Which of the following chromosomal abnormalities is most likely present?	Trisomy 13	Trisomy 18	Trisomy 21	Monosomy X	C	This is Down syndrome\nCaused by trisomy 21 (47,XX+21 or 47,XY+21)\nKey clinical features:\n• Flat facial profile\n• Epicanthic folds\n• Up-slanting palpebral fissures\n• Single palmar crease\n• Hypotonia\n• Intellectual disability	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
536	1	A 30-year-old man presents with fever, headache, neck stiffness, and gradually worsening confusion over 2 weeks. CSF analysis shows lymphocytic pleocytosis, low glucose, and high protein. Imaging shows basal meningeal enhancement. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Viral meningitis	Bacterial meningitis (pneumococcal)	Tuberculous meningitis	Subarachnoid hemorrhage	C	This is Tuberculous meningitis.\nKey points:\n• Subacute/chronic progression (days to weeks)\n• CSF findings:\n  - Lymphocytic pleocytosis\n  - Low glucose\n  - High protein	69	2026-07-13 02:33:12.648075	\N
537	3	A newborn is screened for metabolic disorders shortly after birth. Later testing reveals elevated phenylalanine levels and decreased tyrosine levels. The infant is at risk for intellectual disability, musty body odor, and hypopigmentation if untreated. Which of the following enzyme deficiencies is most likely responsible?	Homocystinuria	Galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase	Phenylalanine hydroxylase	Tyrosinase	C	This is Phenylketonuria\n• Caused by deficiency of phenylalanine hydroxylase\n\nKey points:\n• Phenylalanine cannot be converted to tyrosine\n• Leads to:\n  • ↑ phenylalanine\n  • ↓ tyrosine (important for melanin synthesis)	70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
538	3	A 40-year-old man presents with neck swelling and difficulty swallowing following a deep neck infection. Imaging shows spread of infection into the "danger space" of the neck, allowing it to extend from the skull base into the mediastinum. Which of the following fascial layers is most directly involved in forming this pathway?	Superficial cervical fascia	Pretracheal fascia	Prevertebral fascia	Investing layer of deep cervical fascia	C	This is Prevertebral fascia\nKey points:\n• Encloses vertebral column and deep neck muscles\n• Extends from base of skull to upper thorax\n• Forms part of the "danger space" pathway	70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
890	3	APG Gene is	Normal gene	Tumor suppressor gene	Proto oncogen	Tumor activator gene	B		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
540	3	A 50-year-old woman presents with chronic greasy, foul-smelling stools that float in water (steatorrhea). She has a history of ileal resection due to Crohn disease. Which of the following substances is most likely deficient due to impaired enterohepatic circulation?	Gastrin	Bile salts	Secretin	Peptin	B	This is Bile salts\nKey points:\n• Bile salts are synthesized in the liver and reabsorbed in the terminal ileum\n• Ileal resection → loss of enterohepatic circulation\n• Leads to:\n  • ↓ fat emulsification\n  • ↓ micelle formation\n  • Fat malabsorption → steatorrhea	70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
541	3	A 58-year-old man is advised to increase dietary intake of vegetable oils rich in polyunsaturated fatty acids as part of lipid management therapy. After starting this dietary change, which of the following is the most likely effect associated with polyunsaturated fatty acid intake?	Increased LDL cholesterol	Increased risk of thrombosis	Decreased serum triglycerides	Increased platelet aggregation	C	Vegetable oils contain polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs)\n• PUFAs are known to have cardioprotective effects\nKey effects of PUFAs:\n• ↓ serum triglycerides\n• ↓ LDL cholesterol\n• ↑ HDL (mild or neutral effect depending on type)\n• ↓ platelet aggregation (anti-thrombotic effect)\n• ↓ atherosclerosis risk	70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
542	3	A pathology student is examining gallbladder pathology in a patient with chronic biliary colic. The gallbladder mucosa shows accumulation of crystals and stones formed due to imbalance of bile components. Which of the following is the most likely major component of gallstones?	Bilirubin	Cholesterol	Calcium oxalate	Lecithin	B	This is Gallstones\nKey points:\n• Most gallstones in developed countries are cholesterol stones\n• Formed due to supersaturation of bile with cholesterol\n• Factors favoring formation:\n  • Obesity\n  • Female sex\n  • Pregnancy\n  • Rapid weight loss\nComposition types of gallstones:\n• Cholesterol stones (most common) → yellow, radiolucent\n• Pigment stones → bilirubin (seen in hemolysis, cirrhosis)	70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
543	3	A 55-year-old man is asked to stand upright for a prolonged period during a clinical examination. After some time, his jugular venous pressure (JVP) is noted to decrease. Which of the following is the most likely physiological explanation for this finding?	Increased venous return due to muscle pump	Decreased sympathetic tone causing vasodilation	Blood pooling in lower limb veins due to gravity	Increased cardiac output	C		70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
544	3	A 40-year-old man undergoes carotid sinus massage during examination. Immediately afterward, his heart rate decreases and jugular venous pressure (JVP) increases transiently due to changes in autonomic tone. Which of the following physiological mechanisms best explains this response?	Increased sympathetic stimulation of the heart	Decreased parasympathetic tone	Increased vagal (parasympathetic) activity	Increased circulating catecholamines	C		70	2026-07-13 02:33:47.634954	\N
545	2	A 60-year-old man is evaluated for abnormal breathing patterns. During inspiration, his respiratory effort is limited and he cannot generate strong inspiratory force. Neurological examination suggests dysfunction of the respiratory control centers in the brainstem. Which of the following structures is most likely affected?	Dorsal respiratory group (DRG)	Ventral respiratory group (VRG)	Apneustic center	Pneumotaxic center	A		71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
546	2	A 50-year-old woman presents with a groin swelling below the inguinal ligament that is more prominent on coughing. Surgical exploration reveals a femoral hernia. Which of the following structures forms the posterior wall of the femoral canal?	Inguinal ligament	Lacunar ligament	Fascia lata	Pectineal ligament	D	This is Femoral canal\nKey anatomical points:\n• Anterior wall: Inguinal ligament\n• Medial wall: Lacunar ligament\n• Lateral wall: Femoral vein\n• Posterior wall: Pectineal (Cooper's) ligament	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
547	2	A 30-year-old man with severe respiratory distress following an asthma attack is observed using accessory muscles of respiration. Which of the following muscles is most likely involved in elevating the ribs to increase thoracic expansion during forced inspiration?	Serratus anterior	Serratus posterior inferior	Rectus abdominis	Internal intercostals	A	This is Serratus anterior\nKey points:\n• Acts as an accessory muscle of inspiration in respiratory distress\n• When scapula is fixed, it helps elevate ribs -> increases thoracic volume\n• Commonly recruited in severe asthma or COPD exacerbation	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
548	2	A 45-year-old woman undergoes thyroidectomy for multinodular goiter. A few days after surgery, she develops hoarseness of voice and difficulty speaking loudly. Laryngoscopy shows unilateral vocal cord paralysis. Which of the following structures is most likely injured?	Superior laryngeal nerve	Recurrent laryngeal nerve	Hypoglossal nerve	Facial nerve	B	This is Recurrent laryngeal nerve\nKey points:\n• Supplies all intrinsic muscles of the larynx except cricothyroid\n• Injury leads to:\n  - Hoarseness of voice\n  - Weak or breathy speech\n  - Vocal cord paralysis (unilateral -> hoarseness; bilateral -> airway obstruction)	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
549	2	A 35-year-old malnourished man presents with shortness of breath, bilateral pedal edema, and tachycardia. He has a history of chronic alcohol use and a diet mainly consisting of polished rice. On examination, there are signs of high-output heart failure. Which of the following vitamin deficiencies is most likely responsible for this condition?	Vitamin B2 (Riboflavin)	Vitamin B3 (Niacin)	Vitamin B1 (Thiamine)	Vitamin B6 (Pyridoxine)	C	This is Beriberi\nKey points:\n• Caused by thiamine (B1) deficiency\n• Leads to impaired carbohydrate metabolism -> ↓ ATP production\nCardiac (wet beriberi):\n• Causes high-output heart failure\n• Features:\n  - Tachycardia\n  - Cardiomegaly\n  - Peripheral edema\n  - Shortness of breath\nNeurologic (dry beriberi):\n• Peripheral neuropathy\n• Muscle weakness	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
550	2	A 25-year-old healthy man climbs a flight of stairs quickly. During this activity, his cardiac output increases. Which of the following is the most important immediate physiological mechanism responsible for this increase?	Decreased heart rate	Increased venous return	Decreased stroke volume	Increased systemic vascular resistance	B	During exercise (e.g., stair climbing), cardiac output increases mainly due to increased preload\nKey points:\n• Muscle pump + respiratory pump -> ↑ venous return\n• ↑ venous return -> ↑ end-diastolic volume -> ↑ stroke volume (Frank-Starling mechanism)\n• Leads to increased cardiac output	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
551	2	A 45-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of color changes in her fingers (white -> blue -> red), especially on exposure to cold. She is diagnosed with limited systemic sclerosis. Which of the following drugs is most appropriate for relieving her symptoms?	Propranolol	Nifedipine	Enalapril	Prednisolone	B	This is Limited systemic sclerosis\nKey points:\n• Patient has Raynaud phenomenon (digital vasospasm)\n• Triggered by cold or stress -> triphasic color changes\nTreatment:\n• Calcium channel blockers (CCBs), especially nifedipine, are first-line	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
891	3	Increase gall stone formation after hemicolectomy is due to	Impaired enterohepatic circulation	Decrease bile salts absorption	Bile are colesterol rich	Increase bilirubin production	A		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
552	2	A 60-year-old man presents with headache, dizziness, and pruritus after a hot shower. On examination, he has plethoric appearance and splenomegaly. Laboratory tests show increased hemoglobin, hematocrit, and red cell mass. Which of the following genetic mutations is most likely responsible for this condition?	BCR-ABL fusion gene	JAK2 mutation	p53 mutation	RB gene deletion	B	This is Polycythemia vera\nKey points:	71	2026-07-13 02:34:23.964792	\N
553	2	A patient presents with recurrent infections caused by catalase-positive organisms, including recurrent Salmonella infections and severe susceptibility to Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Laboratory testing shows impaired respiratory burst in neutrophils. Which of the following is the most likely underlying defect?	Myeloperoxidase deficiency	NADPH oxidase deficiency	CD4 T-cell deficiency	C3 deficiency	B	This is Chronic granulomatous disease. Key points: Caused by NADPH oxidase deficiency. Leads to failure of respiratory burst in neutrophils and macrophages.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
554	2	A pregnant woman in her third trimester presents with shortness of breath on exertion and mild fatigue. Cardiac examination shows a soft systolic murmur. Physiological cardiovascular changes of pregnancy are suspected. Which of the following hemodynamic changes is most likely seen in late pregnancy?	Decreased cardiac output	Decreased blood volume	Increased atrioventricular (AV) pressure gradient	Decreased heart rate	C	In late pregnancy, there is physiological adaptation. Key cardiovascular changes: Increased blood volume and cardiac output; Decreased systemic vascular resistance; Increased venous return (due to expanded plasma volume).	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
555	2	A 55-year-old man presents with muscle weakness and fatigue. Laboratory tests show hyperkalemia and hyponatremia. Blood pressure is low, and plasma aldosterone levels are decreased. Which of the following is the most likely underlying condition?	Primary hyperaldosteronism	Primary hypothyroidism	Addison disease (primary adrenal insufficiency)	SIADH	C	This is Addison disease. Key points: Destruction of adrenal cortex -> decreased aldosterone and decreased cortisol. Electrolyte changes: decreased aldosterone -> hyperkalemia (H+ retention), decreased aldosterone -> hyponatremia (Na+ loss). Hypotension due to volume depletion.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
556	2	A 34-year-old woman presents with fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, and constipation. Laboratory tests show low T3/T4 levels. Which of the following hormonal patterns is most likely seen in this patient?	Low TSH, low TRH	High TSH, high TRH	Low TSH, high TRH	High TSH, low TRH	B	This is Primary hypothyroidism. Key points: Thyroid gland failure -> decreased T3/T4 -> Loss of negative feedback -> hypothalamus and pituitary respond by increasing hormone release.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
557	2	A 60-year-old chronic smoker presents with persistent cough, weight loss, and chest pain. Imaging shows a central lung mass. During evaluation, the tumor is found to be invading nearby mediastinal structures including a nerve that supplies the diaphragm. This invasion results in diaphragmatic paralysis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Tuberculosis	Bronchogenic carcinoma	Pulmonary embolism	Pneumonia	B	This is Bronchogenic carcinoma. Key points: Strongly associated with smoking; Can invade mediastinal structures. Phrenic nerve involvement: Phrenic nerve (C3-C5) supplies the diaphragm; Tumor invasion -> diaphragmatic paralysis -> elevated hemidiaphragm + dyspnea.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
558	2	A 30-year-old woman presents with fatigue, recurrent infections, and easy bruising. Blood tests show pancytopenia with low reticulocyte count. Bone marrow biopsy reveals marked hypocellularity replaced by fat. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Acute leukemia	Aplastic anemia	Iron deficiency anemia	Thalassemia major	B	Aplastic anemia. Key points: Characterized by failure of bone marrow hematopoiesis. Findings: Pancytopenia (decreased RBC -> anemia/fatigue, decreased WBC -> infections, decreased platelets -> bleeding); Low reticulocyte count (low production); Bone marrow: hypocellular, replaced by fat.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
559	2	A 28-year-old pregnant woman presents with fatigue and mild pallor. Blood tests show macrocytic anemia with elevated MCV. She has a diet low in green leafy vegetables. Which of the following vitamin deficiencies is most likely responsible for her condition?	Vitamin B12	Vitamin C	Folate	Vitamin B6	C	This is Folic acid deficiency. Key points: Causes megaloblastic (macrocytic) anemia; Common in pregnancy due to increased demand; Found in green leafy vegetables, legumes, citrus fruits. Clinical features: Fatigue, pallor; Macrocytosis (increased MCV); No neurological deficits (important distinction from B12 deficiency).	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
560	2	A 40-year-old man presents with peripheral neuropathy, irritability, and seizures. He has a history of isoniazid therapy for tuberculosis. Which of the following vitamin deficiencies is most likely responsible for his symptoms?	Vitamin B1 (Thiamine)	Vitamin B2 (Riboflavin)	Vitamin B6 (Pyridoxine)		C	Isoniazid therapy causes a depletion of Vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) by inhibiting its activation and promoting its excretion, leading to peripheral neuropathy, irritability, and seizures.	72	2026-07-13 02:35:04.32331	\N
561	2	A 2-year-old child is brought to the clinic with bluish discoloration of the lips and tongue. The cyanosis is present even at rest and does not improve with warming of the extremities. Oxygen saturation is low on pulse oximetry. Which of the following best describes this condition?	Peripheral cyanosis due to vasoconstriction	Central cyanosis due to reduced arterial oxygen saturation	Methemoglobinemia due to iron oxidation	Carboxyhemoglobinemia due to CO poisoning	B	This is Central cyanosis\nKey points:\n• Involves mucous membranes (lips, tongue)\n• Caused by low arterial oxygen saturation (<85%)\n• Does NOT improve with warming\nCommon causes:\n• Congenital heart disease (right-to-left shunt)\n• Severe lung disease (COPD, pneumonia)\n• High altitude	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
562	2	A 14-year-old girl is evaluated for short stature and delayed puberty. She has a webbed neck, broad chest with widely spaced nipples, and primary amenorrhea. Laboratory tests show elevated FSH and LH with low estrogen levels. Which of the following karyotypes is most likely?	46,XX	47,XXX	45,XO	47,XXY	C	This is Turner syndrome\nKey points:\n• Caused by complete or partial loss of one X chromosome (45,XO)\nClinical features:\n• Short stature\n• Webbed neck\n• Broad chest with widely spaced nipples\n• Primary amenorrhea\n• Streak ovaries → infertility\nHormonal pattern:\n• ↑ FSH, ↑ LH (due to gonadal failure)\n• ↓ estrogen	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
563	2	A 32-year-old man presents after a stab injury to the right side of his spinal cord at the T10 level. On examination, he has ipsilateral loss of vibration, proprioception, and fine touch below the level of the lesion, and contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation below the lesion. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Central cord syndrome	Anterior spinal artery syndrome	Brown-Séquard syndrome	Posterior cord syndrome	C	Brown-Séquard syndrome\nKey points:\n• Caused by hemisection of the spinal cord (often trauma like stab injury)\nClassic pattern:\n• Ipsilateral (same side as lesion):\n  o Loss of vibration, proprioception, and fine touch (due to dorsal column damage)\n• Contralateral (opposite side):\n  o Loss of pain and temperature (due to spinothalamic tract crossing)	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
564	2	A 60-year-old man presents with loss of vibration sense, proprioception, and fine touch on the right side of his body. Pain and temperature sensations are intact. MRI shows a lesion affecting the pathway that ascends in the spinal cord and relays in the thalamus before reaching the somatosensory cortex. Which of the following pathways is most likely affected?	Spinothalamic tract	Corticospinal tract	Dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway	Spinocerebellar tract	C	This is the Dorsal column-medial lemniscus (DCML) pathway\nKey points:\n• Carries fine touch, vibration, and proprioception\n• Ascends ipsilaterally in spinal cord\n• Synapses in medulla → crosses → thalamus (VPL nucleus) → somatosensory cortex	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
565	2	A 28-year-old man falls asleep with his arm hanging over a chair ("Saturday night palsy"). On examination, he has wrist drop and inability to extend the wrist and fingers. Sensation is decreased over the dorsal aspect of the lateral hand. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?	Ulnar nerve	Median nerve	Axillary nerve	Radial nerve	D	This is Radial nerve\nKey points:\n• Common injury: compression in spiral groove of humerus (Saturday night palsy)\n• Functions:\n  o Motor: extension of wrist and fingers\n  o Sensory: posterior arm, forearm, and dorsum of lateral hand	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
566	2	A 19-year-old student complains of blurred and distorted vision at both near and far distances. He reports difficulty focusing on letters and headaches after reading for long periods. On examination, visual acuity improves with cylindrical lenses. Which of the following conditions is most likely responsible?	Myopia	Hyperopia	Astigmatism	Presbyopia	C	This is Astigmatism\nKey points:\n• Caused by irregular curvature of cornea or lens\n• Leads to unequal refraction of light in different meridians	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
567	2	A 55-year-old man with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease develops areas of poorly ventilated alveoli in the lungs. In response, blood flow is redirected away from these hypoxic regions to better-ventilated alveoli. Which of the following physiological mechanisms is responsible for this response?	Bronchodilation in hypoxic regions	Pulmonary vasodilation in hypoxic regions	Hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction	None of the above	C	Hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction is a physiological phenomenon in which small pulmonary arteries constrict in the presence of alveolar hypoxia, redirecting blood flow to alveoli with higher oxygen content.	73	2026-07-13 02:35:49.13303	\N
568	2	A 26-year-old man presents with chronic low back pain and morning stiffness that improves with exercise. He reports difficulty bending forward and reduced chest expansion. Imaging reveals bilateral sacroiliitis. Which of the following is the most strongly associated genetic marker with his condition?	HLA-DR4	HLA-B27	HLA-DQ2	HLA-B51	B	This is HLA-B27\nKey points:\n• Strongly associated with ankylosing spondylitis\n\nClassic clinical features:\n• Inflammatory back pain (worse at rest, better with exercise)\n• Morning stiffness\n• Sacroiliitis on imaging\n• Reduced spinal mobility and chest expansion	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
569	2	A 42-year-old man presents with chronic cough, weight loss, and chest X-ray shows cavitary lesions in the upper lobe and sputum is positive for acid-fast bacilli. Despite infection, his macrophages show impaired activation due to a defect in interferon-gamma signaling. Which of the following immune pathways is most likely affected?	IL-4 mediated B-cell class switching	Complement activation (C3 pathway)	IFN-γ activation of macrophages (Th1 response)	IL-10 anti-inflammatory signaling	C	This is Interferon-gamma signaling pathway\nKey points:\n• IFN-γ is produced by Th1 cells and NK cells\n• It is essential for macrophage activation and intracellular killing	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
570	2	A 65-year-old man presents with sudden onset of severe flank pain radiating to the groin. He has a history of uncontrolled hypertension that is difficult to manage with multiple drugs. Imaging reveals narrowing of the renal artery. Which of the following is the most likely underlying mechanism causing his hypertension?	Increased aldosterone due to adrenal tumor	Decreased renin secretion	Activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system	Decreased sympathetic activity	C	This is Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system\nKey points:\n• Renal artery stenosis -> ↓ renal perfusion pressure -> Kidney interprets this as hypovolemia -> releases renin\n\nCascade:\nRenin -> angiotensin I -> angiotensin II\nAngiotensin II -> vasoconstriction + aldosterone release\nAldosterone -> Na+ and water retention	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
571	2	A 45-year-old man presents with difficulty dorsiflexing and plantarflexing his foot after a lower limb injury. On examination, he has a high-stepping gait and weakness in both foot inversion and eversion. Which of the following muscle groups is most likely affected?	Gastrocnemius and soleus	Tibialis anterior and tibialis posterior	Peroneus longus and brevis	Quadriceps femoris	B	This is Tibialis anterior muscle and Tibialis posterior muscle\nKey points:\n• Tibialis anterior: dorsiflexion + inversion\n• Tibialis posterior: plantarflexion + inversion + foot arch support	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
572	2	A patient on anti-tubercular therapy develops hyperuricemia and joint pain suggestive of gout. Which of the following drugs is most likely responsible for increasing uric acid levels?	Isoniazid	Rifampicin	Ethambutol	Pyrazinamide	D		74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
573	2	A 30-year-old man is involved in a road traffic accident and sustains a neck injury at the C3-C5 level. After the injury, he is unable to breathe spontaneously and requires ventilatory support. Which of the following nerves is most likely affected, leading to diaphragmatic paralysis?	Vagus nerve	Recurrent laryngeal nerve	Phrenic nerve	Accessory nerve	C	This is Phrenic nerve\nKey points:\n• Origin: C3, C4, C5 ("C3,4,5 keep the diaphragm alive")\n• Innervates the diaphragm (main muscle of respiration)	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
574	2	A 45-year-old man develops fever, chills, back pain, and dark urine within minutes of receiving a blood transfusion. He becomes hypotensive and tachycardic. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Delayed hemolytic transfusion reaction	Febrile non-hemolytic reaction	Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction	Allergic urticarial reaction	C	This is Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction\nKey points:\n• Occurs due to ABO incompatibility\n• Mediated by IgM antibodies - complement activation - intravascular hemolysis\n\nClinical features:\n• Fever and chills\n• Back/flank pain\n• Hemoglobinuria (dark urine)\n• Hypotension, shock\n• DIC in severe cases\n\nTiming:\n• Minutes to hours after transfusion (very rapid onset)	74	2026-07-13 02:36:21.826319	\N
575	2	A 55-year-old man with hypercholesterolemia is started on a lipid-lowering drug. The medication works by inhibiting the rate-limiting step in cholesterol synthesis in the liver. Which of the following enzymes is inhibited by this drug?	Lipoprotein lipase	HMG-CoA reductase	Acetyl-CoA carboxylase	Lecithin-cholesterol acyltransferase (LCAT)	B	This is HMG-CoA reductase\nKey points:\n• This enzyme catalyzes the rate-limiting step in cholesterol biosynthesis\n• It converts HMG-CoA → mevalonate\n• Inhibited by statins (e.g., atorvastatin, simvastatin)	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
