576	2	Thyroid hormones increase body temperature and basal metabolic rate. What is the primary mechanism by which thyroxine increases energy production?	Inhibition of glycolysis	Uncoupling of oxidative phosphorylation	Decreased ATP synthesis directly	Blockade of electron transport chain	B	Hormone: Thyroxine (T4)\nMain metabolic effect:\n- Increases basal metabolic rate\n- Increases oxygen consumption\n- Increases heat production\nMechanism:\n- Stimulates mitochondrial activity\n- Uncouples oxidative phosphorylation\n- Energy from electron transport chain is released as heat instead of ATP	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
577	2	A 70-year-old man in septic shock is on mechanical ventilation with high inspired oxygen. Despite this, his arterial blood gases show that oxygen and carbon dioxide values in arterial blood are nearly identical to mixed venous blood values. Which of the following is the most likely underlying mechanism?	Increased alveolar diffusion capacity	Severe ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) mismatch with shunt physiology	Increased cardiac output	Increased hemoglobin concentration	B	This is Ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) mismatch\nKey points:\n• When arterial blood gases resemble mixed venous blood, it suggests failure of oxygenation in the lungs\n• Blood passes through lungs without adequate gas exchange (physiologic shunt)\nMechanism:\n• Alveoli are perfused but not ventilated (or severely under-ventilated)\n• Result: blood leaves lungs with little oxygen uptake and poor CO2 removal	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
578	2	A 45-year-old woman presents with weight gain, moon face, purple striae, proximal muscle weakness, and hypertension. Laboratory tests show elevated cortisol levels that do not suppress with low-dose dexamethasone. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Addison disease	Cushing syndrome	Hypothyroidism	Acromegaly	B	This is Cushing syndrome\nKey points:\n• Caused by excess cortisol (endogenous or exogenous)\nClassic clinical features:\n• Central obesity\n• Moon face\n• Buffalo hump\n• Purple striae\n• Proximal muscle weakness\n• Hypertension\n• Hyperglycemia	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
579	2	A 60-year-old man is diagnosed with a lung apex tumor. On examination, he has drooping of the eyelid on the right side, constricted pupil, and decreased sweating on the same side of the face. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Myasthenia gravis	Horner syndrome	Bell palsy	Third nerve palsy	B	This is Horner syndrome\nKey points:\n• Caused by disruption of sympathetic supply to the face\nClassic triad:\n• Ptosis (drooping eyelid)\n• Miosis (constricted pupil)\n• Anhidrosis (loss of sweating)	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
580	2	A 3-year-old child presents with edema, an enlarged fatty liver, irritability, and a distended abdomen. The child has been weaned early and is receiving a carbohydrate-rich but protein-poor diet. Which of the following is the most likely underlying deficiency?	Carbohydrate deficiency	Protein deficiency	Vitamin C deficiency	Iron deficiency	B	This is Kwashiorkor\nKey points:\n• Occurs when protein intake is severely low despite adequate calories\nClinical features:\n• Edema (↓ albumin → ↓ oncotic pressure)\n• Fatty liver (impaired lipoprotein synthesis)\n• Distended abdomen\n• Irritability and growth failure\n• "Flaky paint" dermatosis	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
581	2	A researcher studies multistep carcinogenesis. He finds that one exposure causes permanent DNA mutation, and a later exposure stimulates proliferation of these already mutated cells, increasing tumor formation. Which sequence correctly describes this process?	Promoter → Initiator	Initiator → Promoter	Promoter → Progressor	Progressor → Initiator	B	This is Carcinogenesis\nKey points:\n• Initiator comes first:\n  - Causes irreversible DNA mutation (first hit)\n• Promoter comes second:\n  - Stimulates proliferation of mutated cells\n  - Does NOT directly damage DNA	75	2026-07-13 02:36:47.325065	\N
582	11	A 62-year-old woman presents with fatigue, numbness in her hands and feet, and difficulty walking. She also has a sore tongue. Examination shows pallor, decreased vibration sense, and a smooth red tongue. Labs: low Hb, MCV 112 fL, low Vitamin B12, positive anti-intrinsic factor antibodies. What is the underlying mechanism?	Iron deficiency	Autoimmune destruction of gastric parietal cells	Folate deficiency	Thalassemia	B	Diagnosis: Pernicious anemia\n• Macrocytic anemia (↑ MCV) → impaired DNA synthesis\n• Neurological signs → vitamin B12 deficiency\n• Anti-intrinsic factor antibodies → autoimmune cause\n• Pathology: parietal cell destruction → ↓ intrinsic factor\n• ↓ B12 absorption in terminal ileum	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
583	11	A 14-year-old boy presents with recurrent episodes of severe bone pain and fatigue. He has a history of multiple hospitalizations for similar pain crises. The examination shows pallor and mild jaundice. Labs reveal low Hb, elevated reticulocyte count, and increased LDH. Peripheral smear shows sickled RBCs. What is the underlying mechanism?	Autoimmune destruction of RBCs	Decreased globin chain production	Polymerization of hemoglobin under low oxygen conditions	Iron deficiency	C	Disease: Sickle cell anemia\n• Caused by mutation in β-globin → HbS formation\n• Low O2 → HbS polymerization → RBC sickling\n• Sickled cells → rigid → vaso-occlusion (pain crises)\n• Leads to hemolysis → ↑ LDH, ↑ bilirubin, ↑ reticulocytes	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
584	11	A 45-year-old man presents with chronic sinusitis, hemoptysis, and hematuria. Chest imaging shows multiple lung nodules, and kidney biopsy reveals necrotizing granulomatous vasculitis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Goodpasture syndrome	Microscopic polyangiitis	Granulomatosis with polyangiitis	Sarcoidosis	C	Condition: Granulomatosis with polyangiitis\n• Classic triad:\n  o Upper airway: chronic sinusitis, nasal ulcers\n  o Lower airway: hemoptysis, lung nodules\n  o Kidneys: glomerulonephritis → hematuria\n• Pathology: Necrotizing granulomas + vasculitis\n• Serology: c-ANCA (PR3 positive)	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
585	11	A 20-year-old man presents with recurrent episodes of sneezing, nasal congestion, and watery eyes, especially after exposure to dust. Symptoms occur within minutes of exposure. What is the underlying immunologic mechanism?	IgG-mediated cytotoxic reaction	Immune complex deposition	T-cell mediated delayed hypersensitivity	IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation	D	Condition: Allergic rhinitis\n• Sneezing → Type I hypersensitivity reaction\n• Allergen exposure → IgE production\n• IgE binds mast cells → cross-linking on re-exposure\n• Leads to mast cell degranulation\n• Releases histamine → sneezing, itching, rhinorrhea	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
586	11	A patient presents with swelling in the floor of the mouth and pain while eating. The pain increases during meals. On examination, the swelling is located beneath the tongue. Which salivary gland is most likely involved?	Parotid gland	Sublingual gland	Submandibular gland	Minor salivary glands	C	The Submandibular gland drains via Wharton's duct\n• Duct opens in the floor of the mouth under the tongue\n• Pain during meals → suggests salivary stone (sialolithiasis)\n• Submandibular gland most commonly affected (thick, alkaline saliva)	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
640	3	A 40-year-old man presents with a chronic discharging sinus from a post-surgical wound. The discharge is thick, yellowish, and purulent. Which of the following cells is the predominant component of this pus?	Lymphocytes	Macrophages	Neutrophils	Eosinophils	C		85	2026-07-13 02:47:22.47307	\N
587	11	A 55-year-old man presents with epigastric pain that is worse at night and improves with food. He has a history of NSAID use. What is the main mediator responsible for gastric pain and mucosal inflammation in this condition?	Histamine	Gastrin	Prostaglandins	Secretin	C	Condition: Peptic ulcer disease\n• NSAIDs inhibit cyclooxygenase (COX) → ↓ prostaglandins\n• Prostaglandins normally:\n  o Protect gastric mucosa\n  o Increase mucus and bicarbonate secretion\n  o Maintain mucosal blood flow\n• ↓ Prostaglandins → mucosal injury + pain	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
588	11	A patient undergoes colectomy. What is the main physiological consequence?	Protein malabsorption	Loss of electrolytes	Vitamin B12 deficiency	Fat malabsorption	B	The Colon normally:\n  o Absorbs water and electrolytes (Na+, Cl-)\n  o Concentrates stool\nAfter removal:\n  o ↓ Na+ and water absorption → electrolyte loss + dehydration\n• Other nutrients (protein, fat, iron, B12) are absorbed in small intestine, not colon	77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
589	11	A 28-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus presents with hematuria, proteinuria, and hypertension. Urinalysis shows RBC casts. Renal biopsy reveals focal segmental involvement of fewer than 50% of glomeruli with subendothelial immune complex deposition. What is the diagnosis?					 		77	2026-07-13 02:43:06.093947	\N
590	3	A patient presents with generalized anxiety, restlessness, and insomnia. Which neurotransmitter system is primarily involved in reducing neuronal excitability and is commonly targeted by anxiolytic drugs?	Dopamine	Serotonin	GABA	Acetlycholine	C	Anxiety is associated with reduced inhibitory control in the CNS. Main inhibitory neurotransmitter: GABA (γ-aminobutyric acid). GABA acts via GABA-A receptors -> increases Cl- influx -> neuronal hyperpolarization. Decreased GABA activity -> increased neuronal excitability -> anxiety, insomnia.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
591	3	A 55-year-old chronic smoker presents with a persistent cough. Bronchoscopy shows that the normal ciliated columnar epithelium of the bronchus has been replaced by stratified squamous epithelium. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Dysplasia	Metaplasia	Hyperplasia	Neoplasia	B	Condition: Metaplasia. Chronic irritation (smoking) adaptive cellular change. Normal bronchial epithelium columnar -> Replacement: stratified squamous epithelium (more resistant to...). Key features: Reversible adaptation. Protective response to chronic irritation. Loss of specialized function (mucociliary clearance).	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
592	3	A 30-year-old man presents with vomiting and dehydration. Arterial blood gas shows: pH 7.34, HCO3- 18 mEq/L, and PaCO2 32 mmHg. What is the most likely acid-base disorder?	Uncompensated metabolic acidosis	Compensated metabolic acidosis	Uncompensated respiratory acidosis	Compensated respiratory alkalosis	B	Condition: Metabolic acidosis. Key findings: Decreased pH (slightly low/near normal), Decreased HCO3- -> primary metabolic acidosis, Decreased PaCO2 -> respiratory compensation (hyperventilation). Compensation: Lungs blow off CO2 to correct acidosis.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
593	3	A patient's respiratory parameters are measured. The total ventilation is 5000 mL/min. If the tidal volume is 500 mL and dead space is 150 mL, what is the alveolar ventilation per minute?	1750 mL/min	2500 mL/min	3500 mL/min	5000 mL/min	C	Alveolar ventilation formula: Alveolar ventilation = (Tidal volume - Dead space) x Respiratory rate. Given: Tidal volume = 500 mL, Dead space = 150 mL. Respiratory rate = 5000 / 500 = 10 breaths/min. Calculation: (500 - 150) x 10 = 350 x 10 = 3500 mL/min.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
594	3	A 65-year-old man presents with sudden onset blurred vision. He has no ocular abnormalities on eye examination. Neurological examination suggests a cortical lesion. Which part of the brain is most likely affected?	Frontal cortex	Parietal cortex	Temporal cortex	Occipital cortex	D	Vision is processed in the Occipital cortex. Lesion in this area causes: Blurred vision, Visual field defects, Cortical blindness (in severe cases). Eye exam remains normal because the problem is central (brain), not ocular.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
595	3	During cardiac cycle, at what left ventricular pressure does the aortic valve open?	0 mmHg	5 mmHg	40 mmHg	80 mmHg	D	The Aortic valve opens when: Left ventricular pressure exceeds aortic diastolic pressure. Aortic diastolic pressure ≈ 80 mmHg. Therefore, valve opens when LV pressure just exceeds ~80 mmHg. This occurs during isovolumetric contraction phase -> ejection phase transition.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
596	3	A patient with asthma is started on theophylline for bronchodilation. Which enzyme is inhibited by this drug to increase intracellular cAMP?	Cyclooxygenase	Phosphodiesterase	Acetylcholinesterase	Tyrosine kinase	B	Drug: Theophylline. Mechanism: Inhibits phosphodiesterase (mainly PDE4 in airway smooth muscle). Prevents breakdown of cAMP -> Increased cAMP. Leads to bronchodilation. Also: Mild adenosine receptor antagonism, which leads to increased cAMP -> smooth muscle relaxation in bronchi.	78	2026-07-13 02:43:42.873263	\N
597	2	A 45-year-old man presents with loss of vibration sense and impaired joint position sense in both lower limbs. He also has difficulty maintaining balance with eyes closed (positive Romberg sign). Which pathway is most likely affected?	Spinothalamic tract	Corticospinal tract	Dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway	Spinocerebellar tract	C	Pathway: Dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway\nCarries:\n- Vibration sense\n- Fine touch\n- Conscious proprioception\nClinical features when affected:\n- Loss of vibration side\n- Loss of joint position sense\n- Positive Romberg sign (sensory ataxia)\nReason:\n- Sensory input from lower limbs is not reaching brain via DCML\nOther tracts:\n- Spinothalamic -> pain & temperature\n- Spinocerebellar -> unconscious proprioception (no Romberg sign)\n- Corticospinal -> motor weakness	79	2026-07-13 02:44:05.222794	\N
598	2	A 50-year-old chronic alcoholic presents with unsteady gait, difficulty maintaining balance, and truncal swaying while walking. On examination, limb coordination is relatively preserved, but there is marked difficulty in sitting and standing upright. Which part of the cerebellum is most likely affected?	Flocculonodular lobe	Cerebellar hemisphere	Vermis	Cerebellar peduncle	C	Condition involves Cerebellar vermis\nVermis controls:\n- Truncal stability\n- Posture\n- Gait coordination\nLesion (common in chronic alcoholism) leads to:\n- Truncal ataxia\n- Wide-based gait\n- Difficulty sitting/standing without support	79	2026-07-13 02:44:05.222794	\N
599	2	A 28-year-old woman presents with drooping of eyelids that worsens throughout the day and improves with rest. She also reports difficulty chewing after prolonged talking. On examination, muscle strength fatigues with repeated use. Which of the following is the underlying mechanism?	Demyelination of peripheral nerves	Autoimmune destruction of presynaptic acetylcholine release	Autoimmune antibodies against postsynaptic acetylcholine receptors	Increased acetylcholine breakdown	C	Condition: Myasthenia gravis\nMechanism:\n- IgG antibodies target postsynaptic acetylcholine receptors (AChR)\n- Leads to decreased neuromuscular transmission\nClinical features:\n- Fluctuating muscle weakness\n- Worsens with activity, improves with rest\n- Ptosis and diplopia common	79	2026-07-13 02:44:05.222794	\N
