648	3	A 55-year-old man with liver cirrhosis presents with confusion, asterixis, and disorientation. He is diagnosed with hepatic encephalopathy. Which of the following is the first-line treatment to reduce ammonia levels?	Neomycin	Lactulose	Rifaximin	Metronidazole	B	Condition: Hepatic encephalopathy\nFirst-line drug:\n- Lactulose\nMechanism:\n- Converts ammonia (NH3) -> ammonium (NH4+) in gut\n- NH4+ is non-absorbable -> excreted in stool\n- Also acts as a cathartic -> decreases gut ammonia production	86	2026-07-13 02:47:59.058322	\N
649	3	A 68-year-old man suddenly develops right-sided weakness and difficulty recognizing objects placed in his left hand. MRI shows an infarct in the parietal cortex. Which of the following is the most likely site of the lesion?	Left frontal cortex	Right parietal cortex	Left temporal lobe	Cerebellum	B	Condition: Cerebral infarction\nParietal cortex functions:\n- Sensory integration\n- Spatial awareness\n- Object recognition (stereognosis)\nRight parietal lobe lesion causes:\n- Left-sided weakness (contralateral motor deficit via adjacent pathways)\n- Left-sided sensory/spatial neglect\n- Astereognosis (cannot recognize objects by touch in left hand)	86	2026-07-13 02:47:59.058322	\N
650	3	A 25-year-old medical student is very angry after being scolded by his professor for poor performance. Instead of expressing anger toward the professor, he goes home and argues aggressively with his younger sibling over a minor issue. Which defense mechanism is most likely being used?	Projection	Sublimation	Displacement	Reaction formation	C	Mechanism: Displacement\nIn this scenario:\n- True source of anger: professor\n- Actual expression of anger: younger sibling (safer target)\nKey feature:\n- Emotional shift from dangerous/authority figure -> safer person/object	86	2026-07-13 02:47:59.058322	\N
651	13	A tumor cell divides how many times before becoming clinically detectable?	10	20	30	40	C	Tumor growth follows Exponential growth, starting from a single malignant cell. After about 30 divisions, the tumor reaches approximately 10^9 cells (~1 cm), which is the minimum size for clinical detection. Fewer divisions (10-20) produce too few cells to detect, while around 40 divisions correspond to a much larger, often life-threatening tumor burden.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
652	13	A patient presents with proximal muscle weakness that improves with repeated use, along with dry mouth and autonomic symptoms. Imaging reveals a lung mass. This condition is most commonly associated with which type of lung cancer?	Adenocarcinoma	Squamous cell carcinoma	Large cell carcinoma	Small cell carcinoma	D	Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome is a paraneoplastic disorder caused by antibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated Ca2+ channels. Leads to ↓ acetylcholine release at neuromuscular junction. Muscle weakness improves with repeated use (facilitation). Associated autonomic symptoms: dry mouth, impotence. Strongly associated with Small cell lung carcinoma. Small cell carcinoma is a neuroendocrine tumor commonly causes paraneoplastic syndromes.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
690	3	A 7-year-old child presents with high-grade fever, sore throat, and "strawberry tongue" on examination. Which is the most likely causative organism?	Staphylococcus aureus	Streptococcus pyogenes	Streptococcus pneumoniae	Corynebacterium diphtheriae	B	This is Scarlet fever. Classic features: High fever, Sore throat (pharyngitis), Strawberry tongue, Sandpaper-like rash.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
653	13	A 55-year-old patient underwent pelvic radiation therapy and is now unable to achieve erection. The problem is most likely due to damage to which of the following?	Pudendal nerve	Sympathetic fibers	Parasympathetic fibers	Somatic motor fibers	C	Erection is mediated by parasympathetic fibers (S2-S4). These fibers release nitric oxide -> vasodilation of penile arteries. Radiation damages pelvic autonomic nerves -> affects parasympathetic supply. Leads to erectile dysfunction (failure to achieve erection). Sympathetic fibers are responsible for ejaculation, not erection. Age is not essential in this question because the mechanism depends on nerve damage, not age-related physiology; radiation history is the key clue.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
654	13	A 60-year-old patient with long-standing hypertension is found to have an enlarged left ventricle. This enlargement is due to which of the following?	Hyperplasia	Hypertrophy	Metaplasia	Dysplasia	B	In Hypertension, the heart pumps against increased resistance (afterload). Cardiac muscle cells cannot divide -> no hyperplasia. Instead, individual cell size -> hypertrophy -> left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH). This is an adaptive response to increased workload. Hyperplasia occurs in tissues with dividing cells, not cardiac muscle.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
655	13	A 45-year-old chronic smoker presents with a persistent cough. Bronchoscopy shows replacement of normal ciliated columnar epithelium of the bronchus with stratified squamous epithelium. This change is best described as which of the following?	Hyperplasia	Hypertrophy	Metaplasia	Dysplasia	C	This is a classic example of Metaplasia. Chronic irritation (smoking) causes replacement of fragile ciliated columnar epithelium. It is replaced by tougher stratified squamous epithelium to withstand stress. This is an adaptive and potentially reversible change if the irritant is removed. It is not cancer, but long-standing metaplasia can increase risk of dysplasia and carcinoma.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
656	13	A 50-year-old man with long-standing GERD undergoes endoscopy. Biopsy from the lower esophagus shows replacement of normal squamous epithelium with intestinal-type columnar epithelium containing goblet cells. This change is best described as which of the following?	Stratified squamous epithelium	Simple columnar epithelium without...	[Incomplete]	[Incomplete]	D	This is Barrett esophagus. Chronic acid exposure from Gastroesophageal reflux disease damages normal epithelium. Normal stratified squamous epithelium is replaced by intestinal-type columnar epithelium with goblet cells. This is a type of Metaplasia. Goblet cells indicate intestinal differentiation and increased risk of adenocarcinoma.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
657	13	A 52-year-old woman suddenly develops the "worst headache of her life" while watching TV. She also has nausea, vomiting, and neck stiffness. CT scan shows bleeding in the subarachnoid space. The most likely cause is rupture of which structure?	Charcot-Bouchard microaneurysm	Berry aneurysm	Atherosclerotic plaque	Arteriovenous malformation of dura	B	This is a classic presentation of Subarachnoid hemorrhage. Key symptom: sudden severe "thunderclap" headache. Often associated with meningeal irritation -> neck stiffness, photophobia. Most common cause: rupture of a Berry aneurysm. Berry aneurysms occur at circle of Willis bifurcations.	87	2026-07-13 02:48:59.556004	\N
658	2	A patient presents with a sudden severe "worst headache of life" and CT scan confirms subarachnoid hemorrhage. Which of the following is the most appropriate drug to give to prevent complications?	Ceftriaxone	Beta blocker	Nimodipine	Mannitol	C	This is Subarachnoid hemorrhage. Major complication after SAH is cerebral vasospasm -> delayed ischemia. Drug of choice to prevent vasospasm: Nimodipine. Mechanism: blocks calcium influx in vascular smooth muscle -> prevents vasoconstriction. Ceftriaxone -> used for bacterial meningitis, not SAH. Beta blockers -> used in hypertension, not acute SAH management. Mannitol -> used for raised intracranial pressure, but not primary preventive therapy for vasospasm.	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
659	2	A 48-year-old man with a history of chronic liver disease presents with massive hematemesis after vomiting. Endoscopy confirms bleeding esophageal varices. What is the most appropriate initial drug for management?	Omeprazole	Ceftriaxone	Octreotide	Propranolol	C	This is Esophageal varices due to portal hypertension. Acute variceal bleeding is a medical emergency. First-line pharmacologic therapy: Octreotide. Mechanism: causes splanchnic vasoconstriction -> portal venous inflow -> bleeding. Ceftriaxone -> given as prophylaxis against infection in cirrhotics, but not primary acute hemostatic drug. Omeprazole -> used in peptic ulcer bleeding, not varices.	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
660	2	Which receptors are primarily responsible for increasing arteriolar constriction?	β1 adrenergic receptors	β2 adrenergic receptors	α1 adrenergic receptors	M2 muscarinic receptors	C	Arteriolar vasoconstriction is mainly mediated by Alpha-1 adrenergic receptor signaling. Activation of α1 receptors (by norepinephrine) causes: Contraction of vascular smooth muscle, ↑ peripheral vascular resistance. β1 receptors mainly affect heart (↑ heart rate and contractility). β2 receptors cause vasodilation (especially in skeletal muscle). M2 receptors act on heart (↓ heart rate).	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
661	2	A 30-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a road traffic accident. He has a deep laceration in his thigh. On examination, there is continuous dark red, non-pulsatile bleeding that is difficult to notice at first but gradually leads to significant blood loss over time. Which vessel is most likely injured causing the maximum total blood loss if not controlled?	Artery	Vein	Venule	Capillary	B	This is injury to a vein causing Venous bleeding. Venous bleeding characteristics: Dark red blood, Non-pulsatile flow, Continuous oozing. Veins act as capacitance vessels, containing the largest blood volume in the body. Because bleeding is less dramatic than arterial bleeding, it may go unnoticed longer -> greater total blood loss over time.	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
662	2	In Hodgkin lymphoma, which subtype is associated with poor prognosis?	Lymphocyte-rich	Nodular sclerosis	Mixed cellularity	Lymphocyte-depleted	D	This is Hodgkin lymphoma. Prognosis depends on histologic subtype and immune background. Lymphocyte-depleted subtype has the worst prognosis because: Very few normal reactive lymphocytes, High number of Reed-Sternberg cells, Often associated with advanced disease and immunosuppression (e.g., HIV). Lymphocyte-rich subtype has better prognosis. General trend: Lymphocyte-rich -> best prognosis, Nodular sclerosis -> most common, intermediate prognosis, Mixed cellularity -> intermediate, Lymphocyte-depleted -> worst prognosis. So, lymphocyte depletion = poor immune response = poor prognosis.	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
663	2	A 28-year-old man has recently moved from sea level to a mountainous region at high altitude. After a few weeks, he reports mild fatigue but is otherwise healthy. Laboratory tests show increased red blood cell count and elevated hemoglobin levels. Which of the following best explains this adaptation?	Decreased erythropoietin due to hypoxia	Increased erythropoietin production due to hypoxia	Decreased oxygen affinity of hemoglobin due to CO exposure	Bone marrow suppression due to hypoxia	B	This is a physiological response to chronic hypoxia at high altitude. Low oxygen stimulates renal peritubular cells to release erythropoietin (EPO).	88	2026-07-13 03:00:39.261182	\N
664	2	A patient with severe kyphoscoliosis presents with chronic shortness of breath. Arterial blood gas analysis is most likely to show which of the following?	Decreased PaCO2 and increased pH	Increased PaCO2 and decreased pH	Decreased PaCO2 and decreased pH	Increased PaCO2 and increased pH	B	Kyphoscoliosis causes restrictive lung disease due to impaired chest wall expansion. This leads to alveolar hypoventilation. Resulting effects: CO2 retention -> ↑ PaCO2. Respiratory acidosis -> ↓ pH. This condition is a type of Chronic respiratory acidosis. Kidneys may partially compensate by retaining bicarbonate in chronic cases.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
665	2	A 30-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after smoke inhalation in a closed-room fire. He is confused and has a headache. Arterial blood gas shows normal PaO2, normal PaCO2, and normal pH, but tissue hypoxia is suspected. Which of the following best explains the physiological finding?	Decreased arterial oxygen content due to hemoglobin binding	Increased PaCO2 due to hypoventilation	Increased arterial oxygen tension with normal oxygen delivery	Increased oxygen unloading to tissues due to left shift of curve	A	This is Carbon monoxide poisoning. CO binds hemoglobin with very high affinity -> forms carboxyhemoglobin. Key effects:\n- Normal PaO2 (oxygen dissolved in plasma is unchanged)\n- Normal SaO2, and pH initially\n- Markedly reduced oxygen content of blood (↓ O2 bound to Hb). This causes tissue hypoxia despite normal arterial oxygen tension.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
666	2	People living at high altitude have increased respiratory rate as an adaptive response. What acid-base disturbance is most likely seen initially?	Metabolic acidosis	Metabolic alkalosis	Respiratory acidosis	Respiratory alkalosis	D	At high altitude, there is low atmospheric oxygen -> hypoxia. This stimulates hyperventilation (↑ respiratory rate). Hyperventilation causes excessive CO2 loss. ↓ CO2 leads to ↓ carbonic acid -> ↑ pH. This results in Respiratory alkalosis.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
667	2	A 32 year old patient has the following arterial blood gas results: PaCO2 = 35 mmHg, HCO3- = 15 mEq/L. What is the most likely acid-base disturbance?	Respiratory acidosis	Respiratory alkalosis	Metabolic acidosis	Metabolic alkalosis	C	This pattern is consistent with Metabolic acidosis. Key findings:\n- Low HCO3- (15 mEq/L) -> primary problem is metabolic loss of bicarbonate or acid gain\n- PaCO2 = 35 mmHg -> slightly low/normal, suggesting respiratory compensation (hyperventilation) to blow off CO2 to reduce acidity.\nCompensation: Since bicarbonate is primarily decreased -> this is metabolic acidosis with partial respiratory compensation.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
668	2	A deep-sea diver surfaces rapidly after a long dive and develops severe joint pain, dizziness, and shortness of breath. What is the underlying cause of this condition?	Oxygen toxicity	Carbon dioxide poisoning	Nitrogen gas bubble formation in tissues	Decreased helium solubility in blood	C	This is Decompression sickness. At high pressure underwater, nitrogen dissolves in blood and tissues. Rapid ascent -> sudden drop in pressure. Dissolved nitrogen comes out of solution forming gas bubbles. These nitrogen bubbles block blood vessels -> ischemia, and irritate joints -> severe joint pain ("the bends").	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
669	2	A 52-year-old obese man is diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus after routine screening. He has no symptoms of hyperglycemia and all baseline investigations including renal function, liver function, and vitamin B12 are normal. Which of the following describes the mechanism of action of the most appropriate first-line drug for this patient?	Increases insulin secretion from pancreas	Increases glucagon release	Decreases hepatic gluconeogenesis and improves insulin sensitivity	Blocks intestinal glucose absorption by inhibiting SGLT-2	C	This is Type 2 diabetes mellitus. First-line drug: Metformin.\nMechanism of action:\n- ↓ hepatic gluconeogenesis (main effect)\n- ↑ peripheral insulin sensitivity\n- ↑ glucose uptake in muscle\nAdvantages in this patient: Weight neutral or mild weight loss; No risk of hypoglycemia when used alone.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
670	2	A known diabetic patient presents to the emergency department with sweating, confusion, tremors, and blood glucose of 35 mg/dL after starting a new anti-diabetic medication. Which drug is most likely responsible?	Metformin	Sulfonylurea	Acarbose	Pioglitazone	B	This is Hypoglycemia. Symptoms (sweating, tremors, confusion) indicate adrenergic + neuroglycopenic effects. Most likely drug cause: Sulfonylurea.\nMechanism: Stimulates pancreatic β-cells -> ↑ insulin release (regardless of glucose level). Can cause profound hypoglycemia, especially in elderly.	89	2026-07-13 03:01:16.152083	\N
671	14	A 28-year-old woman presents with amenorrhea for 6 weeks and a positive urine pregnancy test. Serum β-hCG is elevated. She is concerned about what this hormone is doing in her body at this stage. What is the primary function of hCG in early pregnancy?	Causes degeneration of corpus luteum	Stimulates ovulation	Maintains corpus luteum and progesterone secretion	Initiates menstruation	C	This is Human chorionic gonadotropin. In early pregnancy, hCG is produced by trophoblast cells. It "rescues" the corpus luteum from degeneration. Maintains corpus luteum function → continued progesterone secretion.	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
672	14	Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is produced from which of the following structures?	Corpus luteum	Maternal endometrium	Syncytiotrophoblast	Cytotrophoblast	C	This is Human chorionic gonadotropin. Produced by the syncytiotrophoblast cells of the placenta. These cells are part of the outer trophoblastic layer of the developing embryo. Function of hCG: Maintains corpus luteum, Supports progesterone secretion in early pregnancy.	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
673	14	A 22-year-old sexually active male presents with urethral discharge. Gram stain shows intracellular Gram-negative diplococci suggestive of Neisseria gonorrhoeae. The physician is concerned about poor patient compliance. Which is the best treatment option?	Oral doxycycline for 7 days	Oral azithromycin single dose alone	Single-dose intramuscular ceftriaxone	Oral ciprofloxacin for 5 days	C	This is Gonorrhea. Organism: intracellular Gram-negative diplococci. Key concern: poor compliance in STI treatment. Best option: Ceftriaxone. Given as single intramuscular dose → ensures compliance. Often also co-treated for possible Chlamydia (e.g., doxycycline if not excluded).	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
674	14	A 24-year-old sexually active patient presents with urethritis and dysuria. Laboratory testing identifies a facultative intracellular organism. Which is the most likely causative organism?	Neisseria gonorrhoeae	Chlamydia trachomatis	Treponema pallidum	Trichomonas vaginalis	B	This is Chlamydia trachomatis infection. Key point: facultative intracellular organism. It has two forms: Elementary body (infectious form), Reticulate body (replicative form inside cells). Causes: Urethritis, Cervicitis, PID.	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
675	14	Which is the most abundant immunoglobulin in human serum?	IgA	IgM	IgG	IgE	C	This is Immunoglobulin G. IgG is the most abundant immunoglobulin in blood (~75%).	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
818	3	Protooncogenes are:	Normal genes for DNA	Normal genes controlling cell growth	Abnormal DNA	Functional genes	B		110	2026-07-14 23:53:31.077992	\N
819	3	Which one is the feature of Neurofibromatosis 1	Glial nodule	Bilateral vestibular nerve schwannoma.	Cafe au lait spot	Fibrosis	C		110	2026-07-14 23:53:31.077992	\N
677	14	A pregnant woman is Rh-negative, and her partner is Rh-positive. What is the appropriate prophylactic management during pregnancy?	Anti-D immunoglobulin	Rho(D) antigen vaccine	Maternal IgG infusion	No treatment needed	A	This is Rh incompatibility. When Rh-negative mother carries an Rh-positive fetus, fetal RBCs may enter maternal circulation. This can trigger maternal anti-D antibody formation → risk in future pregnancies (hemolytic disease of newborn). Prevention: Rho(D) immune globulin. Mechanism: Binds fetal Rh-positive RBCs in maternal blood. Prevents maternal immune sensitization.	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
678	14	A 10-year-old child presents with fatigue, jaundice, and intermittent episodes of dark urine. Physical examination reveals splenomegaly. Peripheral blood smear shows numerous spherocytes without central pallor. Which of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test to confirm the underlying condition?	Direct Coombs test	Osmotic fragility test	Ham test	Hemoglobin electrophoresis	B	This is Hereditary spherocytosis. Clinical features: Hemolytic anemia (fatigue, jaundice), Splenomegaly due to RBC destruction. Peripheral smear finding: spherocytes (no central pallor). Pathophysiology: Defect in RBC membrane proteins (spectrin/ankyrin) → decreased surface area. RBCs become spherical → trapped and destroyed in spleen.	90	2026-07-13 03:01:51.987556	\N
679	15	... maternal infection or structural uterine abnormality. What is the most appropriate investigation to determine a genetic cause?	Western blot	Southern blot	Karyotyping	ELISA	C	Recurrent miscarriages suggest possible Recurrent pregnancy loss. One important cause is chromosomal abnormalities in either parent (balanced translocation, inversion). Best initial genetic test: Karyotyping	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
680	15	Which neurotransmitter is primarily involved in signaling from the globus pallidus back to the corpus striatum in the basal ganglia circuit?	Dopamine	Acetylcholine	GABA	Glutamate	C	The Corpus striatum and globus pallidus are part of a feedback loop. The globus pallidus (especially internal segment) sends inhibitory output using GABAergic transmission. Basal ganglia pathways are predominantly inhibitory circuits using GABA. Dopamine acts from substantia nigra to striatum (modulatory, not direct GP -> striatum transmission). Acetylcholine acts mainly within the striatum as interneurons.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
681	15	A 26-year-old patient presents with fever for 4 days, positive dengue NS1 antigen, and currently has abdominal pain and mild ascites on ultrasound. Which of the following clinical findings would be indication for hospital admission in dengue infection?	Mild fever with body ache	Positive NS1 antigen only	Positive shifting dullness on abdominal exam	Mild headache without warning sign	C	This is Dengue fever. Admission is required when warning signs or plasma leakage appear. Shifting dullness indicates ascites -> plasma leakage. This is a warning sign of severe dengue progression.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
682	15	A 55-year-old male with chronic liver disease (CLD) presents with ascites and pedal edema. What is the most likely change in plasma oncotic pressure?	Increased oncotic pressure	Normal oncotic pressure	Decreased oncotic pressure	No change in oncotic pressure	C	This is Chronic liver disease. Liver is responsible for albumin synthesis. In CLD -> ↓ albumin production -> ↓ plasma oncotic pressure. Low oncotic pressure causes: Fluid leakage into tissues -> pedal edema, Fluid accumulation in peritoneal cavity -> ascites.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
683	15	A 10-year-old child presents with a history of sore throat 2-3 weeks ago. Now he has periorbital puffiness and protein in urine. Which organism is most likely responsible for this condition?	Streptococcus group A	Streptococcus group B	Staphylococcus aureus	Escherichia coli	A	This is Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Typical history: Recent sore throat or skin infection. Latent period of 1-3 weeks. Clinical features: Edema (periorbital puffiness), Proteinuria ± hematuria.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
684	15	A 30-year-old patient presents to the emergency department with palpitations and dizziness. ECG shows an irregular rhythm with no distinct P waves and a varying ventricular response. The most likely site of the underlying problem is which of the following?	Left bundle branch	Right bundle branch	Bundle of His	Bundle of Kent	D	This is Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. Key ECG clue in accessory pathway tachycardia: Irregular rhythm with rapid conduction. Due to re-entry circuits. Mechanism: Bundle of Kent = accessory pathway between atria and ventricles -> Bypasses AV node -> abnormal conduction -> arrhythmias.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
685	15	A 60-year-old man is diagnosed with pulmonary hypertension. What is the most likely right ventricular systolic pressure in this condition?	5 mmHg	10 mmHg	15-25 mmHg	25-60 mmHg	D	This is Pulmonary hypertension. Normal right ventricular systolic pressure = 15-25 mmHg. In pulmonary hypertension: ↑ pulmonary vascular resistance -> Right ventricle works harder against increased afterload -> This leads to increased right ventricular systolic pressure. Mild-moderate cases: 25-60 mmHg	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
686	15	A 58-year-old man presents with crushing chest pain. ECG shows ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF. Which wall of the heart is affected?	Anterior wall	Inferior wall	Lateral wall	Posterior wall	B	This is Inferior myocardial infarction. ECG lead correlation: II, III, aVF -> inferior surface of heart. Inferior wall is mainly supplied by the right coronary artery (RCA). So ST elevation in these leads indicates inferior wall myocardial infarction.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
687	15	A child presents with continuous "machine-like" murmur heard best in the left infraclavicular area with bounding pulses and wide pulse pressure. Which condition is most likely?	Ventricular septal defect	Atrial septal defect	Patent ductus arteriosus	Tetralogy of Fallot	C	This is Patent ductus arteriosus. Classic clinical features.	91	2026-07-13 03:02:17.629266	\N
688	3	The kidney maintains a relatively constant glomerular filtration rate (GFR) despite changes in systemic blood pressure. Which mechanism is primarily responsible for this autoregulation?	Tubuloglomerular feedback and myogenic mechanism	Renin-angiotensin system only	Sympathetic nervous system only	Atrial natriuretic peptide only	A	This is Renal autoregulation. Kidney autoregulation works mainly by two mechanisms: Myogenic mechanism: Afferent arteriole constricts when stretched (↑ BP), Dilates when BP falls. Tubuloglomerular feedback (glomerulotubular feedback): Macula densa senses NaCl delivery in distal tubule, Adjusts afferent arteriole tone accordingly.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
689	3	Activation of the renin-angiotensin system causes arteriolar constriction mainly due to which substance?	Renin	Angiotensin I	Angiotensin II	Aldosterone	C	This is Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. Key step: Renin is an enzyme released from juxtaglomerular cells -> It converts angiotensinogen -> angiotensin I. Then ACE converts angiotensin I -> angiotensin II. Angiotensin II is the main active hormone causing: Powerful arteriolar vasoconstriction -> ↑ blood pressure.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
894	3	A patient with cirrhosis and portal hypertension presents with prominent abdominal veins and hematemesis. Which vessels are involved?	Superior mesenteric vein - Inferior vena cava	Left gastric vein - Esophageal veins	Splenic vein - Renal vein	Portal vein - Hepatic vein	B		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
691	3	A patient develops prolonged muscle paralysis and apnea after receiving succinylcholine for intubation. Which enzyme deficiency is most likely responsible for this delayed effect?	Acetylcholinesterase	Pseudocholinesterase (butyrylcholinesterase)	Glucuronyl transferase	Monoamine oxidase	B	This is Succinylcholine Pseudocholinesterase. Normally, succinylcholine is rapidly broken down in plasma by pseudocholinesterase (butyrylcholinesterase). Deficiency of this enzyme leads to: Prolonged action of drug -> Extended muscle paralysis -> Delayed recovery from anesthesia.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
692	3	A 40-year-old patient presents with episodic headaches, sweating, palpitations, and severe hypertension. Laboratory findings suggest pheochromocytoma. These tumor cells arise from which of the following?	Adrenal cortex	Chromaffin cells of adrenal medulla	Juxtaglomerular cells	Parafollicular (C) cells of thyroid	B	This is Pheochromocytoma. Origin: chromaffin cells of adrenal medulla. These cells are derived from neural crest and produce: Epinephrine, Norepinephrine. Clinical features ("rule of 10s"): Episodic hypertension, Headache, sweating, palpitations.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
693	3	Itraconazole is an antifungal drug. What is its mechanism of action?	Inhibits fungal cell wall synthesis	Binds ergosterol and forms pores in membrane	Inhibits squalene epoxidase	Inhibits 14-a-demethylase (cytochrome P450 enzyme)	D	This is Itraconazole. Mechanism: Inhibits fungal cytochrome P450 enzyme (14-a-demethylase) -> Blocks conversion of lanosterol -> ergosterol. Result: ↓ ergosterol synthesis -> defective fungal cell membrane -> Increased membrane permeability -> fungal cell death/inhibition.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
694	3	A 23-year-old woman presents with fever, facial rash, and joint pain involving multiple small joints. She also reports fatigue and photosensitivity. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Rheumatoid arthritis	Systemic lupus erythematosus	Osteoarthritis	Gout	B	This is Systemic lupus erythematosus. Key clinical features: Fever, Malar ("butterfly") rash, Symmetrical polyarthritis (joint pain), Photosensitivity.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
695	3	A 25-year-old man sustains a fracture at the neck of the fibula after a road traffic accident. He develops foot drop and loss of dorsiflexion of the foot. Which nerve is most likely injured?	Tibial nerve	Common peroneal nerve	Femoral nerve	Obturator nerve	B	This is Common peroneal nerve. The nerve winds around the neck of fibula, making it highly vulnerable in fractures. Injury leads to: Foot drop (loss of dorsiflexion), Sensory loss over lateral leg and dorsum of foot.	92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
696	3	A 28-year-old woman presents with a painless, cystic swelling at the posterolateral aspect of the vaginal opening (labia majora area). What is the most likely diagnosis?	Skene's gland cyst	Bartholin cyst	Gartner duct cyst	Epidermoid cyst	 		92	2026-07-13 03:02:42.383314	\N
697	3	A patient presents with cardiac tamponade and requires emergency pericardiocentesis. Which is the safest anatomical site for needle insertion?	Left 2nd intercostal space, midclavicular line	Left 5th intercostal space, midaxillary line	Subxiphoid (infrasternal) angle	Right 4th intercostal space, parasternal line	C	This is Pericardiocentesis. The safest approach is the subxiphoid (infrasternal) route. The needle is inserted just below the xiphoid process and directed toward the left shoulder at a 30–45° angle.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
698	3	A 65-year-old patient with known COPD is given high-flow oxygen in the emergency department. Shortly after, the patient becomes drowsy and develops worsening respiratory acidosis. What is the most likely cause of this deterioration?	Pneumothorax	Oxygen-induced hypoventilation and CO2 retention	Pulmonary embolism	Acute myocardial infarction	B	This is Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) with chronic CO2 retention. In these patients, ventilation is partly driven by a hypoxic respiratory drive. High-flow oxygen causes a decreased hypoxic drive, leading to decreased respiratory rate (hypoventilation) and worsening V/Q mismatch.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
699	3	A 20-year-old tall, thin male suddenly develops sharp unilateral chest pain and shortness of breath while resting. On examination, there are reduced breath sounds on one side. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Pulmonary embolism	Asthma attack	Spontaneous pneumothorax	Pleural effusion	C	This is Primary spontaneous pneumothorax. The typical patient is a tall, thin young individual, and the condition is often due to the rupture of apical blebs.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
700	3	A 19-year-old male presents with intermittent mild jaundice, especially during stress or fasting. Liver function tests are otherwise normal, and there is no hemolysis. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Crigler-Najjar syndrome	Gilbert syndrome	Dubin-Johnson syndrome	Rotor syndrome	B	This is Gilbert syndrome. Key features include mild intermittent jaundice triggered by stress, fasting, or illness, with normal liver function tests and no hemolysis.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
701	3	An 70-year-old man presents with progressive jaundice, dark urine, pale stools, and generalized itching. Examination reveals a palpable gallbladder. What is the most likely cause of his condition?	Hepatitis A infection	Hemolytic anemia	Obstructive jaundice due to carcinoma head of pancreas	Gilbert syndrome	C	This is Obstructive jaundice. Key features in this elderly patient include progressive jaundice, dark urine (conjugated bilirubin in urine), pale stools (no bile reaching the gut), pruritus (bile salt deposition), and a palpable gallbladder (Courvoisier sign, which suggests a malignant cause such as carcinoma of the head of the pancreas).	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
702	3	A patient undergoes ileal resection for Crohn's disease. Which of the following is the most likely long-term complication?	Constipation	Steatorrhea	Increased iron absorption	Hypercalcemia	B	This is Ileal resection syndrome. The terminal ileum normally absorbs bile acids and Vitamin B12. After resection, decreased bile acid absorption leads to bile acid deficiency in the enterohepatic circulation, leading to impaired fat emulsification and steatorrhea.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
703	3	A liver biopsy shows inflammation predominantly around the portal triads with lymphocytic infiltrates and interface activity. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Cirrhosis	Viral hepatitis	Active hepatitis	Fatty liver disease	C	This is Chronic active hepatitis. Key histological features include portal triad inflammation (lymphocytes in portal areas) and interface hepatitis (extension into periportal hepatocytes). 'Active hepatitis' indicates ongoing hepatocellular injury and inflammation.	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
704	3	At which level does the common carotid artery typically bifurcate into the internal and external carotid arteries?	C1 vertebra	C2 vertebra	C3-C4 intervertebral disc	C5 vertebra	C	The common carotid artery normally bifurcates into the internal carotid artery (which supplies the brain) and the external carotid artery (which supplies the face/scalp) at the level of the upper border of the thyroid cartilage (corresponding to the C3-C4 level).	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
895	3	A patient presents with dysphagia. Endoscopy reveals a mass with an intact mucosa. Small intestinal tumor with non metastatic nature What is the most likely diagnosis?	GIST (Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumor)	Leiomyoma	Leiomyosarcoma	Adenocarcinoma	A		115	2026-07-14 23:55:57.574075	\N
705	3	A child falls on an outstretched hand and sustains a supracondylar fracture of the humerus. He is now unable to extend his wrist and shows "wrist drop". Which nerve is most likely injured?	Median nerve	Radial nerve	Ulnar nerve	Axillary nerve	B	A supracondylar fracture of the humerus can injure the radial nerve, leading to "wrist drop" (the inability to extend the wrist and fingers).	93	2026-07-13 03:03:19.485597	\N
706	3	A 24-year-old woman at 20 weeks of pregnancy presents with excessive nausea, vaginal bleeding, and uterine size larger than expected for gestational age. Ultrasound shows a "snowstorm" appearance with no viable fetus. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Ectopic pregnancy	Hydatidiform mole	Placenta previa	Missed abortion	B	This is Hydatidiform mole\nClassic features:\n• Vaginal bleeding in pregnancy\n• Severe nausea/vomiting due to very high hCG\n• Uterus larger than dates\n• Snowstorm pattern on ultrasound	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
707	3	A 5-year-old boy is brought to the clinic because of difficulty climbing stairs and frequent falls. On examination, he has calf pseudohypertrophy and uses his hands to rise from the floor (Gowers sign). What is the most likely diagnosis?	Becker muscular dystrophy	Duchenne muscular dystrophy	Myasthenia gravis	Spinal muscular atrophy	B	This is Duchenne muscular dystrophy\nClassic presentation in young boys:\n• Proximal muscle weakness\n• Difficulty climbing stairs\n• Frequent falls\n• Gowers sign\n• Calf pseudohypertrophy\nCause:\n• Mutation in dystrophin gene on X chromosome\nLab findings:\n• Markedly elevated CK levels	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
708	3	A 28-year-old man sustains a stab wound to the posterolateral aspect of the knee. He is now unable to plantarflex the foot and has weakness of toe flexion. Which nerve is most likely injured?	Common peroneal nerve	Sural nerve	Tibial nerve	Femoral nerve	C	This is Tibial nerve\n• In the popliteal fossa/posterior knee, the tibial nerve runs centrally and supplies: o Gastrocnemius, Soleus, Tibialis posterior, Toe flexors\nInjury causes:\n• Loss of plantarflexion ("can't flex foot downward")\n• Weak toe flexion\n• Sensory loss over sole of foot\nWhy posterolateral knee matters:\n• Structures in popliteal region are vulnerable in penetrating trauma\n• Sural nerve is mainly sensory only\n• Common peroneal injury causes foot drop (loss of dorsiflexion), not plantarflexion	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
709	3	A 26-year-old patient with asthma is using inhaled beclomethasone 250 µg regularly but remains symptomatic despite using salbutamol as needed. What is the most appropriate next step in management?	Start oral prednisolone long term	Increase beclomethasone to 2000 µg only	Add formoterol to inhaled corticosteroid therapy	Stop beclomethasone and use salbutamol only	C	This is Asthma\n• Patient is uncontrolled on low/moderate-dose inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) + rescue salbutamol\nStandard step-up therapy:\n• Add LABA (long-acting beta2-agonist) such as Formoterol\n• Continue ICS	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
710	3	A 55-year-old woman presents with sudden, severe, electric shock-like pain over the right side of her face triggered by chewing and touching the cheek. Episodes last a few seconds. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Migraine	Temporal arteritis	Trigeminal neuralgia	Bell palsy	C	This is Trigeminal neuralgia\nClassic features:\n• Sudden stabbing/electric shock facial pain\n• Usually unilateral\n• Triggered by touching face, chewing, brushing teeth, talking\n• Episodes last seconds to minutes	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
711	3	Which of the following is a leukotriene receptor antagonist used in asthma management?	Salbutamol	Montelukast	Theophylline	Budesonide	B	Montelukast blocks leukotriene receptors -> reduces effects of leukotrienes\nEffects in asthma:\n• ↓ bronchoconstriction\n• ↓ airway inflammation\n• ↓ mucus secretion	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
712	3	The anti-inflammatory action of corticosteroids in asthma is mainly due to inhibition of which pathway?	Leukotriene C4, D4, and B4 receptors	Histamine H1 receptors	Phospholipase A2 via lipocortin (annexin-1) induction	Cyclooxygenase-1 enzyme	C	This is Corticosteroids\nMain mechanism:\n• Steroids induce lipocortin (annexin-1)\n• Lipocortin inhibits phospholipase A2\nResult:\n• ↓ arachidonic acid production\n• ↓ synthesis of:\n  • Leukotrienes (C4, D4, B4)\n  • Prostaglandins	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
713	3	A patient presents with multiple endocrine abnormalities including amenorrhea, galactorrhea, and signs of hormone imbalance. Imaging reveals a sellar mass. Where is the most likely site of the lesion?	Hypothalamus	Pituitary gland	Thalamus	Pineal gland	B	This is Pituitary adenoma\nPituitary tumors can cause multiple endocrine problems because the pituitary regulates many hormones:\n• Prolactin -> galactorrhea	95	2026-07-13 03:04:31.841135	\N
714	2	A 72-year-old patient presents with slowly progressive memory loss, difficulty recalling recent events, and getting lost in familiar places. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Alzheimer disease	Frontotemporal dementia	Lewy body dementia	Vascular dementia	A	This is Alzheimer disease\nKey feature:\n• Gradual, progressive memory loss (especially recent memory first)\nTypical presentation:\n• Forgetfulness of recent events\n• Disorientation in familiar places\n• Slow decline in cognition	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
715	2	A 68-year-old man presents with resting tremor, bradykinesia, rigidity, and a stooped posture while walking. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Alzheimer disease	Huntington disease	Parkinson disease	Multiple sclerosis	C	This is Parkinson disease\nClassic features (TRAP):\n• Tremor (resting)\n• Rigidity\n• Akinesia/bradykinesia\n• Postural instability	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
716	2	A surgeon is performing a long operation for 15 hours after having fasted for about 30 hours. After this prolonged fasting, what is the primary source of energy for the body?	Glycogenolysis	Gluconeogenesis	Amino acid oxidation only	Ketone body utilization only	B	After ~24-30 hours of fasting:\n• Liver glycogen stores are largely depleted\n• So the body shifts metabolism:\n• Early fasting → glycogenolysis\n• Prolonged fasting → gluconeogenesis becomes main glucose source	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
717	2	A 30-year-old pregnant woman (3rd trimester) presents with burning pain, tingling, and numbness over the lateral aspect of the thigh. Symptoms worsen with standing and walking. Which nerve is most likely affected?	Femoral nerve	Obturator nerve	Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve	Sciatic nerve	C	This is Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve\n• Condition: Meralgia paresthetica\n• In pregnancy:\n• Enlarged uterus + increased weight → compression of nerve\n• Nerve function:\n• Pure sensory suppl. to anterolateral thigh	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
718	2	Reynolds number is used to determine which of the following in fluid dynamics?	Pressure of blood flow	Type of blood vessel wall thickness	Whether blood flow is laminar or turbulent	Oxygen content of blood	C	This is Reynolds number\n• Reynolds number predicts the type of flow in a vessel:\n• Laminar flow (smooth, parallel layers)\n• Turbulent flow (chaotic, disordered flow)	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
820	3	After 6 months of renal transplant, patient presents with sign of renal failure. His symptoms are resolved by giving immunosuppressive therapy. What is the likely cause?	Chronic cellular rejection	Acute cellular rejection	Acute humoral	Acute cell mediated	B	Acute cellular rejection resolves with treatment.	110	2026-07-14 23:53:31.077992	\N
719	2	A patient's cardiac output remains stable despite changes in circulation. Which mechanism is responsible for maintaining this stability?	Decreased heart rate only	Increased stroke volume and increased blood volume	Decreased blood viscosity	Decreased peripheral resistance only	B	This is Cardiac output regulation\nCardiac output = Heart rate × Stroke volume\n• The body maintains cardiac output via compensatory mechanisms:\n  • Increased blood volume → increases venous return\n  • ↑ venous return → ↑ preload → ↑ stroke volume (Frank-Starling mechanism)	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
720	2	A 45-year-old patient has hypercalcemia and hypophosphatemia due to excess parathyroid hormone (PTH). Which nephron segment is primarily affected by PTH via the cAMP second messenger system?	Proximal convoluted tubule (PCT)	Thick ascending limb of loop of Henle	Distal convoluted tubule (DCT)	Collecting duct	C	This is Parathyroid hormone\n• PTH acts mainly on kidney via Gs protein → ↑ cAMP pathway\n• Primary site of action:\n  • Distal convoluted tubule (DCT)	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
721	2	A 28-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after being found unconscious in a closed garage with a running car. He has headache, dizziness, and cherry-red skin discoloration. Pulse oximetry shows normal oxygen saturation despite symptoms. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Methanol poisoning	Carbon monoxide poisoning	Cyanide poisoning	Hypothermia	B	This is Carbon monoxide poisoning\n• Classic scenario:\n  • Closed space exposure (car exhaust)\n  • Headache, dizziness, loss of consciousness\n• Mechanism:\n  • CO binds hemoglobin with ~200-250× higher affinity than oxygen\n  • Forms carboxyhemoglobin → reduces oxygen delivery to tissues	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
722	2	A 22-year-old man accidentally pricks his finger with a needle. He immediately feels a sharp, well-localized pain that lasts for a few seconds before dull aching pain begins. Which nerve fibers are responsible for this initial sensation?	C fibers	A-beta fibers	A-delta fibers	A-alpha fibers	C	This is Pain transmission\n• The initial fast, sharp, well-localized pain is mediated by A-delta fibers	97	2026-07-13 03:05:49.463402	\N
723	2	... numbness. Lab reports show hypokalemia and metabolic alkalosis. Plasma renin activity is low. CT scan shows a unilateral adrenal mass. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Pheochromocytoma	Conn syndrome	Cushing syndrome	Addison disease	B	This is Conn syndrome\nSite: adrenal cortex (NOT medulla)\nHormone excess: aldosterone\nKey findings:\n- ↑ aldosterone\n- ↑ Na+ retention → hypertension\n- ↓ K+ loss → hypokalemia\n- ↑ H+ loss → metabolic alkalosis	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
724	2	A 25-year-old patient has multiple primary cancers at a young age, including osteosarcoma and breast cancer in the family history. Genetic testing reveals a mutation in a tumor suppressor gene. Which gene is most likely affected?	APC gene	BRCA1 gene	p53 gene	RB gene	C	This is Li-Fraumeni syndrome\nGene involved: TP53 (tumor suppressor gene p53)\nFunction of p53:\n- "Guardian of the genome"\n- Stops cell cycle if DNA damage occurs\n- Promotes DNA repair or apoptosis	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
725	2	A 40-year-old woman presents with fatigue, weight loss, hypotension, hyperpigmentation, and salt craving. Laboratory tests show hyponatremia and hyperkalemia. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Cushing syndrome	Addison disease	Conn syndrome	SIADH	B	This is Addison disease\nCause: autoimmune destruction of adrenal cortex → ↓ cortisol + ↓ aldosterone\nKey features:\n- ↓ cortisol → fatigue, weight loss, weakness\n- ↓ aldosterone → hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, hypotension	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
726	2	A 55-year-old patient presents with fatigue and macrocytic anemia. Endoscopy shows chronic atrophic gastritis affecting the stomach body and fundus. Which of the following is the primary function of parietal cells?	Secretion of pepsinogen	Secretion of gastrin	Secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl) and intrinsic factor	Secretion of mucus	C	This is Parietal cell\nParietal cells (oxyntic cells) are located in the stomach body and fundus\nFunctions:\n- Hydrochloric acid (HCl) → digestion, activates pepsin\n- Intrinsic factor → essential for vitamin B12 absorption in terminal ileum	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
728	2	A 60-year-old patient is taking warfarin for atrial fibrillation. After drinking cranberry juice regularly, his INR becomes elevated and he develops easy bruising. What is the most appropriate advice?	Continue cranberry juice with increased warfarin dose	Stop cranberry juice and monitor INR	Stop warfarin immediately	Start vitamin C supplementation	B	This is Warfarin\nCranberry juice can increase INR by:\n- Inhibiting warfarin metabolism (CYP interaction)\n- Enhancing anticoagulant effect → ↑ bleeding risk	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
729	2	A 30-year-old woman presents with a pituitary mass on MRI and bilateral galactorrhea (nipple discharge). Which hormone normally inhibits this symptom?	Prolactin	Levodopa	Oxytocin	Growth hormone	B	This is Dopamine\nProlactin secretion from the pituitary is under tonic inhibition by dopamine\nDopamine action:\n- ↓ prolactin release from anterior pituitary lactotrophs\n- If dopamine is reduced or blocked (or pituitary stalk compression occurs): ↑ prolactin → galactorrhea + amenorrhea	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
730	2	A 58-year-old man presents with sudden onset weakness of the right side of the body (face, arm, and leg) but has normal sensation. No cortical signs like aphasia or neglect are present. Where is the most likely site of the lesion?	Primary motor cortex	Internal capsule	Thalamus	Cerebellum	B	This is Internal capsule\nKey features:\n- Pure motor hemiparesis (face + arm + leg)\n- No sensory loss\n- No cortical signs (aphasia, neglect)	98	2026-07-13 03:07:03.559662	\N
