735	3	A 7-year-old boy presents with abdominal pain, palpable purpura over the legs and buttocks, and joint pain in the knees and ankles. Urinalysis shows hematuria and proteinuria. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)	Henoch-Schönlein purpura	Kawasaki disease	Hemophilia A	B	This is IgA vasculitis (Henoch-Schönlein purpura)\nClassic triad:\n• Palpable purpura (buttocks & lower limbs)\n• Arthralgia (knees, ankles)\n• Abdominal pain (GI vasculitis)\n• Renal involvement (hematuria, proteinuria)	99	2026-07-13 03:07:34.881424	\N
