737	3	A 65-year-old man presents to the emergency room with chest pain, hypotension (BP 70/30 mmHg), and bradycardia (pulse 40/min). ECG shows an acute myocardial infarction. Which coronary artery is most likely involved?	Left anterior descending (LAD) artery	Left circumflex artery	Right coronary artery (RCA)	Left main coronary artery	C	This is Acute myocardial infarction\nKey clues in the stem:\n• Hypotension + bradycardia -> suggests SA/AV node involvement	99	2026-07-13 03:07:34.881424	\N
738	3	In terms of ECG correlation, the systole phase of the cardiac cycle corresponds to which part of the ECG?	P wave	PR interval	QRS complex to end of T wave	ST segment	C	This is Cardiac cycle\nECG correlation:\n• Systole (ventricular contraction)\nStarts at QRS complex -> ventricular depolarization\nContinues through:\n• ST segment (ventricular ejection phase)\n• Ends at T wave (ventricular repolarization)	99	2026-07-13 03:07:34.881424	\N
739	3	A patient presents with irregular pulse and basal crepitations on chest examination. He is on antiarrhythmic therapy. Which drug is most likely responsible?	Amiodarone	Flecainide	Beta blocker	Digoxin	A	This is Amiodarone\nKey clue: basal crepitations -> suggest pulmonary toxicity\nWhy amiodarone?\n• Amiodarone is famous for multiple toxicities, especially:\n• Pulmonary fibrosis / pneumonitis -> basal crepitations, SOB\n• It is used for atrial fibrillation, which can present as irregularly irregular rhythm	99	2026-07-13 03:07:34.881424	\N
740	3	A patient develops fever, hypotension, flank pain, and hemoglobinuria shortly after receiving a mismatched blood transfusion. What type of hypersensitivity reaction is this?	Type I (IgE-mediated)	Type II (antibody-mediated cytotoxic reaction)	Type III (immune complex-mediated)	Type IV (delayed T-cell mediated)	B	This is Type II hypersensitivity\n• In acute hemolytic transfusion reaction:\n• Recipient antibodies (IgM/IgG) attack donor RBC antigens\n• Activates complement -> intravascular hemolysis	99	2026-07-13 03:07:34.881424	\N
