765	3	A 50-year-old man presents with loss of vibration sensation, proprioception from the lower limbs. He has a positive Romberg sign but normal pain and temperature sensation. Which pathway is most likely affected?	Spinothalamic tract	Corticospinal tract	Dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway	Spinocerebellar tract	C	This is Dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway. Functions of dorsal column: Vibration sense, Proprioception (joint position sense), Fine/discriminative touch.	102	2026-07-13 03:09:37.907521	\N
766	3	A 20-year-old patient presents with generalized tonic-clonic seizures ("fits"). Which is the most appropriate first-line long-term drug?	Diazepam	Phenytoin	Valproate	Levetiracetam	D	This is Levetiracetam. Levetiracetam is now widely used as first-line or preferred option for generalized tonic-clonic seizures because: Broad-spectrum efficacy, Minimal drug interactions, Safe long-term profile, No liver enzyme induction.	102	2026-07-13 03:09:37.907521	\N
822	3	A patient has frequently irregular pulse on examination. ECG shows no p wave and many abrupt R waves and QRS complex occurs irregularly what is the diagnosis	Ventricular fibrillation	WPW syndrome	Atrial fibrillation	Atrial flutter	C		110	2026-07-14 23:53:31.077992	\N
767	3	A 45-year-old man with a long history of generalized anxiety disorder has been taking diazepam 10 mg daily for 7 years. He is now scheduled for elective inguinal hernia repair under general anesthesia. During the pre-anesthetic assessment, he reports no recent change in his medication. He appears calm but has a slightly increased baseline heart rate. Question: What is the most appropriate adjustment in anesthetic management for this patient?	Increase the dose of anesthetic agents	Decrease the dose of anesthetic agents	Stop diazepam immediately before surgery	Give flumazenil preoperatively	A	Chronic daily benzodiazepine use (years) leads to pharmacodynamic tolerance -> downregulation of GABA-A receptors. General anesthetics (propofol, sevoflurane, barbiturates) also act via GABA potentiation. A tolerant patient requires higher doses of GABAergic anesthetics to achieve the same clinical effect (hypnosis, amnesia, immobility). Decreasing the dose (as the original answer key suggested) would risk awareness or inadequate anesthesia. Stopping diazepam immediately risks withdrawal seizures and severe anxiety pre-op. Flumazenil is contraindicated in chronic users (precipitates acute withdrawal). Switching to barbiturates does not solve tolerance and adds cross-tolerance.	102	2026-07-13 03:09:37.907521	\N
768	3	A 62-year-old man presents with sudden severe headache, vomiting, and loss of consciousness. CT scan shows intracerebral hemorrhage. His blood pressure is 160/100 mmHg and there are signs of increased intracranial pressure. What is the most appropriate immediate management step?	Increase blood pressure to maintain cerebral perfusion	Give mannitol	Start aspirin	Give thrombolysis (tPA)	B	This is Intracerebral hemorrhage. Key problem here: raised intracranial pressure (ICP). Why mannitol? Mannitol mechanism: Increases plasma osmolarity, Pulls fluid out of brain tissue -> reduces cerebral edema, Lowers ICP quickly.	102	2026-07-13 03:09:37.907521	\N
769	3	A patient develops induration and redness 48-72 hours after a tuberculin skin test (Mantoux test). Which type of hypersensitivity reaction is responsible?	Type I (IgE-mediated)	Type II (antibody-mediated cytotoxic)	Type III (immune complex-mediated)	Type IV (delayed T-cell mediated)	D	This is Type IV hypersensitivity. Seen in tuberculin (Mantoux) test reaction. Mechanism: Sensitized T cells (CD4+ Th1) recognize TB antigens -> Release cytokines (IFN-γ) -> macrophage activation -> Causes localized inflammation and induration.	102	2026-07-13 03:09:37.907521	\N
770	3	A patient with autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome (APS) is found to have multiple endocrine gland failures. Which of the following is most commonly associated with this condition?	Type 2 diabetes mellitus	Type 1 diabetes mellitus	Acromegaly	Cushing syndrome	B	This is Autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome (APS). APS (especially type 2) commonly includes: Type 1 diabetes mellitus, Autoimmune thyroid disease (Hashimoto or Graves), Addison disease (primary adrenal insufficiency).	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
771	3	A 14-year-old boy presents with recurrent gout-like arthritis and developmental delay. Lab tests show increased uric acid levels. A defect in which enzyme of purine synthesis is most likely responsible?	Xanthine oxidase	HGPRT	PRPP synthetase	Adenosine deaminase	C	This is Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate synthetase (PRPP synthetase). PRPP is a key substrate in purine synthesis pathway. Mechanism: ↑ PRPP synthetase activity → ↑ PRPP → ↑ purine synthesis → ↑ uric acid production. Leads to hyperuricemia and gout-like symptoms at a young age.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
772	3	A middle-aged man presents with chronic diarrhea, weight loss, and joint pain. Small bowel biopsy shows foamy macrophages that stain positive with PAS. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Crohn disease	Celiac disease	Whipple disease	Ulcerative colitis	C	This is Whipple disease. Key histology: PAS-positive macrophages in intestinal lamina propria. Organism: Tropheryma whipplei.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
773	3	A patient presents with high-grade fever accompanied by chills and rigors. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Dengue fever	Malaria	Typhoid fever	Viral hepatitis	B	This is Malaria. Key feature: paroxysmal fever with chills and rigors. Why malaria? Fever pattern: Cold stage (chills/rigors), Hot stage (high fever), Sweating stage. Why not dengue? Dengue typically causes: Continuous high fever, Severe myalgia ("breakbone fever"), Rash, bleeding tendency.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
774	3	A chronic alcoholic presents with hepatomegaly, jaundice, and elevated AST > ALT. Liver biopsy shows eosinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions called Mallory bodies. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Viral hepatitis	Alcoholic hepatitis	Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease	Hepatocellular carcinoma	B	This is Alcoholic hepatitis. Key histological feature: Mallory-Denk bodies (Mallory bodies) = damaged intermediate filaments in hepatocytes. Other classic findings: Hepatocyte ballooning, Neutrophilic infiltration, Fibrosis (can progress to cirrhosis).	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
775	3	A 20 year old patient experiences unusually prolonged action of a local anesthetic after administration. This is due to deficiency of which enzyme?	Monoamine oxidase	Pseudocholinesterase	Acetylcholinesterase	Cytochrome P450	B	This is Pseudocholinesterase. Normally, pseudocholinesterase breaks down: Ester local anesthetics (e.g., procaine, tetracaine), Succinylcholine.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
776	3	A 45-year-old man presents with fatigue, weight loss, and abdominal fullness. Examination reveals massive splenomegaly. Blood smear shows markedly elevated WBC count with all stages of myeloid maturation. Cytogenetic analysis reveals a Philadelphia chromosome. What is the most likely diagnosis?	Acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL)	Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL)	Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)	Acute myeloid leukemia (AML)	C	This is Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML). Key features: Massive splenomegaly, High WBC count, Presence of all stages of granulocyte maturation (left shift), Philadelphia chromosome t(9;22) -> BCR-ABL fusion.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
777	3	A patient develops urticaria, itching, and bronchospasm immediately after exposure to an allergen (e.g., peanuts or bee sting). Which type of hypersensitivity reaction is this?	Type I	Type II	Type III	Type IV	A	This is Type I hypersensitivity. Mechanism: First exposure -> IgE formation (sensitization), Re-exposure -> allergen binds IgE on mast cells -> degranulation.	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
778	3	In Parkinson disease, which neurotransmitter imbalance is primarily responsible for the clinical features?	Increased acetylcholine and increased dopamine	Decreased acetylcholine and increased dopamine	Decreased dopamine and relative increase in acetylcholine	Increased dopamine and decreased serotonin	C	This is Parkinson disease. Neurochemical imbalance: ↓ Dopamine (from substantia nigra pars compacta).	103	2026-07-13 03:10:07.396771	\N
