780	3	A newborn develops vomiting and abdominal distension shortly after first feeding. Failure to pass meconium is noted. Contrast study shows a narrowed distal colon. What is the diagnosis?	Intussusception	Hirschsprung disease	Pyloric stenosis	Meckel diverticulum	B	Congenital absence of ganglion cells in submucosal/myenteric plexus. Failure of relaxation causes functional obstruction. Delayed meconium passage is classic clue.	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
781	3	A 62-year-old woman presents with pressure-like chest pain for 30 minutes that improves with rest. ECG shows horizontal ST segment depression in leads V4-V6. Cardiac enzymes are still normal. What is the most likely interpretation of this ECG finding?	Transmural myocardial infarction	Pericarditis	Subendocardial Ischemia causing ST segment depression	Early repolarization (normal variant)	C	The ST segment reflects the phase when ventricles are fully depolarized. In partial-thickness (subendocardial) ischemia, injury does NOT involve the entire myocardial wall, leading to Subendocardial Ischemia causing ST segment depression.	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
782	3	A 42-year-old man presents with recurrent burning epigastric pain and chronic diarrhea despite prolonged treatment with proton pump inhibitors. Upper GI endoscopy shows multiple peptic ulcers extending into the distal duodenum and proximal jejunum. Laboratory testing reveals markedly elevated fasting serum gastrin levels. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	MEN 2	Zollinger-Ellison syndrome	Carcinoid syndrome	SIADH	B	Caused by a gastrin-secreting tumor (gastrinoma), usually in pancreas or duodenum. Excess gastrin causes massive gastric acid secretion. Leads to multiple recurrent peptic ulcers, often in unusual locations (distal duodenum/jejunum). Acid excess inactivates pancreatic enzymes -> chronic diarrhea.	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
783	3	A 45-year-old man with no past medical history presents with chest pain that started 2 hours ago. ECG shows ST segment elevation in leads I, aVL, V5, and V6. Cardiac enzymes are elevated. Which coronary artery is most likely occluded?	Right coronary artery	Left anterior descending artery	Left circumflex artery	Posterior descending artery	C	The ST segment elevation indicates acute transmural myocardial infarction. Myocardial Ischemia causing ST segment elevation	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
784	3	A 3-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with recurrent ear infections and episodes of bloody diarrhea. His mother reports persistent itchy skin rashes since infancy. Examination shows eczema over the flexural areas and scattered petechiae on the legs. Laboratory studies reveal thrombocytopenia with small platelets. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	SCID	Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome	Chronic granulomatous disease	CVID	B	Classic triad: eczema + recurrent infections + thrombocytopenia. X-linked recessive disorder caused by mutation in WAS gene. Defective cytoskeletal function in immune cells -> combined T-cell and B-cell dysfunction. Platelets are characteristically small and low in number.	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
785	3	A 58-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe central chest pain radiating to his left arm for 1 hour. ECG shows ST segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF. Troponin levels are elevated. Which of the following best explains the significance of the ST segment elevation?	Delayed ventricular repolarization due to atrial fibrillation	Early depolarization of the atria	Myocardial Ischemia causing ST segment elevation	Increased AV node conduction	C	The ST segment represents the period when the ventricles are fully depolarized and beginning repolarization. In acute transmural myocardial ischemia, the injured myocardium alters electrical currents, producing: Myocardial Ischemia causing ST segment elevation. Why ST elevation happens: Full thickness (transmural) injury -> current of injury. Causes upward displacement of ST segment on ECG.	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
786	3	A 62-year-old man with long-standing hypertension suddenly develops a severe headache followed by vomiting and loss of consciousness while at home. On arrival at the emergency department, his blood pressure is 210/120 mmHg. Neurological examination shows right-sided weakness and a decreased level of consciousness. CT brain shows an intracerebral bleed. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Ischemic Stroke	Hemicrania Stroke	Transient ischemic attack	Subdural hematoma	B	This is a classic case of intracerebral hemorrhage (hemorrhagic stroke): Hemorrhagic Stroke. Key features supporting hemorrhage: Sudden severe headache ("thunderclap-like but often with...	104	2026-07-13 03:10:41.477507	\N
787	3	A 67-year-old man presents with recurrent episodes of dizziness and transient right-sided weakness lasting a few minutes. On examination, a bruit is heard at the upper border of the thyroid cartilage. Imaging shows atherosclerotic narrowing at the point where the common carotid artery divides. Which of the following structures is located at the site of this bifurcation?	Carotid sinus and carotid body	Jugular vein and vagus nerve	Thyroid gland and trachea	Hypoglossal nerve only	A	The bifurcation of the common carotid artery occurs at the level of C4 (upper border of thyroid cartilage), where it divides into:\n• Internal carotid artery\n• External carotid artery\nAt this bifurcation are two important sensory structures:\n• Carotid sinus -> senses blood pressure\n• Carotid body -> senses blood gases	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
788	3	A 45-year-old man falls on his outstretched hand. After the injury, he has difficulty initiating shoulder abduction. On examination, he is unable to start lifting his arm away from the body for the first 15 degrees, but once assisted, he can continue abduction normally. There is also pain over the lateral shoulder. Which structure is most likely injured?	Deltoid	Supraspinatus	Infraspinatus	Teres minor	B	The first 0-15° of shoulder abduction is performed by the: Supraspinatus muscle.\nAfter that:\n• Deltoid takes over (15°-90°)	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
789	3	A 68-year-old man with a long history of smoking is brought to the emergency department because of confusion, lethargy, and nausea. His family reports reduced appetite and recent weight loss. On examination, he is euvolemic with no peripheral edema or signs of dehydration. Laboratory studies show serum sodium 118 mEq/L, low serum osmolality, and inappropriately concentrated urine with high urine sodium. Chest imaging reveals a hilar lung mass. Which of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his hyponatremia?	Diabetes insipidus	Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH)	Primary polydipsia	Adrenal insufficiency	B	• Severe hyponatremia causing confusion and lethargy\n• Euvolemic hyponatremia with low serum osmolality suggests SIADH\n• Urine remains concentrated despite low serum sodium because ADH is high\n• High urine sodium is common due to natriuresis\n• Strong association with Small Cell Lung Carcinoma producing ectopic ADH	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
