790	3	A 24-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a fall from a motorcycle. He reports severe shoulder pain and is unable to lift his right arm away from his body. On examination, there is loss of sensation over the "regimental badge" area of the lateral shoulder and weakness in shoulder abduction from 15° to 90°. X-ray shows an anterior shoulder dislocation. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?	Suprascapular nerve	Axillary nerve	Radial nerve	Musculocutaneous nerve	B	Anterior shoulder dislocation commonly injures the axillary nerve. Axillary nerve passes through the quadrangular space and is vulnerable in shoulder trauma. It supplies:\n• Deltoid muscle -> shoulder abduction (15°-90°)	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
791	3	A 62-year-old man with a known history of severe COPD presents to the emergency department with sudden onset sharp, right-sided chest pain and severe shortness of breath while at rest. On examination, he is tachycardic, hypotensive, and in obvious respiratory distress. Trachea is deviated to the left, and there are markedly reduced breath sounds on the right side with hyperresonance on percussion. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Pleural effusion	Tension pneumothorax	Pneumonia	Myocardial infarction	B	• COPD patients may develop ruptured emphysematous bullae leading to pneumothorax\n• When air enters pleural space and cannot escape -> tension pneumothorax\n• Key findings:\n  • Sudden pleuritic chest pain\n  • Absent breath sounds on affected side\n  • Tracheal deviation away from affected side	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
792	3	A 46-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after suddenly developing a severe "worst-ever" headache while watching TV. Within minutes, he developed neck stiffness and vomiting. On arrival, he is drowsy but intermittently responsive, and his neurological exam shows no focal deficits. The temperature is 37.2°C. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Bacterial Meningitis	Subarachnoid Hemorrhage	Viral meningitis	Brain tumor	B	This is a classic presentation of subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH):\n• Sudden thunderclap headache ("worst headache of life")\n• Neck stiffness (meningeal irritation from blood)\n• Vomiting\n• Fluctuating consciousness (common in SAH depending on bleed severity and ICP changes)\n• No fever initially\nCaused by rupture of aneurysm -> Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. Why not bacterial meningitis? Bacterial Meningitis typically shows:\n• Fever (usually high)	105	2026-07-13 03:11:08.013945	\N
793	3	A 67-year-old man presents with progressive shortness of breath on exertion and dry cough over the past several months. He worked in shipbuilding for 30 years, frequently handling insulation materials without respiratory protection. On examination, there are bilateral fine inspiratory crackles at the lung bases. Pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern with reduced total lung capacity. Chest imaging reveals interstitial fibrosis with pleural plaques. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Silicosis	Asbestosis	Coal worker's pneumoconiosis	Sarcoidosis	B	• Caused by inhalation of asbestos fibers (shipbuilding, construction, insulation work)\n• Leads to interstitial pulmonary fibrosis -> restrictive lung disease\n• Classic features:\n• Progressive dyspnea\n• Dry cough\n• Basal crackles\n• Restrictive pattern on PFTs	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
794	3	A 34-year-old woman is brought to the clinic after several episodes of dizziness, sweating, tremors, and confusion, especially in the early morning before breakfast. Her symptoms improve rapidly after drinking sugary drinks. During a supervised fast test, she develops hypoglycemia with inappropriately high insulin and C-peptide levels. Abdominal imaging reveals a small mass in the pancreas. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Glucagonoma	Insulinoma	Gastrinoma	VIPoma	B	• Insulinoma is a pancreatic beta-cell tumor that secretes excess insulin\n• Leads to fasting hypoglycemia (Whipple triad):\n• Symptoms of hypoglycemia (confusion, tremors, sweating)\n• Low blood glucose\n• Relief with glucose intake\n• Key lab findings:\n• ↑ C-peptide (rules out exogenous insulin use)	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
795	3	A 7-year-old boy is brought to the clinic with swelling around the eyes and reduced urine output. His mother reports that he had a sore throat about 2-3 weeks ago that resolved without antibiotics. On examination, there is periorbital edema and mild hypertension. Urinalysis shows red blood cell casts and proteinuria, and the urine appears dark brown ("cola-colored"). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?	Minimal change disease	Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (PSGN)	IgA nephropathy	Nephrotic syndrome	B	• Occurs 1-3 weeks after streptococcal pharyngitis or skin infection\n• Immune complex deposition in glomeruli -> inflammation\n• Classic features:\n• Cola-colored (hematuric) urine	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
796	3	A 29-year-old man presents with fatigue, right upper quadrant discomfort, and mild jaundice. He reports a history of unprotected sexual contact and intravenous drug use. Laboratory tests show elevated ALT and AST levels. Serology reveals positive hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) and hepatitis B core antibody (anti-HBc). The physician explains that the infecting organism belongs to a unique group of hepatotropic viruses with a partially double-stranded DNA genome and uses reverse transcriptase in its replication cycle. Which of the following is the causative virus?	Hepatitis A virus (HAV)	Hepatitis B virus (HBV)	Hepatitis C virus (HCV)	Hepatitis D virus (HDV)	B	• HBV is the only DNA virus among hepatitis viruses\n• It has a partially double-stranded DNA genome\n• Uses reverse transcriptase (RNA intermediate step in replication)\n• Transmitted via blood, sexual contact, and perinatal exposure	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
797	3	A 50-year-old man presents to the clinic with a 3-month history of worsening difficulty swallowing. He first noticed trouble swallowing solid foods, but over time the difficulty progressed to include liquids as well. He also reports unintended weight loss, fatigue, and reduced appetite. He has a long history of smoking and occasional alcohol use. On evaluation, there are no signs of heartburn relief with antacids. Which of the following is the most likely concerning diagnosis?	Achalasia	Esophageal carcinoma	Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)	Esophageal spasm	B	• Progressive dysphagia (solids -> liquids) strongly suggests a mechanical obstructive lesion\n• Associated weight loss and systemic symptoms are red flags for malignancy\n• Risk factors: smoking, alcohol, chronic irritation\n• Unlike achalasia, malignancy typically presents with significant weight loss and constitutional symptoms	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
798	3	A 45-year-old man with a long history of chronic alcohol use is brought to the emergency department by his family because of confusion, unsteady gait, and abnormal eye movements. On examination, he is disoriented to time and place, has horizontal nystagmus, and shows marked ataxia while trying to walk. His blood glucose is 68 mg/dL. The clinician prepares to correct his metabolic status but recognizes that giving glucose alone may worsen his neurological condition. What is the most appropriate immediate management step?	Administer intravenous glucose only	Start insulin infusion	Give intravenous thiamine before glucose	Administer folate only	C	• This presentation is classic for Wernicke encephalopathy\n• Triad:\n• Confusion\n• Ataxia\n• Ophthalmoplegia/nystagmus	106	2026-07-13 03:11:46.361619	\N
